reviewr_text: Affordable, huge portions. Similar to Applebee's in the states. Service was good. Food was decent. Nothing outstanding to really rave about, or complain about.

title: Taitong Steamer Foods
reviewr_text:
This place is obscure at its best. While walking in the rain, I came across this place hoping to have a hot cup of tea.
Upon looking at the menu, I started with bola-bola siopao. After realizing it tasted good and how I imagine chinese restaurant food should taste, I proceeded with the Hong Kong Noodles and that also tasted good. Prices seem high for a home in the wall place, but it tasted good. I haven't had good chinese food in a while except maybe for tsay cheng at the grand majestic convention center which is kinda upscale.

title: 168 Ramen
reviewr_text:
いろんなラーメンが揃う店

お隣の焼肉屋さんとの兄弟店のこちら168（一路発）ラーメン。
いろんな種類のラーメンが食べることができます。
僕がいただいたのは辛味噌ラーメン。

日本基準から考えるとありふれたラーメンかもしれませんが、セブでこの再現度のラーメンはめちゃくちゃ嬉しいです。

title: Ramen Yushoken
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Angela L."},{"reviewer_name":"Gio G."},{"reviewer_name":"Dani S."},{"reviewer_name":"Zerra Mae Lyka L."},{"reviewer_name":"Judy J."}]
reviewr_text:
If there's one place my dad would think of going to have a meal, it would be at Yushoken. I can't count the number of times he's talked about Yushoken. Finally got to try it on a vacation back home in Cebu.

I've had plenty of ramen and I can say that this is one of the better ones that I've had, even better than the ramen places in Los Angeles' Little Tokyo! 

The menu is simple and focuses on a tonkotsu broth. To taste the broth I opted for a shio tare. My parents ordered the shoyu, which I was also able to taste. The tonkotsu shined in my shio ramen, with the broth thick and rich enough to cling to the noodles. The chashu is also fatty, buttery and tender. The gyoza were very plump, and more meaty than most gyozas served within the city. Aji tamago was perfectly cooked as well. 

I'm very, very surprised at how everything was prepared close to perfection! After hearing about the ramen craze in the Philippines, I didn't expect the execution to be this good in Cebu after trying some of the hyped ramen places in Manila. At Yushoken, everything surpassed my expectations and more!

title: Watda Pho
reviewr_text:
Cute clean and new, no crowds yet,  quiet,  easy to get to.  with free Wi-Fi and many built in outlets to charge your phone. also a hand washing station with paper towels!   
First time here. Enjoyed the fresh spring rolls, the pho,  and a rice noodle salad.  All were fresh,  tasty,  and gluten free.
Staff super friendly and helpful. We will definitely return.

title: Cafe Laguna
reviewr_text: Loved this restaurant so much I wanted to eat there for lunch and dinner. I was actually looking to find Laguna Garden Cafe and fell into this one instead. Delicious & authentic Filipino food! I wish they had more chains in Manila! Thee service was quick and they were attentive. I got the bulalo soup which was  amazing and flavored really well. My sister got the lumpiang sariwa & vegetable spring roll which she engulfed in less than 5 minutes. I also had the melon cooler which was completely refreshing

title: Phat Pho
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Verne A."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael H."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Terri S."},{"reviewer_name":"Myles C."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text:
This is one of my favorite restaurants in Cebu City. Their soup and congee are great, especially during rain days. I love their meat skewers too. I'm a frequent coffee drinker, and their Vietnamese Drip Coffee is great for me!

Definitely a must try for locals and tourists alike. Plus, Crossroads Mall has plenty of parking, two arts and crafts stores: Craft Story and HOLICOW, and two dessert places: Abaca Baking Co. and La Marea. Amazing!

reviewr_text: This place gets the jon done. Its not super fancy but not dingy or terrible either. This place just opened compared to the escario location, so things are in descent shape. The price is very reasonable in my opinion. The staff is accommodating though not quick, but understandable since they deal with a high volume of people at times. I would definitely come to his place when the budget allows more than the fancy places since they are more expensive.

reviewr_text:

They have some yummy vegetarian dishes too like this nangka dish and the adobong Kang kong.  Also price wise it doesn't hurt you wallet.

title: Blackbeard's Seafood Island
reviewr_text:
One of my first meals back in the motherland and my brother decides to take me to an amazing seafood restaurant located within Ayala Mall in Cebu.  There is something to be said about how deliciously fresh seafood can be when you know the supply probably had just been caught this morning.  There's no long term refrigeration here people.  The crab, fish, and all matter of sea creatures that were prepared for the benefit of my hungry stomach could not be any fresher.  Actually the only way that it could be is for me to catch it down by the beach and then clean it and cook it myself.  But that's too much of a hassle so I'll settle for a restaurant that does all of it and I don't have to break a sweat.

Blackbeard's is a casual restaurant that is warm and inviting.  By warm I mean the welcome not the temperature.  Thankfully the restaurant is fully air-conditioned so I actually stopped sweating for some time.  It was a welcome respite from the stifling outside temperature.  The look and feel definitely screams island life, which was fitting considering it was my first time back to this island in more than a decade.

I trusted my sister-in-law to order what she thought was best.  The menu was extensive but she went with the Mt. Apo.  This particular order is meant to be shared by 5-7 people.  It has everything that you could imagine.  Crabs, shrimp, squid, chicken prepared two ways, vegetables, rice, and so much more.  This platter came out and I was instantly blown away.  The presentation, the aroma, and the quantity is beyond expectation.  They say a picture is worth a thousand words but in this case no words could adequately describe what was set before me and my fam.  My nephews and I dug right into it and I was instantly transported to food nirvana.  Delicious is an understatement.  I could have eaten everything on that huge platter myself if only my stomach didn't have a finite amount of stretching ability to it.  I knew that my sis-in-law had made the right choice and I couldn't have been any happier.

If you happen to be in Ayala Mall or nearby, don't hesitate to make your way to this place.  Trust me when I say this you will not be disappointed.

title: Neo Neo BBQ Grille
reviewr_text:
Delicious is the best thing that describes this place! They have the best tasting ngohiong, pancit, and bbq at a price that everyone can afford. 

The place is spacious with outside and inside seating. Well lit and well ventilated, the venue is best for both family and corporate get togethers.

title: Lighthouse Restaurant
reviewr_text: There are so many choices for Filipino food in Cebu.  My favorite after trying many, is Lighthouse.  Also specifically this location. The reason being a newer more spacious and island theme restaurant.  The food  has been great that I have returned a few times, the quality is consistent and the prices are very reasonable.  Dishes can be simple but with ingredients that would be hard to find in the states.  Tuna belly, tuna jaw, crispy kangkong, bicol express, and baked stuffed mussels, scallops and oysters.   Also a big plus is that it isn't crowded and they can easily accommodate large parties.

title: Ramen Yushoken
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Angela L."},{"reviewer_name":"Gio G."},{"reviewer_name":"Dani S."},{"reviewer_name":"Zerra Mae Lyka L."},{"reviewer_name":"Judy J."}]
reviewr_text:
The best ramen place in Cebu! 

The broth alone is incredibly tasty, and with the noodles and other toppings the ramen here is absolutely delicious. Definitely a must-try here in the city. 

I recommend their miso ramen or their tonkotsu dipping noodles. I've had both in the past. Both have incredibly complex flavors expertly blended into one perfect bowl of ramen. For sides, I suggest gyoza and the karaage. You simply cannot miss the gyoza, and Yushoken does the juiciest and most delicious karaage I've ever had. You can also choose to sit at the bar and watch the chefs cook your meal! 

The place gets a bit busy, so make sure you get there earlier, especially for dinner.

title: Tokyo Table
reviewr_text:
Every once in a while I like to take a break from the usual routine carenderia or eating home in order to stay on budget.  Today was the day I decided to take a break, and decided to go to Tokyo Table in Tipolo, Mandaue City, Cebu City. It's a bit far from Cebu City, but if your in the area and looking for clean, pleasant place to have a nice meal with professional service this is the place. The presentation gives an aura of quality and the ambiance is very pleasant. The cuisine is primarily Japanese and is buffet style but they also offer the ability to barbecue your food, as well as Chinese Dim Sum dishes and the ability to make you own Vietnamese soup noodle dish called Pho. I have also head that they do not use MSG in their cooking since I am not fond of its use and despite that the food is still delicious in IMHO.

During lunch hours, the dessert selection is limited to ice cream, halox2, and taho. But dinner time is when you get the full selection which includes creme brulee.

Its a welcome sight to have a place like this in this part of town. If you are in the area, and are in the mood for asian cuisine specializing in Japanese.. definitely add this place to the list.

reviewr_text: You can't visit the Philippines without enjoying a jollibee meal.  This is the McDonald's of the Philippines or maybe even better. Must have the chicken joy and spaghetti.  Also the pineapple juice is the best!

title: KAYU: Kitchen + Bar
reviewr_text:
I was in Cebu for vacation and looking for a nice place to take my friend for dinner. Stumbled upon this place and it piqued my interest when I saw that it was in an area developed by Rockwell, which I've stayed at in Manila. 

The restaurant is set back in a lunch garden across a small pool from a dessert spot. We were greeted and accommodated despite not having a reservation. The ambience of the restaurant was beautiful - modern yet cozy. The restrooms were clean and the servers very polite and attentive. 

The food was delicious. My friend ordered the salmon dish and I order a shrimp pasta. For dessert, the server recommended one of their specials - a tiramisu creatively  plated as a flower in a flower pot with a watering can filled with a delicious white sauce that is to be poured on top. 

The price fit the food and the general feeling and service of the place.

title: Café George
reviewr_text:
Good food but not so good service. The staff was so noisy talking amongst themselves it was hard to have a serious conversation with my wife. There were only two tables occupied. Waited quite awhile for the change that I had to stand up and get it myself, and when I asked, the cashier said "aw ganina ra diay na siya?"  Probably didn't notice that a customer was waiting because they were too busy chatting and making chika. 

The food is yummy but just have a lot of patience in dealing with the staff.

title: Cebu's Original Lechon Belly
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jefferson S."},{"reviewer_name":"Abbys A."},{"reviewer_name":"Gio G."},{"reviewer_name":"Gil M."},{"reviewer_name":"Anneke D."},{"reviewer_name":"Barry T."},{"reviewer_name":"Maputing E."},{"reviewer_name":"Mike M."},{"reviewer_name":"Swan L."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."}]
reviewr_text:
Let's just talk about the food, never mind the location or the ambiance.  This is your typical street food that what matters the most is the cleanliness, flavor and tastiness of the lechon (roasted pig).  Their pork belly is one of a kind.  Tender, juicy, crispy and absolutely full of flavor.  The hanging rice was also something I've missed.  There's a hint of banana leaf (clean flavor) and scent in the rice.  It's not as compact as I remembered though, this one sort of falls off which was a bit of a disappointment. 

They provide benches and tables for those who wants to eat there.  But it's outdoor.  They also provide plastic gloves for those who want to use their hands to eat. It's kind of fun because that's something new to me.  In the old days, you just eat with your hands and just wash before and after.  They still provide hand washing center though so no worries.  

Overall, a fun eat.  And a must when you're in town.

title: Meximama
reviewr_text:
Mexican food (Tex-Mex, but the closest thing here) is hard to come by in the Philippines, especially in Cebu. Thank God for Meximama. It never disappoints. 
There are three locations, the first one we would eat at was at Marina Mall on Mactan. But that is far from the city. So we were thrilled when it opened in Mabolo near Sykes!
My favorites are the chimichanga and elotes, but everything is good. Great service. The best!

title: Brique
reviewr_text: Located in Ayala Mall, 4th floor balcony Aaron's, Brique offers a wide variety of foods. We opted for the string fries, calamari, wings, carbonara pasta, house salad, and salmon with mashed potatoes. We could have gone without the pasta and been happy. But overall it was good. Service was kind of slow but it doesn't mean the food wasn't good. Calamari is a must try! The sauce that goes with it is absolutely delicious! This place is great for meet ups as portions are generous.

title: Charcoal Boy
reviewr_text: Glad I was able to stop by and try this place during my vacation.  Super delish, fast service and cheap for what you get.  Definitely try the oyster in Cheese and garlic sauce.

title: Tim Ho Wan
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Marissa S."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Cynthia Q."},{"reviewer_name":"Tracy N."},{"reviewer_name":"Ray J."}]
reviewr_text:
Tim Ho Wan (THW) is located in different malls in the Philippines.  This particular location was in a mall in Cebu.  THW is based out of Hong Kong and is a Michelin rated restaurant.  Anyhow my buddy had eaten at THW and recommended it for lunch.

Tim Ho Wan specializes in dim sum.  We ordered
* Baked BBQ Pork Buns (3 Pieces) / 酥皮焗叉 (top selling item)
* Steamed Dumplings w/Shrimp and Chives / 鮮蝦韮菜餃 (Awesome)
* Steamed Bean Curd W/Meat & Vegetable
美味炆鮮竹卷 (these were truly F-in amazing)
* Steamed Pork Dumplings W/Shrimp (Siu Mai) 鮮蝦燒賣皇 (Very good)
* Congee W/Pork & Preserved Egg 金銀蛋瘦肉粥

title: CnT Lechon
reviewr_text: Disgusting.  They gave us a pile of scraps and fat after tossing it in the microwave.  Chewy, bland, skin like a limp noodle.  We gave it back.

title: Tymad Bistro
reviewr_text:
Its a french cusine place. I haven't tried their meals, but i have tried the baked goods such as rasberry French macaroon, croissant, apple tatin. I'm a fan of the apple tatin.

title: Handuraw
reviewr_text:
I never thought this would happen but I finally got sick of rice. After almost two and a half weeks in the Philippines and exclusively eating Filipino fare -- I was DYING for a slice of pizza. I was so desperate I was going to suggest going to the Sbarro's or Pizza Hut at the Ayala but luckily my cousin (and Yelp) suggested we check out Handuraw, a local Cebuano favorite.

Thin crust pizza is the game here and when our Handuraw House Special came out I was shocked to see that the pizza looked like it was made on a flimsy ass tortilla. I grabbed a slice, braced myself for the worst and took a bite -- it as surprisingly good! The crust was crunchy and held up to all of the toppings quite nicely. We downed two pizzas with the quickness as well as an order for the chili wings. 

They have a good beer selection and sell gin and juice by the pitcher which is pretty gangsta of them.

As we were finishing up, a local band started playing CCR hits and guess what --- they were amazing. The restaurant is very lively and fun and I'd definitely come back for a thoroughly modern Filipino experience.

title: Larsian BBQ
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Julia C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christopher C."},{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Matthew S."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"JessicaAllyn C."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Carlo L."},{"reviewer_name":"Fedd F."},{"reviewer_name":"Jeelyn D."},{"reviewer_name":"Janine D."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."},{"reviewer_name":"Emma D."}]
reviewr_text:
Larsian is all about BBQ. This is coming from someone who's lived and vacationed there, trust me. Do not pass up going to this place when you're in Cebu or if you're planning to go there, this is something that needs to be part of your list. It's not a fancy tourist spot but if you want the full experience and really mix with the locals then you should definitely pay them a visit. Like I said, it's nothing fancy so your wallet shouldn't worry, it comes pretty cheap. I suggest you go here with friends and family because the experience is more fun when you're with a group. 

When we go to Larsian, it's usually out of the blue like we'd wonder where we're gonna eat and someone would suggest Larsian and magically we'd all agree. And it's fun at anytime of the day but since it's an open area / al fresco then night time is the ideal choice!

Where do you go to when you're in Cebu?

title: Ipar's Restaurante Y Bar De Tapas
Górliz
reviewr_text: Amazing food so far. The ambience here is very warm and welcoming. Met some friends here in Cebu and I've ordered the lychee martini which I love! We've ordered a few different food options so I'm looking forward to trying it!

title: Cherry's The Spice
reviewr_text: You know the place is authentic when many/most customers are Indians, also the cook is Indian as well. Expect to wait a long time since they cook their food as you order (that would be good since you know that your food is cooked fresh) but for me it was worth it. When I first came here some time ago, my first impression was that their service was quite slow, but in the end it was worth the wait since their food is pretty good and tasty. Authentic Indian cuisine indeed and you get to choose whether you want it spicy, medium, or mild. As for me, I always opt for spicy since I can handle the heat. I got the naan bread which was good paired with their chicken tikka masala. The chicken tikka masala was delicious especially if you mix it with their biryanis. I usually go for their vegetable biryani since I already ordered a meat dish (chicken tikka masala) and you also get to choose whether you want it spicy, medium, or mild as well. I don't usually order drinks since they give you a pitcher of ice cold water for free, and it's refillable too. Overall it's a good place to eat if you're into and looking for authentic Indian cuisine. The only downside of this place is that you need to wait long for your order to arrive but the food is definitely worth it. I've been here a few times already and the food doesn't disappoint.

title: Zubuchon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Jacques I."},{"reviewer_name":"Tellie N."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Ron Z."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Lillian C."},{"reviewer_name":"Linda P."},{"reviewer_name":"Benjamin C."},{"reviewer_name":"Cris T."},{"reviewer_name":"David L."},{"reviewer_name":"Kathrine P."},{"reviewer_name":"John A."},{"reviewer_name":"Barry T."},{"reviewer_name":"Aileen B."},{"reviewer_name":"Angeli Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Ian Maren C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Geoffrey U."}]
reviewr_text:
Located in a strip mall, this is one of many locations (there's even one at the airport!) After Anthony Bourdain claimed that Zubuchon had the best lechon in all of Philippines, I knew I had to try. We walked in around 11am and saw that they just received their delivery of the whole pig (we were also told they receive it twice a day). Knowing that this pork will be as fresh as it comes, we placed an order for zubuchon lechon. The orders go by weight of how much lechon you want and because we just had breakfast, we ordered the smallest order.

The order also comes with a side of rice, a small side of a ginger salad mix, vinegar and soy sauce, which is a perfect combo for a lunch size portion. Now, onto the meat. Let me preface this by saying that I'm not the biggest pork consumption eater but this had to be the most succulent pork I've ever had with the crispiest crackling skin. Color me impressed. My friend, who's a local said that lechon is usually eaten with a special dark sauce similar to hoisin so we requested that on the side and it complimented the pork well, cutting through the saltiness.

The interior was clean and there are plenty of tables to situate yourself in. I'm glad I was able to try Zubuchon's claim to fame and implore you to try it out as well!

title: Isla Sugbo Seafood City
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"David P."},{"reviewer_name":"Gregory C."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Danie S."},{"reviewer_name":"Erica V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Jennelle L."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Jo Anne G."},{"reviewer_name":"Laura A."},{"reviewer_name":"Rocky Betty Jo P."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco F."}]
reviewr_text:
This one is a tough one for me. I really wanted to love this place but some how it fell a little short for me. Here it is:
The good:
- the service was attentive and generous
- the decor is on point. Its a great location for a celebration
- the location is very easy to find and access
- the concept of an open market preparing fresh seafood is amazing

The bad
- for me ( and only for me) the flavors were off. Every preparation  came our sweet. The garlic wasnt garlicy at all, the spicy chili was sweet and sour sauce, the plain steam was bleh. 
- im going to say that the seafood quality was questionable. Other than the large crab that i purchased at a high additional cost every thing else was definitely  not fresh. The meat was hard to get out of the shell and it was severly overcooked...almost like it had been precooked. I selected shrimp which were alive but what arrived at my table was long dead.

Im am very glad that i visited but honestly id be in no rush to visit again.

title: Hukad sa Golden Cowrie
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jonny M."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert N."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael H."},{"reviewer_name":"Totong B."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jenny C."},{"reviewer_name":"Swan L."},{"reviewer_name":"Emma D."},{"reviewer_name":"Keisha R."},{"reviewer_name":"Liza M."},{"reviewer_name":"Thomas L."},{"reviewer_name":"Nataraki T."}]
reviewr_text:
I met up with a friend who coincidentally was in Cebu City the same night. Talk about good timing. We decided to meet up at The Terraces (inside Ayala Center) which has an endless option of food, coffee and bubble tea spots. Hukad looked good for Filipino food so we gave them a try.

We dropped in on a Wednesday evening (around 9:00pm) and it was busy. Lots of tables, inside and outside, to choose from and friendly service. 
 
The menu is split into appetizers, soup, seafood platters, meat, rice, veggies, sweets and drinks.

- 2x Garlic rice (48 PHP) - this took awhile to come out so they scooped us some steamed rice (on the house) to go with the other dishes that had arrived. It was worth the wait. Really tasty, prominent garlic flavour.
- Cowrie pinakbet (119 PHP) - apparently, we got the very last order. Good flavours; I got a hint of shrimp/seafood paste and spiciness. Vegetables were a welcome sight to see.
- Tuna belly (235 PHP) - they were out of squid so we settled on a piece of tuna. Nicely grilled, tender and a good portion size.

This was surprisingly good for mall eats!

title: Providore
reviewr_text:
I ate so much on our trip to the Philippines!!  One morning we ate breakfast at Providore inside Summit Galleria Hotel.  Their breakfast buffet was included with our 1 night stay.  It is 495 Philippine Pesos per adult, and about half the price per child.

They have a nice variety of choices for breakfast.  Of course there are plenty of Filipino food such as Cebu Longanisa, dried fish, suman, and pan de sal.  There are also western choices such as little pancakes and waffles.  

I think their signature item is the Ube Champorado.  If you are a Filipino, then you must try it cause it is super yummy!!!!  If you are a foreigner, then I highly suggest trying it too.  I had never seen ube flavored champorado before that morning.  I am used to the traditional chocolate flavored champorado.  What is Champorado?  Traditionally, it is a chocolate flavored rice porridge.  I love eating it with dried salted fish cause it the perfect combination of sweetness and saltiness!  

My favorite item from their buffet was their Ensaymada.  I ate so many of their mini ensaymadas!  They were soft, round, sugary, and topped with cheese.  I loved their version of this traditional Filipino pastry/bread.

We enjoyed the buffet at Providore.  Service was top notch.  The restaurant was very clean.  I recommend them.

reviewr_text:
Gimmie sum dim sum! The famed Tim Ho Wan has finally arrived in cebu. Today is the first day it opens so there was definitely a line.
For those of you not familiar with their reputation, their base restaurant in Hong Kong has earned a michelin star.
There are many locations in manila, but this is the first one on cenu. Their signature dishes are the baked pork buns amd vermicilli dishes. I personally gonwith thr baked pork buns and the standard dim sim dishes of siomai (pork dumpling) and hakaw(shrimp dumpling)
As a dim sum foodie, my expectations were high so, for me the food was good but it didnt wow me

title: Treat Street Cafe
reviewr_text:
Treat Street Cafe is owned by the great Trina Ang! Who is also known for baking excellent wedding cakes!

I was thrilled to know she is opening a cafe as it would mean easy access to her cakes lol i love the texture of the pastries she makes and one of my favorites is their classic chocolate cake. It is not too sweet, icing is made smooth and delicate and texture is just right. The green tea and sesame cake had a chiffon-cake texture but surprisingly it blended pretty well with the icing/mousse that it was such a joy to eat.

I can't say much for the coffee as i havent tried it but i bet they are pretty good as well. I expected nothing but the best from Trina. Treat Street is definitely worth trying!

Update: i've finally tried their coffee after 2 years! Lol coffee was solid with a nice frothy cream. Very good in my opinion.

title: Big Tom's Charbroiled Burgers
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Dexter S."},{"reviewer_name":"William E."},{"reviewer_name":"Dean S."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert C."},{"reviewer_name":"Craig F."},{"reviewer_name":"Danny G."},{"reviewer_name":"Leah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Mike M."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheika G."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris M."}]
reviewr_text: I was recommended to come here so my expectations were high. I even told the Owner Tom I was a Big Critic from Los Angeles. We ordered burgers well done and they came medium with red in the middle. For some reason Filipino burgers can not stay together.  They just aren't firm enough like L.A. Burgers. The meat seems to always fall apart. The bread was great. If you ask for a regular burger plate it will not come with lettuce or tomato which is completely standard. The Fries portion is a tease and it left me wanting McDonald huge fries. In short I was very disappointed and know now that perfect burgers in the Phillipines just do not exist. The place is very neat and nicely decorated but I will definitely stick to Fried Chicken in the Phillipines....

reviewr_text:
Coming from almost a two hour traffic, I was kind of hesitant to go to a place that makes you choose LIVE food that still needs to be cooked but it was my mom's birthday and we did want her to feel special and you can always count on fresh shrimps to make her feel just that. 

Despite my all wanting to just sit down & eat, this place is actually worth the little wait or even more. The shrimps were exquisitely cooked in butter & garlic. You can taste it's sweetness in all it's freshness & simplicity. The service was also right on the money but yes it's a little bit pricey especially for a place like Cebu where the cost of living is really low but hell you can always find time to splurge just a little bit especially if it's your mom's birthday!

reviewr_text: Driveway Larangan is one of the neighbor friendly dishes with bisaya lutong pambahay. All love for this karenderya. They even offer crabs  for very low prices! Its new in town so better try it out! Just along the highway so you can never miss them out!

title: La Maison Rose
reviewr_text:
This is one of the nicest restaurants in Cebu. Very good good, nice setting and a bit out of town so you don't choke on Cebu pollution.

Our Belgian foodie friend said this is not great French food, but for a pedestrian eater it was excellent. True to french style, the waiters were a bit snooty but we enjoyed the meal and would return.

title: Meximama
reviewr_text: This is the worst of the worst in the world!I can't believe that it was the best of Cebu in 2015.What?Was There just one restaurant in 2015?I hope no one experience the same shit like me.HORRIBLE!

title: Café George
reviewr_text: Wow!! I love this place ! From the salads to the main entrees, all are very tasty and delicious! The price is very reasonable too. Asian fusion at its best. Serving size is perfect for me but it might not be enough for the young ones with big appetites. I love the california salad, grilled pork chop with herb butter. Parrot fish with chipotle butter. For dessert, i had pecan pie and lemon cheesecake which were both very delicious. I will be back to try everything else.

reviewr_text: Really great Mexican food, better than I get in Tucson. All of it is good - enchiladas, tacos, fajitas, empanadas, etc.. Great ambiance, haha, nice dia de muertos skull masks. Just a cool place. Looks like they have a great selection of tequilas also but I don't drink so can't comment. But the staff is excellent and service great.

title: Tymad Bistro
reviewr_text: If you really want the best croissants then Tymad Bistro is where you will get it.  Not only do they have delicious pastries but their food is also yummy.  Their crepes are the bomb along with their pasta and salads.  Plus the owner is the nicest guy ever.  He always makes you feel at home.  Great place for good food whether it's dinner or dessert or both! :)

title: Anzani
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Bobby L."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Katherine O."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Scott G."},{"reviewer_name":"Cathy M."},{"reviewer_name":"Kartik K."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael W."}]
reviewr_text: Beautiful interior. It looked like a mixture of modern italian and nature (from the outside). Service was great, they served us a choice of gluten free bread for starters with 3 different choices of dips. Their food had nice presentation and was delicious! The arugula salad is to-die-for. The spicy penne pasta was cooked al dente. The beef was very tender. Definitely coming back again.

title: Port Restaurant
reviewr_text:
A restaurant that was recommended by our tour guides. It's a filIpino / asian buffet restaurant below the Pagcor building. The place was clean and friendly. There is plenty of seats and for large groups. The prices are decent for what they offer. 

They had plenty to offer from lechon kawali, sushi, pasta, clams, adobo rice, veggies, kare kare, fresh lumpia, etc. Half of the food was decent as well as the dessert. 

It was good enough because I was starving but I wouldn't be a regular here. There was nothing wowing me to return. [21/100]

title: House of Lechon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]
reviewr_text:
Was in cebu over the weekend and we knew that lechon is a must try when in Cebu.  We were seated in the outside seating area because the inside was packed.  But that was ok though because there was a roof and ceiling fans so it kept it nice and cool.  Our waiter was attentive and nice, i believe he was the manager on shift at the time.  He patiently explained the dishes to us and was patient as we figured out what we were going to order.  So we ordered 2 orders of lechon (carcar), one regular and the other spicy, fried calamari, soup (utan bisaya na may pasayan), squid adobo, vegetables (pinakbet), noodles (canton guisado), baked scallops and the garlic fried rice and a coconut shake.
The lechon was rediculously good!!!  Soft inner meat and the crunchiness of the skin was out of this world.  The meat just melts in your mouth.  Ive never had such good lechon in the states.  I was blown away with it and it wasent even too salty.  I can see from the lechon why they were so busy.  The spicy one wasent spicy at all...
The fried calamari and squid adobo were ok.  They werent amazing like the lechon.   The soup was good in that it cleansed your pallet and the warmth from it helps to breakdown the fattiness of the lechon.
The garlic fried rice was good.  It easily fed 7 people a good amount of rice.  There was a hint of garlic and it played well to the overall meal.
The vegetables were good in that it provided you with less guilt knowing that you had your serving of vegetables.
Baked scallops were lathered in too much cheese and the flavor of the seafood was lost, which was meh....
Also had a coconut juice which was so refreshing.  Eating all that protein in the hot environment, the coconut juice was a nice finish to the meal. 

Overall im glad i dont live close by to this place.  Because the taste and texture of the lechon is dangerous to my arteries and waistline.   But i enjoyed every bite of this rich rich meal.  Cebu did not disappoint with ther lechon!!!

title: Maya Mexican Restaurant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Susan D."},{"reviewer_name":"Elee J."},{"reviewer_name":"Bobby L."},{"reviewer_name":"Verne A."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco F."},{"reviewer_name":"Jay H."},{"reviewer_name":"Randy H."},{"reviewer_name":"Becky C."},{"reviewer_name":"john b."},{"reviewer_name":"Jorge B."}]
reviewr_text:
So while perusing the internet I saw great reviews for a mexican spot in Cebu on a travel website.  I love great mexican food and a margarita so I thought I would give this place a try.

Decor:  The first thing that sold me on this place was the ambiance and the look.  It literally had me turning my head every which way to make sure I didn't miss something hanging on the walls or posted on a shelf.  It was beautiful.  While I was alone, I could see how this spot would be perfect for date night.

Food:  I went on a sunday evening, so there were 2 for 1 margaritas and discounts on some of the dips/salsa.  I had the queso fundido which was pretty much a cheese and jalapeno dip.  It was very melty and had a great flavor.  It is very thick and most of my chips broke in the dip, but since I was alone I didn't mind digging right in with my fork.  I also ordered the brisket tacos.  They were decent but not great.  The brisket was a little tough for my liking.  I prefer my brisket a little more tender.  The top seller was a pork option, but I was over eating pork at this point.

Service:  Like most places in the Philippines, service is not the same as in the USA.  I never had a dedicated waiter/waitress that came over and asked me what I wanted.  I always had to get someone's attention and tell them that I was ready to order or if I had questions.  I don't say this as a negative, just something I noticed throughout the country.  It didn't bother me but if you aren't used to it you may think you are being ignored.  However, when you are able to talk to staff they are VERY PLEASANT.  Great experience.  

Sidenote:  Sundays are also salsa night after 9.  There were tons of people there salsa dancing the night away.  It captivated me more and added to the ambiance of the restaurant.  Definitely a date night top pick.

title: Everything Yummy
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Pier View P."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Jo Anne G."},{"reviewer_name":"Yna C."}]
reviewr_text:
Only a place that takes great pride in their food can call themselves Everything Yummy. So far this place does not disappoint. My favorite is their spicy humba. It tastes like a really good home cooked meal. I like how they took that old-aged recipe and made it a  little special by adding that spicy sesame oil! YUM! Their salads were also a big hit for me but maybe a 7 out of 10 because i've had better ones before.

The ambiance is very simple and laid back. You won't be expecting to get such tasteful dishes at mere glance & most probably the only reason you dared to try it out is because you've heard too many good things about their food that you simply can't let it pass by.

Their service is not that good. It's not bad but I think they can surely do much better. I say they improve a little on their service, add more to their dessert menu & they're set for the next 10yrs. 

It's not easy to give yourself a name that you can't live up to but EVERYTHING YUMMY is indeed everything yummy!

reviewr_text: I love this place.  Who doesn't love Shabu Shabu, you get a good portions and you can create the sauce that you want to dip in plus they have hello kitty shaped fish balls which are super cute!

title: Tsay Cheng
reviewr_text: Huge Place for Big events and special occasions like weddings and birthdays! This place can seat hundreds! The food is pretty good , the serving size for banquets are more than adequate and price for set menus are great! We had a private room for 2 tables to seat all twenty of us. I really love the birthday noodle, fried pigeon and the salmon but not necessarily in that order. Suckling pig had very crunchy and tasty skin ! Our two waiters are great and always smiling. Over all one of the best chinese restaurants in cebu!

title: Siosai Tempura
reviewr_text:
The staff is friendly and accommodating. I went for meal set number 3; 2pc shrimp, 1 white fish, amd 3 veggies.  Set came with bowl of rice, miso soup and dipping sauce. Overall a pretty good meal, though would have preferred slightly more crispy batter.
The pricing seemed reasonable but take note I prefer bigger meals. For dessert, I tried the leche flan tempura. Might try different dessert next time, since I would have preferred the flan to be room temp. it seemed to be on the cold side, despite the frying.
Overall a ok meal and enjoyable experience.

reviewr_text:
If you love Lechon, you must come to Zubuchon! 

The waitress took our order quickly and advised it would be a 20 minute wait which was fine. 

We had the 500g of plain lechon, with garlic rice and some sauteed green vegetables. The lechon was juicy and succulent and so delicious! It was pretty amazing and I was so glad to be in the Philippines.

The best thing about Zubuchon is when you walk past, you can see the Chef preparing the lechon and it just makes you want to come inside. JUST DO IT! You won't regret it! One of the best lechon's I had in the Philippines.

title: Bari-Uma
reviewr_text: Stumbled onto Bari-Uma while strolling around the Ayala center, and Im glad that we did. My GF got the most popular option and I got the spicy one. She has a higher spice tolerance and we quickly traded- she loved my spicy ramen. What she got originally was really good too. They also have Japanese and San Mig beer options so that was a big plus. We came here at night right in time for the light show so we sat outside to watch. It was a really great experience for us and I would definitely come back again.

title: Chikaan sa Cebu
reviewr_text: This place can be busy during mealtimes and especially weekends. They are good at handling big groups and yhe ambiance is pleasant. They have the traditional dishes but their menu evolves based on trending filipino fare.

title: Kuya J's Restaurant
reviewr_text:
Great restaurant in the food court area of Ayala Mall in Cebu, clean with modern decor.

The must haves were Relyenlong Talong, a Filipino eggplant omelette and the Kuya J's Bulalo, which is a beef bone soup. Unfortunately they were out of the kare kare, so we were not able to sample that. The omelette was by far my favorite, it was nice and crispy on the top side and the underside was the soft eggplant. For the beef soup, the broth was superb! We also tried the lumpia - which was disappointingly salty - and also the sisig fried rice. The only reason we got the fried rice was because they charge plain white rice per head. Go ahead and pay for the white rice instead of getting a rice dish because the sisig fried rice was lacking in sisig. Overall a fantastic place with hardly any wait and some tasty choices.

title: Pizza Republic
reviewr_text:
I wish they have bigger pizza size.

The pizza are good and you can select your own toppings and make your own pizza but somehow there is something lacking and I can't figure it out. Also the taste of the food is forgettable.
I can't actually remember if it was good or not. 

Normally I can easily finished a 14 inch size pizza on my own but in this case I only had a few slices. 

Service was fast and staff polite. 

Clean and great ambiance.

Iced Tea is terrible.

title: CoCo Ichibanya
reviewr_text:
Coco Ichibanya is located off F. Cabahug St. at the Bonifacio District Retail Center. If you're coming from the Ayala Mall area it'll be on your left on that street after the curve.

Upon entering we were greeted, loudly, then promptly seated. We ordered the Pork Cutlet Curry and I believe the Chicken Curry as well. As I browsed through the menu I did not notice they had naan but didn't say if they the garlic cheese naan that I ordered back in Japan. Anywho since we had time to kill, why not get online while waiting for our food. Uhh well, they only had wifi for the "admin" the waitress said. "Bummer!" I thought. So we waited for awhile for our food.  I decided to head on over to the restroom to wash my hands. Upon entering the restroom smelled good, like the shampoo from Daiso in Japan. However, the hid the toilet paper behind the mirror. Pretty Odd! The bidet toilet was disgusting. Who on earth would even use that bidet in that condition. Also, the toilet was right infront of the sink so if someone was not careful they would end up hitting their head on the sink. Since it was a unisex restroom the men's urinal was comfortably situated on the other side, which I believe for obvious reasons should have been placed on the other side, where the bidet is. But anyway I washed my hands and left.

Food arrived and it smelled and tasted similar to the ones in Japan. The downfall?! I believe their pork cutlet is frozen. The outer part was crispy and hot but the inside was a bit chewy and not as hot. So I'm assuming it was previously frozen. Anyway the curry was authentic and matched the seasoning and flavoring to the branches in Japan. When Inwas in Japan I don't recall having the option to choose rice portion size. So I thought that was kinda weird too. Different price points for different rice portion sizes and different kind of rice. We opted for their combo which included ice cream and a drink. Ice cream and the little fruits in it was good. 

Staff: Throughout our time there various employees were just standing around chit chatting, playing tag with each other, and I believe someone from management sitting at the counter watching movied on their phone. I know there weren't many patrons but I don't think it pleasing to watch employees just randomly doing whatever they want. Anyway our waitress was good her service was acceptable.

Overall, I think if you haven't visited coco ichibanya in Japan than this is a way to try it out. Would I come back to this particular one again? Probably not. The establishment itself looks nice and neat, the bathroom ehh yucky. I just wish that the pork wasn't initially frozen because it was soo chewy, like it was flash fried or something. Curry was good. No Wifi, free parking.

title: La Fortuna Bakery
reviewr_text:
Old known place though I cant find anything special about this bakery. 

Im so hungry during my walking at downtown Sugbo so I decided to eat some rice meal in La fortuna they also have school supplies inside, its more like a 7/11 set-up. Delicious food but I think its too much hunger that makes it delicious that time.

title: Cardinal Coffea
reviewr_text: I only had the pleasure of eating one item from Cardinal Bake Shop.  That one item was their Cheese Rolls.  Let me tell you something.  If you only eat one item from Cardinal Bake Shop, then let it be their Cheese Rolls.  They taste great!!  So simple in their greatness, and it really satisfies my sweettooth without being too sweet!

reviewr_text: As a foreigner I find the boneless meat very convenient. The skin is a nice spicy flavor that does not take away from the whole meal.  Silverware is provided but eating with your hands is a bit more traditional. If you do not want your hands getting greasy plastic gloves are provided as well.  I cannot give this a five star rating since it is a little expensive by Filipino standards but I do not think you can find this around your local markets. Despite the price I think it is worth the price.

title: Hukad sa Golden Cowrie

reviewr_text: Staff are nice, food is fairly priced, clean area and well lit dining area. We will definitely come again.

title: Mooon Cafe
reviewr_text:
Over the years this place has gotten a lot better.  When I first went to Mooon, I was expecting some interesting Mexican.  I don't know what I was expecting....Mexican with an Asian twist?  I don't know how they'd conquer that.   But at that time, Mooon was really only serving pizza!  I was surprised!!  Is pizza Mexican?  I know of Taco Bell's mexican pizza but I don't know anywhere else with something like that. 

Well, the pizza was very good at that time so I went back quite a few times over the years.  I am now seeing that they have a pretty substantial branch of burritos and other Mexican items I would expect.  They also have some classic Filipino food as well.

I say try it if you're interested.  Not a place I'd consider a make-or-break to a trip to the PH

title: Tao Yuan
reviewr_text:
The thing with most Chinese restaurants is that they're a hit or a miss, because of the number of dishes coming out with lauriat style. 

Starting off with cold cuts, it tasted good. The second was soup - and it was served cold! That was a disappointing start to the meal. Singapore style chili crab, while the most expensive (almost 3k for a kilo of shriveled crab), tasted average and wasn't very flavorful.

The buchi balls smelled bad off the fryer. But they did quite well on cha misua, fried lapu-lapu, and Peking duck that we ordered. 

Service is always good, but the kitchen can be very slow to serve. A little on the pricey side, but Cebuanos now have little choice for Chinese seafood restaurants since Choi closed too. Tao Yuan is probably the best from the Manila imports.

title: Neo Neo BBQ Grille
reviewr_text:
The food is delicious and fresh, no doubt about that! The prices are very reasonable and variety is good. However, the service has place for improvement.

If you come as a group and order individually, they can bring food to only one person first, leaving others having to stare at the lucky one. Or they can bring the main dish before the soup or appetizer. And even desert before the main meal. 

They don't know that the drinks should be served first, so expect your drinks when you are finishing your meal. 

They waiters are nice and eager to help, but I think the lack of proper training brings the rep of this restaurant down.

title: Sachi
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Ed T."},{"reviewer_name":"Keisha R."},{"reviewer_name":"Myles C."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris S."}]

title: Phat Pho
reviewr_text:
Coming from a rainy day we decided that some pho would be nice. 

Service was great and we were quickly seated. The waiter and waitress were eager and pleasant when it was time to order.

We ordered 2 pho specials (comes with meatball, literally just the one, beef and tendon, but no tripe. Waitress didn't know what tripe was either) small, one viet coffee ( I said cafe sua da and the waitress didn't know what I was talking about ) and bottled water. We have a spot we frequent back in the States for pho, so this wasn't our first time. I waited patiently for the bean sprout plate they normally hand out before you get your pho but then I noticed written on their wall that they include everything for you in your pho. uhmm ok. So we got our order and the first thing I normally do is take a sip of the broth. Yeah it's not authentic pho for sure. I guess maybe it' their own twist but a Filipino version? Idk, but nothing compares to the broth at Pho Bang in Garland,Texas, so we're pretty spoiled when it comes to pho. The meatball wasn't made like the Viet places we frequent back home, and the taste was also lacking. It was nice that they added the basic cilantro to their pho as I believe cilantro in general is hard to find in dishes here in the Philippines. I like alot of bean sprouts in my pho and I like to add the mint leaves in as well. We didn't have that choice. The viet coffee was ok, I requested extra condense milk. 

Overall the service was great, no complaints at all. The food.. well it was meh, I would have liked some authentic flavored viet pho and wheres the tripe? If we come back maybe we'll try their bahn mi and see how that works out.

Tip: They have no restroom in their restaurant nor a sink to wash your hands. Instead, they were nice enough to hand me some purel. They also accept credit cards.

main: Tony G’s Foodcourt by Ned Nanay’s Grill
title: Tony G's Foodcourt by Ned Nanay's Grill
CnT Lechon
reviewr_text:
Cebu is known for their tasty, crunchy skinned, roasted pig - Lechon. When you ask Cebuanos where to get the BEST, CnT Lechon is the first lechon place they will recommend to tourists. It is meaty, less fatty, juicy and cheaper without sacrificing taste.

When we had lunch here, the lechon was sold out; a true testament of how good the food was. We had to wait for the next batch to arrive. To avoid the crowd/line, we pre-ordered 1Kg of lechon + a plate of Chopsuey (just to give balance to our meal) for 5 people. The one thing I like about CnT lechon is the crispy skin! Make sure you have a piece of skin with the juicy, soft and tender meat. Eat it together with rice and a dab of the dipping sauce (a mixture of vinegar/soy sauce/chili) - you won't stop till you eat every single piece of meat!

One reason why many prefer CnT is because of the price. The price of lechon ranges between Php2800 to Php4500 depending on the size of your whole roasted pig. You can also order it per kilo for only Php320. On our last day, we decided to bring some lechon for our loved ones. We bought 2Kg of lechon then added Php20 for the sealed box. :)

You may want to add other items like sinigang, chicharon, lumpia or just focus on the lechon. Don't hesitate to eat with your hands! :D

reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]
reviewr_text:
I give this 5 stars because it was one of the highlights of my trip. One complaint I'll get out the way is to make the Lechon hotter (temperature) and maybe add more skin. Its something you can fix with a simple request but I'm low maintenance. 

Came here with a lovely date that doesn't mind packing it in. Had the cheese stick appetizer that I'm sure American foreigners won't forget.

Mixed veggies, serving of Lechon, scallops , some fruit drinks = happy me

They have an indoor room I think you can reserve, so if you want the ultimate A/C comfort with good food then call in. The tourist buses usually take them all.

Mix this experience with waterfalls, deep diving in warm waters, and blue and free scenery and you'll want to move to Cebu

title: Isla Sugbo Seafood City
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"David P."},{"reviewer_name":"Gregory C."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Danie S."},{"reviewer_name":"Erica V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Jennelle L."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Jo Anne G."},{"reviewer_name":"Laura A."},{"reviewer_name":"Rocky Betty Jo P."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco F."}]
reviewr_text:
Great concept, as it's a buffet of fresh seafood put out raw.  You pick what you like, then tell them how you would like it prepared.  They have many varieties of fresh fish, shrimp, octopus, scallops, etc..  You can also pick out fresh vegetables and have the chef prepare them for you as well.  Rice is also included, but be careful not to order too much!  The price is reasonable, but only if you finish everything on the table.  If not, you will be charged about double per person,for not finishing.  It's still a fair deal for the quality and the choices, but just pay attention to eating everything you order.  

I will be back on my next visit to Cebu!

I 101% prefer this branch.

title: Yumeya Kihei
reviewr_text: Been to this place ever since I can remember. Owned by Mr. Bong Suda (R.I.P), he used to be the head chef of Kukai Japanese Restaurant before, but he eventually left and decided to open his own restaurant instead. The owner, Mr. Bong Suda (R.I.P) is one of the pioneers in Japanese cuisine here in Cebu. He has been one of the best Japanese chefs in Cebu. From what I hear, he is highly regarded and praised by other Japanese chefs and people here as he is the one who basically started the trend(Japanese cuisine) and make it boom. Ever since Mr. Suda was gone, his son decided and currently is in Japan doing some studying/training in order to follow in his father's footsteps. His wife, Mrs. Carmen Suda, is the one who manages the restaurant while his apprentice is the one cooking for the restaurant now. I have to say, he has done quite an excellent job teaching and training his apprentice. The food is just as good and has been consistent. The quality and taste is still there. I would definitey recommend this restaurant to anyone.

title: Pizza Republic
reviewr_text: Has become my favorite place to eat. Inexpensive and very good. Would compare it with make your own pizza in the US.

title: Cherry's The Spice
reviewr_text:
Best Indian food I've had in Cebu. Veg biryani is full of flavor and veggies, the naan is excellent, the samosas are really fresh made with a tasty mint sauce, and all of the dishes we had, kadai paneer, different masalas, prawn and chickpea, all delicious.

You do have to wait a while for your food but the service is good, it's just that the food is all made to order and takes time. Not the place to go if you're in a hurry, but worth the wait when you're craving the flavors of India.

title: Gerry's Grill
reviewr_text: We are balikbayans who ate at this location. A fly swam in our nilaga soup that we barely touched. We told the staff but they didn't offer to replace. We had to pay full price for a soup that we didn't eat.

title: Ramen Yushoken

reviewr_text: The BEST RAMEN in Cebu City!! My boyfriend and I visit here literally every week! One of our reasons why we travel 3 hours away from our hometown! It's always our first stop whenever we are in Cebu. Our orders will always be Shoyu (milky and salty/ MY FOREVER FAVE) and Tantanmen (spicy). Also try their Karaage and Gyoza!!

reviewr_text: This is such a beautiful restaurant in downtown Cebu. The rooftop view is a bonus. We had the pineapple fried rice, lobsters appetizer, and beef stew. It was sufficient to spilt between two people. Their drinks were also really good compared to other places in Cebu. Definitely check this place out for a nice dinner and they take credit card!

title: Choobi Choobi
reviewr_text:
Nestled within Cebu's Fuente area is a gem waiting to be discovered - Choobi Choobi seafood restaurant! 

A quick browse into the menu reveals this resto's specialties - seafoods galore! There's Scampi "baby lobsters" in a bag, giant bamboo clam, lobster/fish combo, and of course their signature dishes; Lola Pepang's Fried Manok and Stan's Fried Black Pepper Shrimps!

They also have classic dining staples such as belly dancer (grilled liempo), pork barbeque, sinigang, nilaga, and a lot more!

Craving for desserts, try their choco molten kiss or their special halo-halo!

The price is okay-ish but it's definitely worth a visit.

title: Luy's Classic Tea House
reviewr_text: Some pretty good Chinese food in Cebu.  They have a huge selection to choose from.  I enjoyed their cucumber salad and fried tofu.  Great place in Cebu if you're craving Chinese food.  All the Chinese tourists come here when they visit Cebu so you know it's the real deal.

title: Vibes
reviewr_text: I discovered this place from a friend. Its always open during the after hours and the chicken dishes are interesting. In the past they have had really spicy dishes, these days a little more mainstream it seems

title: Rica's
reviewr_text:
Staying at The Henry and this being the restaurant downstairs meant that I ate here a few times during my stay. That and the fact that we are greedy folk who order more than what 2 people ordinarily would eat in a single seating means that I've had a good range of the menu. 

They start every meal with these long crackers and an addictive salsa. Not sure how chopped tomato, capsicum (peppers) and onion with olive oil can taste so good. 

Notable mentions must go to their forty chicken - very small but delicious chicken cooked with 40 cloves of garlic and butter. Oreo crepe and their frozen layered dessert were also very nice. 

All pastas ordered were al dente and very garlicky. You just like garlic if you go to Philippines! Attentive service, coffees were not bad, wines were cheap at 150 peso per glass. And of course, their interesting decor.

title: Shakey's
reviewr_text:
First time I went to the Philippines, I ate one of the best pizza slices ever.  Was hoping to recreate that feeling again on this latest trip.  Unfortunately, it did not happen.   

While I was at SM City Cebu, I stopped by the Shakey's there.  They had a restaurant for dining in, but I only wanted one slice of their Classic Hawaiian pizza.  They were selling slices of about 4 different kinds of pizzas from their take out section.  I bought a slice from the take out section.   Alas, I did not get that same feeling of happiness that took place years ago.  Still, the pizza did taste decent.  Therefore, I am giving them 3 stars!

title: Ramen Dojo
reviewr_text:
Ramen Dojo is located on the 2nd floor of SM City. On the otherside of lava next door to my greek taverna.

Upon reading their menu I was a bit skeptical of the quality and portion size of their ramen as advertised 150 pesos for any of their ramen bowls. I ordered the tonkotsu and I must say it was satisfying (I mean, what one would expect in terms of portion for that price). They did add some type of mushroom that isn't a familiar ingredient and when taking a bite of it, left me remembering a chinese restaurant instead. Otherwise, the broth was neutral not too salty. They also offered combo items that included gyoza but I just opted for the ramen itself with sprite.

Restaurant was clean. Staff was quick, food came out just as quick as. Piping hot. I was pleasantly surprised by the value and the quality of their food. At 150 pesos not bad at all.

title: Buffet 101
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Cha S."},{"reviewer_name":"Alvin K."},{"reviewer_name":"Wok Star X."},{"reviewer_name":"Rhoel P."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."}]
reviewr_text:
Buffet 101 is located at City Times Square across the street from Park Mall in Mandaue. Parking is limited if you want to park right up front of the restaurant. When you pull into City Times Square, head on over to the garage area pass Liv, take a right then another right and you'll arrive at Buffet 101's open air parking area. 

We made a reservation because we were a party of 16 and it was a Saturday for a 6 pm seating. We arrived and a receptionist seated us. It was a Saturday night and as expected, crowded. As the rest of the group was still situating themselves with seating arrangements I went ahead and browsed their offerings. In one end, they offered a variety of Asian-themed food. Sushi, Japanese omelette, tempura to live shrimp cooked to order and of course, Filipino dishes. They had different kinds of soups and even congee. The middle area consisted of a small salad bar, desserts, and beverages. For those who are wondering, they do have beer on tap. Not sure the brand though. They also had sangria (wine). 

On to the other end of the buffet. I frequented this area as they offered roast beef, chicken and pork. I was told they had lamb as well. They had mashed potatoes, a diy sandwhich area, pizza, and pasta to just name a few. After browsing I grabbed a plate. I started with the roast beef in medium and pizza. Later, I went for the mashed potatoes. Fyi: ask your server for the steak knife, if your in need of one. They also had a station for cook to order seafood.

Staff: The waiters and waitresses were all very quick to please. Once you requested something a few moments later they would arrive with your requested item, promptly. Though at times you had to flag one of them down, it is to be expected at a buffet. The birthday singing at each birthday celebrant's table was absolutely entertaining. 

Cost: We did their birthday promo and there were a few in the group celebrating their birthday month. Paying adults are at 839 pesos each on a Saturday night. (Dinner seating) Their birthday promo allows the celebrant to complimentary dine given they had 3 paying adults in their group.

Overall: Despite having to always hunt down in finding a plate for each go at the buffet, the overall experience at Buffet 101 was fantastic. I won't deny we came on a expectation that the service would be sub par, due to various other reviews mentioning this. However, we were delightly surprised that our first experience here was enjoyable. The food, especially the roast beef and grilled salmon, were delicious and seasoned just right. If Buffet 101 wasn't a ways from where we stay, I'd definitely visit again even if it isnt for a special occasion. No wifi. Free Parking. Restrooms were clean, but had an odor.

reviewr_text: The food was so good here we came back to eat a second time during our stay in Cebu City! Between the two visits combined we probably had 10 different dishes we ate family style and they were all fantastic!The staff were friendly and the owner Karen even toured us around the restaurant to give us the history of when it was their family home. I highly recommend dining here!

reviewr_text: This is a best burger joint I have visited in all of the Philippines!  It is definitely a taste from back home in the United States.  They have a diverse menu of burgers.  You will be very pleased!

title: Cafe Marco
reviewr_text:
Review #044 - 2019

We showed up around 4:30 PM and hung out at the  pool area for about an hour, waiting for the buffet to open up.

We ordered a few drinks and some enseymadas to snack on, which I was told they are known for at this place.  I thought they were pretty good, but not wow'ed by it.  We got both the mango and ube flavors, but I only got to try the ube so I can't comment on the mango flavor.

My fresh young coconut juice was nicely cut so that you can drink it with a straw and then open the top to scoop out the coconut meat later, which I didn't get to enjoy.

We ended up going into the buffet area around 5:30 PM because the house next door was burning some woods or something, but it smelled terrible so our eyes were watering.

The buffet actually opens up at 6:30 PM so we just sat around and chatted until they opened up.

Service was actually very friendly and accommodating.

The food on the other hand was just ok.

The seafood selection didn't seem too fresh, even though I was told that this place serves the best.

My daughter really enjoyed the lechon, which I thought was kind of salty.

Nothing really stood out for me, but I thought their dessert arrangement was very pretty.

I tried the flan which was ok, but it wasn't as soft as I'm used to.

The chocolate mousse was good though.

title: Fujinoya
reviewr_text:
Gateau Chocolate Cake is to die for! I went to Fujinoya shortly after it opened when I lived in Cebu and I could tell the good quality of it's desserts/drinks was very unique. It's a good place to stop by for an afternoon caffeine fix, it's near JY square and therefore, near some great spots in Nivel Hills and TOPS. 

Stop by with some friends here before you head into the nice, cool hills. 

This place has good wifi, a decent amount of seating and good prices!

title: Mitsuyado Sei-Men
reviewr_text: Mitsuyado Sei-Men just recently opened last October 21. Finally decided to try it out today. I had the Marutoku Tsukemen and Gyoza. They were pretty good! The yuzu flavor really stands out and the broth was rich and flavorful. The gyoza was juicy and cooked as expected. I was able to have a couple of bites of their Charsiu Pao, it was okay...somehow it reminded me of the ones I had at Ippudo Ramen. I wasn't able to try the other dishes though but they look good. Overall, it was good. I would definitely come back again and try their other dishes.

title: House of Lechon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]
reviewr_text:
So this place is supposed to have good lechon but I think you really need to figure out the timing when the fresh lechon comes in.

The dinner lechon was re- fried, dry and not good at all.  The lechon is supposed to be from carcar, the well known area for lechon/chicharon.  It's also Cebu lechon which is famous for lechon. However, I'm sad to report that it definitely falls flat from any expectation of a good lechon.

Anyway, it's a nice looking place, food portions are on the smaller side.

title: Kaya
reviewr_text: Although the food in Kaya is actually very delicious I give it a 2 out 5 because of the service.  The waitress decided to put a hot pepper on the grill and it popped which hit my arm and burned it.  Instead of asking me if I was ok the waiter tells us that we shouldn't put hot peppers on the grill to cook for that reason.  We told them that it was the waitress who did it not us but the waitress didn't even admit to her mistake.  Then we had to ask for an ice pack instead of them giving us one which was pretty disappointing.  Hopefully they can learn from this because for me service is just as important as the food.

reviewr_text: Very clean and nicely decorated.  The food is tasty along with the pretty presentation.  It is a great combination to have under one roof.  Vietnam and Thai food.  I am a fan of both so it was a perfect combination.  The menu is a bit limited but they seem to cover most of the favorites.  I was a bit disappointed because they did not have yellow curry but they do have red and green.

title: Harbour City Dimsum House
reviewr_text:
Whenever we visit Cebu, Harbour City is always on our food list be it in SM mall or here at Ayala center. Because we come here so often, we almost forget that his restaurant is supposed to be Chinese than Filipino.

As always, their most popular dish is their steamed rice. It's not just rice that's steamed lol and i mention that because when i first came to America i was so excited to see "steamed rice" on the menu only to find out that it was just how they cook the rice. Here in harbour city, it comes with a pork sauce or gravy. You can't go wrong with it. Now, you also have the option to make it spicy.

In this particular chain, they always serve food dim sum style so they always have the cart around. Other dishes we usually go for is their fried lumpia, and the oooh sooo good siomai with quails egg. So far, no one else make steamed rice and siomai with quails eggs like harbour city. Their prices have gone high over the years though and without change in serving size. Cost of living sucks but it is what it is. It's always a pleasure eating here and I doubt I'd get tired of the place yet. 

Keep in mind this is no fancy restaurant and is almost, if not, the same as Dimsum Break. Either way, it's still a go to place for steamed rice.

title: Micky’s Cafe
reviewr_text:
The owner is japaneae and the attention to detail and tempered flavor of the pastries are present, The strawberry shortcake is the best in town, but not best if you have been to Japan or United States. 
The avocado pie, is another best seller and it is on my first try list if you come bere, I didn't think such a flavor made sense but it works for me flavor and texture wise.

title: Salinas
reviewr_text: Had dinner here with family around 8 to 10 people, at first service was swift serving our good and being attentive on our calls. Although after serving all the food we ordered they didnt even bother to check on us or even look at our group whenever we raised our hands for a refill on our drinks or ask for an order. Food was decent dont get me wrong but with a service like this who woupd have an appetite? I do not recommend this place at all.. there are better places around the area. I was so pissed at the waiter who was giving attitude behind me! Wtf??

title: Dimsum Break SM City Cebu
reviewr_text:
Something about this place that always makes us crave. It's their sauce on their Pai Kuat, chicken feet, siomal quall eggs, steamed chicken. Their garlic pork spare ribs is very yummy. This place NEVER gets old. They have many branches all over Cebu so they're easy to locate. We prefer this place over Harbour City dimsum when it comes to food flavor and seasoning.

They're located on 3rd floor, near the bowling alley, I tried editing the address but whoever at yelp is changing my post is not paying attention. 

We always dine on this branch as it is in the  mall and close to our place. Their space used to be big, they've shrunk and now it's hard to find a spot on peak hours. 

They take credit card but because of spotty internet connection, better bring cash.

title: Kuya J's Restaurant
reviewr_text:
Catfish was pretty good.  The scallops my wife liked however I'm not a scallop person.  Chicken halang-halang she also had and couldn't finish.  The amount of food was more for three not two.  The fruit drinks were excellent as I had watermelon and she had cucumber and it was all natural. 

I wasn't a fan of dipping sauce for the pork rolls or the catfish.  

I gave the rest of the chicken to the homeless kid outside the mall.

title: House of Lechon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]
reviewr_text:
When visiting the Philippines the one thing that everyone tells you to do is to try the lechon. That was my first order of business after landing. Of course I've eaten it before and even made it myself, but all of my Filipino friends say that it's best in country.

This restaurant was very busy and popular. A good (and healthy) sign I've noticed in less developed countries. The Decour reminded me of Island life and was very well staffed, no dish left uncovered slash/no water dropping below half/someone always at your beckon call.

I ordered the smallest lechon dish and soon realized it was too much for one person. I want to say it was at least one pound of pork and came with garlic rice. I paired it nicely with sweetened calamansi juice, which perfectly cleansed my palate before and after the meal. I would've drank a second glass of that juice if possible! 

It's doubtful I'll ever be in Cebu again, but if I were and I wanted lechon this would be the place. Only 4 stars because this place is a bit overpriced.

title: Sunburst
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Britt H."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Nina M."},{"reviewer_name":"Stewart O."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."}]
reviewr_text: Great, spacious room here for dining! I thoroughly enjoyed their vegetable curry. It was flavorful, and paired great with the rice. The chicken, crispy and juicy- was delicious! That also paired well with the rice. The service was great. Raquel, our server, was nice and attentive, as well as patient. I would definitely come back to this place, it's in a great location and I like how they have a variety of options on their menu! Affordable too!

title: Laguna Garden Cafe
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Kimberly T."},{"reviewer_name":"PatrickJ T."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Ken S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Sherwin T."},{"reviewer_name":"Andrew M."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text:
Laguna Garden Cafe was one of the first restaurants I tried in Cebu City years ago.  They were good then, and they are still really good now.  I like their location at Ayala Center in Cebu City.  Terrific place to catch up with family and/or friends.  The service is always good, and the restaurant has always been clean.  Although the CR (restroom) could use an upgrade.

They serve authentic Filipino cuisine at Laguna Garden Cafe.  None of that Fusion stuff!  No foreign food on the menu either.  If you are looking for a burger or lasagna, then you will have to look elsewhere.  Go ahead and order what you want.  Literally, everything we've ordered has tasted delicious.  Don't forget to try their desserts and drinks too!!

title: The Pig & Palm
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Tricie C."},{"reviewer_name":"Jacob C."},{"reviewer_name":"Kevin G."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Daniel S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kristine S."},{"reviewer_name":"Carl I."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Dan P."},{"reviewer_name":"Cynthia Q."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text:
Are here twice for dinner on my entry and exit nights in Cebu.
What a treat to eat food of this quality after traveling around enjoying more rustic fare.
The prawns are a standout for me. The gnocchi with chicken thighs was delicious BUT became entirely too sweet once the caramelized onions were discovered. Completely not needed in this dish.
Beet salad 9/10
Cauliflower 8/10 best to share as it is quite rich 
60' lava cake 9/10 would prefer coconut ice cream to the salted caramel
Croquettes 8/10 needed a bit more salt. The aioli helps.
As a solo diner, I ate in front of the kitchen one night and the other in the side room. I would not recommend the side room. Felt isolated and with larger groups or children, way too loud. The bar would have been better.

Service was above reproach. 
When my travels take me back to Cebu, I will definitely return.

title: Blackbeard's Seafood Island
reviewr_text: Crooks ... I ordered the grilled tuna listed for 100 pesos for 100 grams. But when I checked my bill the charge was listed as 200 pesos. When questioned, the waitress stated that the minimum charge for the item is 200 grams, hence, 200 pesos. This minimum charge, however, was not noted anywhere on the menu nor informed to me by the staff. I suggest avoiding this place ... they're crooks. Who knows what other scam they have hidden on the menu. If you must go, question the price of all the items you order. Good luck.

reviewr_text: I literally had to locate this burger joint because it's a few minutes away from the main street and with a rather simplistic facade but the effort was all worth it! I love their deluxe bacon cheeseburger to death! Juicy, carefully cooked patties with veggies and fries served on top of a chopping board. Quiet novel! You have to drop by here if you love burgers and is in Cebu! Highly recommended!
