title: Cebu's Original Lechon Belly
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jefferson S."},{"reviewer_name":"Abbys A."},{"reviewer_name":"Gio G."},{"reviewer_name":"Gil M."},{"reviewer_name":"Anneke D."},{"reviewer_name":"Barry T."},{"reviewer_name":"Maputing E."},{"reviewer_name":"Mike M."},{"reviewer_name":"Swan L."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."}]
reviewr_text: First Lechon experience in the Philippines and it was probably the tastiest! According to the locals, Cebu Lechon are cooked with spices and aromatics while Manilla Lechon is usually without the spices/aromatics and they use a dipping sauce for flavoring. At Lechon Belly, they serve the belly of the pork and have two options: original and spicy. The spicy is a must, but fair warning, will leave a lasting tingling feeling on the lips for awhile (that is, until you get some shaved snow!) Another important thing to keep in mind is that they don't supply utensils, so get ready to get your hands dirty!

title: Ramen Yushoken
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Angela L."},{"reviewer_name":"Gio G."},{"reviewer_name":"Dani S."},{"reviewer_name":"Zerra Mae Lyka L."},{"reviewer_name":"Judy J."}]
reviewr_text: I've had ramen from Japan so I have pretty high standards when it comes to the dish. There aren't many ramen shops in Cebu that make a decent ramen. So it's a lil exciting for Cebuanos when they come across one. Yushoken is one of the few places that offer decent ramen. The place has a decent amount of tables, but expect to wait for seating at peak hours. Yushoken is widely known in Cebu as the best ramen shop, and this isn't really something I can argue against. But then again, there's also not a lot of competition. I got to try their Tantanmen and Shoyu. I had nothing I could think of to better their broth, and the noodles were cooked just right. The dishes just lacked the complexity that I expected based on the price. You even had to pay an extra 80 pesos in order to have an egg in your ramen. Something that should've been included in the first place. But the ramen themselves tasted great and I would agree that they have the best in Cebu. In my ratings though, I take into account the price. In this case, Yushoken gets one star off because I would say that it wasn't worth the prices.

title: Sunburst
reviewr_text: I remember this place from my childhood before the big malls came in along with "progress." It is now a hole in the wall location, unless you have things to do in the downtown area. Its all about the chicken, if it takes time for you to get your order then its usually a good thing, since they usually cook upon your order. If you are in good health try the fried chicken skin, but if your health conscious try the amplaya with beef although on the salty side or the cellophane noodle which are dishes thar my relatives usually order.

title: Parilya
reviewr_text: Food was really good.  But like in most restaurants in Philippines, service could still be improved.  I just can't wrap my head as to why there are always so many waiters & waitresses but I feel like I have to fight for their attention.  One of the things we ordered also never came out.  But the nice view of the sea was a plus.  Better service would have made this a 5-star review.

title: The Ching Palace
reviewr_text: Definitely not a place I would come for Chinese food.  Food is nothing special and some is a little too oily.  There is better Chinese restaurants in Cebu that will give you a bang for you buck.

title: Lunhaw Vegan Cafe
reviewr_text: Fantastic! The Sig Sig was out of this world! Clean and fast service. Hard to drink lemonade out of mason jar with cover and metal straw. However, love the eco-sustainability. Definitely going back.

title: House of Lechon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]
reviewr_text:
First time in Cebu City and was looking for a restaurant that had lechon.  Asked the concierge and House of Lechon came highly recommended and was within a 5 minute walk from our hotel.  Arrived at around 8 pm on a Thursday for a late dinner (took us 4.5 hours to arrive to our hotel from the port at Maya).  The restaurant is sorta tucked away on a dark side street but the front sign was clearly lit.  

The restaurant was about half full, we were quickly seated at a booth and given a few minutes to browse the menu.  We ended up ordering a little of both the original and the spicy lechon (smallest grams of each), some sauteed ong choy, and some garlic rice.  The food came out pretty quickly which was a good thing as my buddy and I were starving.  I saw calamansi juice on the menu so I knew I had to order that since it was our last dinner during our week long dive trip in Malapascua.

If you can handle a bit of heat, I definitely would recommend the spicy lechon as the perfectly roasted suckling pork was mixed with a spicy and citrusy soy sauce which added a ton of flavor.  The skin was perfectly crispy and the lechon had the perfect fat/meat balance.  The sauteed ong choy was also perfectly sauteed and seasoned and the dab of hot sauce added a nice little kick to the dish. Every meal while in the Philippines should be done with garlic rice as it's tasty as hell.  The iced calamansi juice was super refreshing and hit the spot on a warm night.

Wished we had dined here before heading to Malapascua to start our trip as this was the best meal we had all week long.  As have mentioned, the halo halo isn't like your traditional shaved ice but instead an ube milk shake which was good but having the traditional dessert would've been better.  

Would definitely recommend this place to anyone in the area.

title: Sunburst
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Britt H."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Nina M."},{"reviewer_name":"Stewart O."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."}]
reviewr_text:
A quick meal to have if your staying in the area. Not the best Cebu has to offer but decent enough.

The pricing is great if your American , the dollar goes far here. Spent about 800 pesos for 2 people who each ordered 2 items plus drinks.

Friendly service. So if your feeling like some fried chicken, it's pretty juicy here. Dried fish plate. Oreo shake. Not a fan of the noodles, felt watered down and over poured fat brotha. 

Recommended if your your staying at Horizon. Be careful visiting at night, theirs a club across the street full of "extra" services. Not sure how shady it gets. Also careful crossing the streets !

title: House of Lechon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]
reviewr_text:
Kind of disappointed for their lechon since this is what they're famous for. When it was served to us it was cold and the skin was beyond chewy, not one bit crispy at all. We also ordered a crab meat dish but when it came it was like a soupy crab meat which is not what we expected. We also ordered sisig and it was also kind of disappointing where it was not crunchy at all. It was like eating fatty pork served on a sizzling pan. 

I think my most favorite dish was the vegetables, which tells you a lot. Also my Ube drink was not bad. The only reason I would give it three stars is because of their interior and the comfort of the restaurant. I also like the fact that they gave you a banana leaf as a plate. I think it is worth a try if you have a lot of time in Cebu, but if it is one of those very few meals I think you can skip it.

reviewr_text:
Don't mess around and get over to one of the AA BBQ joints and dig in.

They have a good assortment of bbq and other dishes.

I love the pork bbq skewers. The fried calamari is delish.

Prices are very reasonable.

Go here. Eat. Repeat.

title: Lemon Grass
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Steve F."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Nichole B."},{"reviewer_name":"Alex S."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."},{"reviewer_name":"James R."}]
reviewr_text:
This was my very first restaurant in the PH, and I have dreams of it back at home in the US. They have a delicious Kang Kong dosh that is delightful. All dishes are served with roce, and you eat off of a banana leaf at the table!

It is pricey compared to local restaurants, but I find it is well worth the money. I make this a routine trip every time I visit Cebu.

reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]
reviewr_text:
When locals of Cebu want to celebrate a special event, many pay a visit to "The House of Lechon."

It's quite fancy, minus the table cloth.  They have a ginormous (hahaha) dining area both indoors and outdoor. We dined here for Valentine's Day. Their Lechon (roasted pig cooked underground covered with banana leaves) was surprisingly, delicious! It literally melted in our mouth! Another favorite of ours was their freshly made mango shake. I think they used more than three fresh mangos per glass which was fantastic.  It was so good.

I can understand why the locals come here for their special events. Service was great, and of course being Valentine's Day, we had a romantic dinner style.

Cheers!

title: Blu Bar & Grill
reviewr_text:
This may have been the most disappointing meal I had in Cebu. For 5 star Restaurant they were out of 3 first choices for dinner, waitress was not professional at all.
My wife had fish and there was a paper wrapper in it, waitress explained sorry chef left it in it never offered to take it and replace it.
Had ordered a birthday cake and it was delayed and sent to wrong table, my meal was tasteless.
Waitress was never really trained to work in a five star restaurant, when asked for manager waited 15 minutes and was told not there then asked for Hotel manager and after 15 minutes Restaurant Magerer showed up.
Yes they took off the two bad meals but entire experience was terrible

title: Bicester Cafe
reviewr_text:
Lovely breakfast/brunch spot by the outskirts of Ayala Mall and close to Lot 8 Condominiums. This delicious cafe serves silogs and other foods and cakes, but we came here for breakfast. Early risers also come here to just chill in this clean eatery which has a chill homey ambience. It was definitely a good experience as we had tocilog bowls which were very tasty and filling. The coffee and iced tea is also great here for a pick-me-up in the am. I liked that the location was also low-key.

Lots of seating and tables.
CR available.
Great breakfast/brunch spot.

Mangaon ta!

title: Fujinoya
reviewr_text: Simple, low key, but great coffee. Not too air conditioned. The staff was really friendly and the cakes look great even though I was here right before a wedding so I didn't want to get a bunch of food.

reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco R."},{"reviewer_name":"Caitlin M."},{"reviewer_name":"Sivilay T."},{"reviewer_name":"Tawny T."},{"reviewer_name":"Kartik K."}]
reviewr_text: This restaurant as the name suggests has amazing view of Cebu City. They serve mostly local seafood delicacies. Seafood karekare, seafood tinola, fried calamari, crab soup. They also have bbq chicken and usda beef on the menu. Full bar and plenty of local juices from the bar to go with the food. Amazingly inexpensive and refreshingly local in taste. Parking is limited as it's on the hilltop. Reservation is recommended as it's poplar with the locals. 45 min ride uphill form the city center is worth your time if you want some good views of the Cebu City while you can enjoy local seafood delicacies cooked home style.

reviewr_text: I was not impressed with their service or their barbecue ribs.  Their ribs were fatty and over cooked. I won't go back again.

title: BBQ Choy
reviewr_text: Good food and music , I love the BBQ , located next to a hostel with lots of people to meet .

title: Naruto Tukemen Tokyo Noodle
reviewr_text: This is sort of a kiosk location in additon to the one close the Sykes building in Mabolo. it looks and tastes like a home cooked meal since the broth and noodles seems to stray from the standard broth and noodle textures. This place is at the bottom of my list when it comes to noodle texture, but i respect that fact that he has added cabbage to his broth and with gyoza added to the meal for 250 pesos this may be one of the least expensive meals offered by a japanese entrepenuer.

title: Ikkousha Ramen
reviewr_text: Authentic Hakata style ramen! The taste is just as good as the ones in Japan. I know many have heard or have tried eating at Ichiran Ramen or Butao Ramen, this place is similar to those places. As you enter, you get greeted by the hospitable staff there and your assigned waitress would show you to your seat. First things first, when you get seated, you get this piece of paper where you can fill up and select your preferred ramen, noodle texture, saltiness, and other add-ons including side orders. For those who prefer non-noodle dishes, they have those as well, like the mini donburi. As for me, I ordered the Tonkotsu Special with extra menma(bamboo shoot) and seaweed. The soup was flavorful and the noodles was cooked to my preferred liking. I got the chicken karaage as well, it was crispy, juicy, and cooked to perfection! Overall the meal was pretty good as expected. Too bad the gyoza wasn't available that time but their karaage was good. I would definitely recommend this place to anyone looking for a good ramen place.

title: Sunburst

title: Zubuchon

reviewr_text: Lichen was amazing!!!  We loved it and the skin was crispy!!!  We were visiting from the US.  3 of the 4 adults were filipino though and we all love Lechon.  The food was great, the staff was amazing.  Even the 1 year old loved the food.  A must go to if you are in Cebu.  Prices are great as well.

title: Teppanyaki Brothers
reviewr_text:
Inside the new SM Seaside mall they recently opened Teppanyaki Brothers near the ice skating rink.  I love teppanyaki so we were excited to give it a try. 

We chose the all meats deal that comes with pork,  chicken & beef with rice, vegetables & soup for two for less than 400 pesos.. quite a deal in my opinion. 

Soup was first served that was watered down to much for my taste. 

Steamed rice was next which was most certainly a very low grade of rice.

Vegetables were served next that was bland and tasteless,  even after adding soy sauce the taste was just not right. 

Next came the three meats that we choose to have with chili since they were kind enough to ask what our preference was.  As expected from the previous items served all three were bland and tasteless,  we were so surprised that meet covered in sauce could be this depressing on our taste buds and as for the chili I couldn't taste any and I'm very sensitive to chili and spices. 

We decided to leave before even finishing 1/4 of the meal and got some pizza. 

Hope they can make some changes because this would be a great option to the normal choices around the malls in Cebu.

title: The Burger Joint
reviewr_text: Burgers are in my top 5 dishes of all time. Because of my love for it, I've tried burgers from a lot of places that I've been to, so I do consider myself to be a good judge when it comes to them. Burger Joint reminds me of the cookouts that I've been to back home. The fresh lettuce and tomato, on top of a good patty. Nostalgia is probably playing a role in my overall experience, because Burger Joint reminds me of home. It reminds me of the local diners that I've usually preferred, since I was a child. There's nothing too special about their burgers. But in their simplicity comes mastery. Overall, they serve great burgers at a great price. A well deserved 5/5.

title: Yakski
reviewr_text: My favorite BBQ in Cebu! The original is close to the Capitol building, but this new one in IT park is really great. My favorite thing about their BBQ is the spicy sauce that goes with it. It's to die for! Best meal, best price and so filling and satisfying.

title: Istanblue Resto Lounge
reviewr_text: The food is true to its turkish roots and very affordable. The place  has a cool and chill ambiance perfect for a quite date or dinner with family and friends. I also love the wide variety of beverages from herbal or fruit teas to wines and spirits. The lounging areas are perfect for hanging out with friends over shisha and your favorite drink.

title: Isla Sugbo Seafood City
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"David P."},{"reviewer_name":"Gregory C."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Danie S."},{"reviewer_name":"Erica V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Jennelle L."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Jo Anne G."},{"reviewer_name":"Laura A."},{"reviewer_name":"Rocky Betty Jo P."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco F."}]
reviewr_text:
This is Filipino AYCE at its finest.  After being seated, we were escorted by our waitress to the seafood showcase to select our items.  The food looked pretty fresh, but the taste was just OK.  It seemed on the bland side.  The service was a little on the slow side, too.

Overall, not bad, but pretty much just average.

came here for lunch and their burittos are delicious.  you can havw it with rice or potato.  i actually like both.

im giving this a 3 because their nachos are not so great.  it was cold and it had some sauce that wasnt too yummy.

they also got dips you can try out. one is like super spicy so watch out.

title: Ulli's

title: Domings Ngohiong
reviewr_text: One of the best Ngojiong in Cebu. It is a small place. Sometimes when it gets crowded wait can be long, but when you start eating it is well worth it. The place though is within a residential area, parking can be a challenge if you go around lunch time. Come early!

title: The Pig & Palm
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Tricie C."},{"reviewer_name":"Jacob C."},{"reviewer_name":"Kevin G."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Daniel S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kristine S."},{"reviewer_name":"Carl I."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Dan P."},{"reviewer_name":"Cynthia Q."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]

title: Off Roads Cafe
reviewr_text:
Off Roads Cafe has been here for as long as i can remember. It was decent once but now with the ever changing trends especially with food and drinks i feel as if this place has not been able to keep up.

There was hardly any delectable looking pasty available on their shelf however in fairness to them, they do have good blueberry cheesecake. Drinks are okay but not something I would be craving for.

If not for its location, which is by Sykes and being that they are the only cafe nearby with a rooftop, i doubt this place would've survived until today. I would love to give this place a higher rating if only they would do some updates even if it is just to freshen up their look.

title: Adventure Cafe
reviewr_text: I was here twice this year! The first time this past summer I got nervous and the guys assisting with the ziplining cheered me on, and again the next day when I finally ziplined. It is such a fun place up in the mountainous area of Cebu. The price is very reasonable, I believe we only paid 250 pesos per person to zipline (you could never pay that low in the USA). The experience and scenery is incomparable - it will always be such a peaceful memory to me. The menu in the cafe is also pretty tasty - I forgot to take photos as it was so hot out, I couldn't really focus. That is the only downfall is there is no A/C in the cafe but if you are familiar with the area - that is already a commonality. I hope more visitors review so this spot can get the attention it deserves however they did seem to keep a pretty steady flow of customers. The friendly staff made it an even better experience -  even photographing and videotaping our experience with our phones!

title: Buffet 101
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Cha S."},{"reviewer_name":"Alvin K."},{"reviewer_name":"Wok Star X."},{"reviewer_name":"Rhoel P."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."}]
reviewr_text: This is a super asian buffet. Its about the average size of a big Vegas buffet. For 799 pesos for dinner it's worth it. The seafood quality is really good. You can't get seafood any fresher. The live shrimp comes right out of the tank to pot or grill. So fresh so good! About 90% of the buffet items are international asian and the rest are westerner items. They also have self serve San Miguel beer on tap. That itself is worth it.

reviewr_text: Two stars for being clean and well air conditioned.  Being Keto we ordered steak and shrimp and also the chicken bacon and cheese.  The steak we ordered as medium came a hare's breath from well done was tough and difficult to cut.  It came with vegetable medley which we were told they were out of and would be substituted with corn and carrots.  My chicken bacon cheese was served fajitas style, being on a keto diet I only ate the chicken bacon and cheese portion as it came with tortillas, cream cheese, bell pepper and lettuce.  Service was very lacking, 20 minutes for service water, no refills, no checking on us as we watched locals around us get that service.  It's a pity as Americans we tip based on service.

title: Maya Mexican Restaurant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Susan D."},{"reviewer_name":"Elee J."},{"reviewer_name":"Bobby L."},{"reviewer_name":"Verne A."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco F."},{"reviewer_name":"Jay H."},{"reviewer_name":"Randy H."},{"reviewer_name":"Becky C."},{"reviewer_name":"john b."},{"reviewer_name":"Jorge B."}]
reviewr_text:
First time in Cebu last month.  One of the things I search for when I'm on travel is - where is there Latin dancing?  Maya came up a few times, so it was bookmarked.  Surprisingly, while on the flight to Cebu, there was also an article in the inflight magazine highlighting this place.  So now you know my sole purpose was not the food, or drinks, but the dance...

Sunday night - Latin dance night, mainly salsa, bachata and kizomba.  Not sure about the classes, as I got there after 10:00 pm and there wasn't any... so if you plan to go for classes, maybe call in advance to confirm?  

Ambience/Decor - OMG, this place is just lovely!  I dragged my two teenage sons with me mainly for dinner, but also because I wasn't going to leave them in the hotel...  Anyhow - my older son was soooo impressed with the place!  Quite frankly, for restaurant/bar standards, it is a 5/5!  There are two levels.  Upstairs is the music/dance/restaurant, downstairs is a little more quiet for date night I guess

Food - Okay, okay... I live in Southern California where Mexican food is bountiful.  Unfortunately, this is the one place it lagged.  Food was alright, but it's hard to compete when I am used to authentic Mexican right around my neighborhood.  I would rate 3.5 stars.  Props though for trying.

Drinks - yes, I had the BOGO margarita.  It was so/so.  But can't pass up for the price. 

Service - Like the other Yelper mentioned, service is not something common or expected in much of the Philippines.  Including this place. 

Location - I believe it's in a little plaza called "Crossroads".  There is convenient parking.  But beware - there are plenty (and very enticing) other food choices in this joint.  However, since I came for the dance floor, I was satisfied.

title: Sisig Hooray Cebu
reviewr_text: Senorita's Sisig Bar is a mainstay at the Sugbo Mercado and although it be but a small booth among many, it be mighty! They were serving 5 different types of sisig on our visit -- the traditional pork, beef, chicken, squid, and "seafood". They have the skillets as you walk by, the aromas of brainy, meaty bits casually flowing out to passerby's. The bowl you receive could be considered "snack-sized" and at P90 for the traditional meats, with the seafood fluttering just above P100, this bowl is such a tasty bargain. I've never had beef sisig, so that's what I went for while my friend went for the pork. The beef did have extra pieces of veggies in it. Both meats were seasoned and marinated well, that prominent citrusy-sour flavor made possible by a heavy dose of calamansi. The meat wasn't extraordinary in size, nor was it crunchy or sizzling, but the combined ingredients -- along with the rice and gooey egg added on top -- made for a delicious bowl. While this bowl did fill us up, again, it does fit into the palm of my hand, so maybe that portion size could enable you to sample other delicacies from the many booths sprinkled throughout the mercado.

title: Tymad Bistro
reviewr_text:
I can't pass by this place without stopping by and getting some pastry or just a French baguette. Of cause, you have croissants any other French delicacies. 

The food is delicious as well, but the menu is limited to few dishes. 

There owner is French and I'd always there to personally greet you and just overlook the operations.

title: House of Lechon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]
reviewr_text:
It's overrated. I mean it was good, but nothing fantastic like everyone says it is.

It's a really nice establishment overall; nice dining area, service and ambience. We arrived after a long day of traveling, and this was the first and only place we wanted to try that night for dinner.

Special Carcar Lechon: very cute presentation with the wooden plate shaped like a pig. It was flavorful and nicely salted, the meat itself wasn't bad. The skin wasn't crispy like you'd expect, it was almost chewy? 

Grilled Tuna Belly: pretty good, really large portion and well seasoned! It's a very meaty fish, so make sure you and your friends have the stomach space to indulge in this.

Crispy Chicken Skin: not too memorable

Kinilaw Fiesta: nicely balanced dish in terms of salty/sweet/spicy.

I'd rather go to Rico's than House of Lechon if I were wanting really great Lechon.

title: Buffet 101
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Cha S."},{"reviewer_name":"Alvin K."},{"reviewer_name":"Wok Star X."},{"reviewer_name":"Rhoel P."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."}]

title: Cafe Bai
reviewr_text:
Reserved for a party of 6 for a lunch seating at 1 pm. A birthday celebration. Bai Hotel is located right off Ouano Ave. We pulled up and parked in the garage down below.

The buffet (Cafe Bai) is located on the 2nd floor. Once you get off and out the elevator, the receptionists are just ahead. We arrived about 12:30 to 12:45 and was told to take a seat. By now I'm thinking maybe it's packed. So we waited. 1 pm came and we were seated. Entering Cafe Bai, patrons were sparse. I suppose because it was lunch time?! Anywho we were seated in the far left back, right across their beverage station.

So off we went. I grabbed a plate and started browsing around. I first started with the roast beef, siomai, and pork belly. Roast beef tasted well, chewy but not dry.  Siomai was okay. The pork belly still had its crunch and it was seasoned similar to the lechons Carcar is known for. Tasted great! Second round, went back again for another helping of roast beef but this time stopped by the roasted chicken offering to pick up 2 spoon-full of roasted potatoes. Added some cheese and a dinner roll with some black olives. Walked passed the tempura and grabbed a few. Wife said that she noticed the shrimp tempura hidden behind the counter so she had to ask for some. Picked up some sushi as well. Meh. A little dry. I had to water down their lemonade as it was on the sweet side. Think lemonade concentrate, yeah, water it down. They also offered San Miguel beer on tap, coffee, tea, and some canned beverages found in various fridges around the dining area. For dessert, I had bread pudding and various other sweet desserts offered. They also had a halo halo station. Bread pudding was good only there was a skin-like texture which felt weird when eating. Vanilla sauce is available but no whiskey/bourbon/rum sauce that commonly accompanies bread pudding in the south (ie: Texas or Lousiana) *winks*

Staff: Staff was pleasant from the receptionists to the waiters and waitresses. Their birthday cheer was cool too. Great service. Asked a waiter and waitress to take a picture of us and they were very accommodating.

Restroom: Clean. Toilet bowls were tiny, like ones on an airplane. 

Overall: It is what you would expect from a hotel buffet, only this hotel offered more of an exceptional service than some of its competitors. Security guards bowed entering and exiting the hotel. I don't remember if there was free wifi, I forgot to check. Parking was free. It was a good experience, I left full. 

Tip: The person who made the reservation used the eatigo app to get a promo rate for the buffet. I believe the total bill came to be about 3,500 pesos excluding tip for 6 adults. I'm estimating.

title: Maya Mexican Restaurant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Susan D."},{"reviewer_name":"Elee J."},{"reviewer_name":"Bobby L."},{"reviewer_name":"Verne A."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco F."},{"reviewer_name":"Jay H."},{"reviewer_name":"Randy H."},{"reviewer_name":"Becky C."},{"reviewer_name":"john b."},{"reviewer_name":"Jorge B."}]
reviewr_text:
If you're in Cebu but are craving some authentic Mexican food, you should check out Maya.  It's in the Crossroads Mall on the south side of IT Park.  

I went there for the salsa dancing but stayed and had food and drinks, as well.  It was a fun night.  Maya even hires dance instructors so that you can dance a song or two, even if you didn't bring your own partner.  Very cool!

The music, food, drinks, and decor are on point... what more could you want?

See ya there (when I'm in Cebu).

title: Macaron Tango
reviewr_text: This place is kinda a neighborhood secret.  The owner is French and his food kinda had a homey feel to it. At the present time i think he has someone else do the baking, but the macarons still taste good. The ambiance is very low key but it gets the job done.

title: House of Lechon

title: Birdseed
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"John L."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Maya S."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Alan S."},{"reviewer_name":"Carl V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Rustum N."},{"reviewer_name":"Cha S."},{"reviewer_name":"ravi b."},{"reviewer_name":"Paula T."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris M."},{"reviewer_name":"Pablo G."}]
reviewr_text: Hollandaise sauce was made correctly with the right amount of lemon and butter. Egg was poached perfectly. They use salmon sashimi and the fish tasted fresh and the cut was thick. The "wilted" spinach was also cooked well. It wasn't overcooked. I also ordered the Long Black but was very turned off when I asked for a sugar substitute like Splenda or Equal, they tell me they have Stevia and offer it to me for P10 a packet. I thought that was ridiculous for a cafe. What coffee shop charges for sugar?! Will come back to try the other items. I hope they stay consistent.

title: Kaya
reviewr_text: This was the best Korean BBQ experience I've ever had in the Philippines and in the US! There's usually a wait but they move the line along pretty quick. We've ordered the beef and pork and both were delicious. They give you so much banchan as soon as you get seated that it's hard not to fill up on it before the meat arrives. They give you all kinds of pickled veggies along with your usual kim chi, pancake, chapchae, steam egg, soup - all are unlimited btw. There's someone that also cooks your food for you and when they notice you're running low on something, they're very quick to get you a refill. My brother and I joke and say you get Michelin Star level Service at very affordable prices. You definitely leave out of here with very satisfied bellies and you'll want to come back with friends!

title: Birdseed
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"John L."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Maya S."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Alan S."},{"reviewer_name":"Carl V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Rustum N."},{"reviewer_name":"Cha S."},{"reviewer_name":"ravi b."},{"reviewer_name":"Paula T."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris M."},{"reviewer_name":"Pablo G."}]
reviewr_text: I visited this place recently and the food and service was excellent from drinks to appetizers to the main course everything was exceptional. The staff is very friendly and the place itself is very unique and welcoming. I highly recommend the steak and the pesto chops, they are to die for. The chicken and waffles was also amazing. If you're ever in the area make sure to drop by, you won't regret it.

title: Shaka Hawaiian Restaurant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Tomoe S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kristine A."},{"reviewer_name":"Josh M."},{"reviewer_name":"Amy J."},{"reviewer_name":"Larry Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Biba M."}]
reviewr_text: Love the feel of this place, really feels like your in Hawaii! The food takes a bit long to come out but that's what the beer is for, and overall the foods good, not out of this world but it's really yummy. Only thing bad I have to say is that because it's outside it can get really hot and there's mosquitoes biting you, but if u wear bug spray u should be fine.

title: The Tinder Box
reviewr_text:
Came to this restaurant with a friend who is local.  She suggested this restaurant and deli as a good option for lunch and it did not fail.

The restaurant has a wine cellar with a deli next door.  There are television sets to watch a game, wifi connectivity for folks that want to catch up on work while having a drink or a meal.  The food options were interesting and I ordered the seafood paella.  The rest of the folks ordered other local dishes and sandwiches.  All the food tasted good.

Service was a bit slow and we had to call for service a couple of times.  Parking is available right outside and the security guard will help getting out on the road.

Pricing : Moderate

Will I return? : Maybe, when I am back in Cebu.

title: House of Lechon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]

title: Vikings
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Cha S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kimberly T."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco F."},{"reviewer_name":"Chi Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Scott G."},{"reviewer_name":"Samson C."},{"reviewer_name":"Lizell L."},{"reviewer_name":"Mac H."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael W."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Alvin K."},{"reviewer_name":"Chato M."}]
reviewr_text:
Vikings is located inside SM City Mall Cebu on the second floor by Forever 21. We initially called to reserve a table but they stated they were fully booked but they also accept walk-in guests. So we headed out and arrived about 7-ish pm. We approached the host and they gave us a number. We glanced up at the number being served.. 35 then looked at our number, 71. We decided to wait and it wasn't really a bad wait either. About an hour later our number was called.

We were a party of seven and we were seated near the meat carving area. Upon entering the restaurant it took me back to the time we went to Las Vegas and their buffets at the casino resorts there. It had the same ambiance with about the same amount of customers with friendly waiters and waitresses, quick too, if I may add. I took a walk around to see what they offered. A good variety ranging from Chinese, Filipino, American, Spanish, Japanese, Italian, a salad area, and desserts galore. I decided I would have a go at the meat carving station, ordered a steak at medium well, a portion of chicken and tasted some lamb too. Both the steak and lamb were a bit chewy but seasoned well. The chicken was good. I had mashed potatoes for my side on my first plate and added some garlic sauce on top. Just right for me! mmm. They have a beverage section where you can try out different flavored agua frescas, san miguel beer on tap and you can also get Heineken in a bottle neck. I believe they also offered wine, coffee, and tea.

Dessert ranged from ice cream to rice pudding, churos, small bite sized cakes, fruit salad, and bread pudding with a choice of chocolate or vanilla syrup. The bread pudding was soo good I went back twice. 

Price for dinner: 838 pesos per person
Birthday celebrant is complimentary with other paying adults in your party present. Must bring I.D.

Overall, I will frequent this buffet for special occasions. They have one of the best promotions, price is just right for the variety and quality of food that they offer. Service was great as well!

title: Maya Mexican Restaurant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Susan D."},{"reviewer_name":"Elee J."},{"reviewer_name":"Bobby L."},{"reviewer_name":"Verne A."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco F."},{"reviewer_name":"Jay H."},{"reviewer_name":"Randy H."},{"reviewer_name":"Becky C."},{"reviewer_name":"john b."},{"reviewer_name":"Jorge B."}]
reviewr_text:
Maya is a great place to enjoy a night out with friends. They have great Mexican food and the best mojitos in town. And if you drink there during their weekly Moijto Night, you can order the drink buy one, take one.

They also have Salsa Nights for those who love dancing! Very popular among tourists. 

Highly recommended, along with Phat Pho, Abaca Baking Co., and La Marea (for dining) and Craft Story and HOLICOW (for souvenir shopping).

title: Zubuchon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Jacques I."},{"reviewer_name":"Tellie N."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Ron Z."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Lillian C."},{"reviewer_name":"Linda P."},{"reviewer_name":"Benjamin C."},{"reviewer_name":"Cris T."},{"reviewer_name":"David L."},{"reviewer_name":"Kathrine P."},{"reviewer_name":"John A."},{"reviewer_name":"Barry T."},{"reviewer_name":"Aileen B."},{"reviewer_name":"Angeli Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Ian Maren C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Geoffrey U."}]
reviewr_text:
Zubuchon became popular because of celebrity chef, Anthony Bourdain. A pork lover, when he visited the Philippines, he had to try 2 very important Pinoy dishes: Sisig and Lechon (Roasted Pig). His hosts served him Zubuchon Lechon and, after eating the best parts of the pig, said his famous line: "Best pig...ever!" Of course, that sealed the deal for Zubuchon and everyone wanted a taste of their lechon. So, when I visited Cebu for the first time in 10 years, this was one of the first restaurants I had to try! :) 

Before I ate at Zubuchon, my Cebuano friends recommended other lechon places like CnT or Rico's Lechon. For me, I think Zubuchon's lechon is Excellent! The first time I had Zubuchon, it was during the pig delivery time. I swear, the smell of that pig made me drool! I ordered a 1/2 kilo and ate every piece of meat and skin on the plate (Please look at the photo I took. Gone in 10 minutes. It was worth it!). Meat is very tasty and not too salty (which I prefer) without the need for lechon sarsa (liver gravy). In Cebu, they prefer to dip the lechon meat in spicy vinegar. Apart from lechon, they also serve Cebuano dishes. I recommend that you pair your lechon with an order of their Seaweed Platter, Sizzling Squid Stuffed with Sisig, Five Pork Fried Rice and, for your drink, try their Kamias Shake!

Yes, there are many different lechon places in Cebu and everyone will have their favorites. For me, it's not only about the lechon. I also love Zubuchon because the restaurant is very clean and the service is fast plus you don't need to line up to get your plate of lechon. For first time travelers to Cebu, I would definitely recommend that you eat here! :)

title: Cafe Bai
reviewr_text: Staying in Cebu at Bai Hotel where we found their buffet..the employees, the hotel, the buffet are all better than any Vegas hotels or buffets! Lots of food selections from around the world...with salads, entrees, deserts, ice creams and coffees...this place is outstanding!

title: Jollibee
reviewr_text: This place is what McDonalds is to the United States. The most popular items are chicken joy which is fried chicken, aloha burger for the burger enthusiast, and peach mango pie for the sweet tooth.

title: Veranda Restobar
reviewr_text: Across from our hotel in a shopping Mall. For 6 dishes including steamed garlic rice, the total bill was US$34. We can live and eat like a king here in Cebu. All the dishes were great except for the beef tapas, which was so so. If u there, hv the steamed garlic rice instead of the plain one.

title: Anzani
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Bobby L."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Katherine O."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Scott G."},{"reviewer_name":"Cathy M."},{"reviewer_name":"Kartik K."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael W."}]
reviewr_text: Trendy upscale restaurant.  Outdoor seating overlooks a valley, but the chairs aren't suitable for dining. Best to start with drinks outside, then move inside for the full meal. Had osso buco, kalbi ribs and porcini risotto.  All were outstanding.  Bottle of Columbia Valley wine completed a great meal. A little over $100 for two. Typical of you would expect to pay at one of the best restaurants.  Great date spot.

title: Kuya J's Restaurant
reviewr_text:
Turn around and go to a different restaurant. 

This restaurant is at the Ayala Terraces, across from the Ayala Mall. 

The service here is very very very slow.  I had to constantly get up to get a waiter because They weren't even paying attention to me waiving at them.  I've been to other Kuya J's restaurants and was never dissatisfied.  I was so disappointed that I wanted to walk out immediately when I got my food.  I was even being patient when it took forever to order my food and get drinks.  I was there for 2 hours and I only ordered Pinakbet, steamed bangus and the seafood platter.  Which by the way never get the seafood platter.  It's a waste of money.  They use small shrimp that they even cut up in pieces. It was like four tablespoons of mixed chopped up seafood in a platter.  I now wish I had taken a picture. I paid $900 for crappy food and crappy service.

The restaurant was half full.

title: Casa Verde
reviewr_text:
So I saw this chain pop up numerous times on my search of things to eat in Cebu, Philippines.  So when leaving the mall I was intrigued to stop there for lunch.  Oh the disappointment.

Food:  Everyone swore that the Brian's Ribs were the thing to get here.  It was even marked on the menu as a top seller.  So I decided to give it a try, along with calamari.  I was disappointed in both items.  The ribs were fall off the bone which was great; however, they were full of fat.  Sooooo much fat that I'm almost positive that it was more fat than meat on my plate. The calamari was super rubbery and tough to eat.  I definitely didn't choose correctly when ordering both of these items.  I also ordered a strawberry daiquiri, which was decent but not the best I've ever had.  Decent for the price.

Service:  Typical service that I experienced in the Philippines.  You have to call a waiter over because they won't come automatically.  Additionally, all of my food came at once even tho i ordered an appetizer first then an entree.

I wasn't impressed and wouldn't return unless it was a super happy hour special.

title: Jollibee
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Naomi O."},{"reviewer_name":"Shaima C."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Yochanan H."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Travis M."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."}]
reviewr_text:
When in the Philippines , one must try jollibee!
This place is always packed, adults, kids, and students are always stopping in to get a quick bite. 
My friend and I ended up getting the classic burger and the chicken with gravy and rice.

The burger was interesting, it had a lot of sauce. Kind of reminded  me of a McDonald's burger tbh.

The friend chicken and gravy were good! I can see why people enjoy eating it with rice. The chicken was nice and crisp, and the gravy gave just made it better.

title: Zubuchon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Jacques I."},{"reviewer_name":"Tellie N."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Ron Z."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Lillian C."},{"reviewer_name":"Linda P."},{"reviewer_name":"Benjamin C."},{"reviewer_name":"Cris T."},{"reviewer_name":"David L."},{"reviewer_name":"Kathrine P."},{"reviewer_name":"John A."},{"reviewer_name":"Barry T."},{"reviewer_name":"Aileen B."},{"reviewer_name":"Angeli Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Ian Maren C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Geoffrey U."}]
reviewr_text:
Thank God for Zubuchon. If not for them, I may not have gotten my Cebu Lechon fix while I was in Cebu. Contrary to my girth, I am not that heavy of an eater, so finding a lechon joint that had single servings of lechon was a literal godsend. 

It also helped that this branch was at Cebu IT Park, a gorgeous city center if I ever saw one. Cebu IT Center reminds me of a circa-2000s BGC or Filinvest City with prettier buildings.

As for the lechon, yes it was yummy, although it felt a bit too oily for my liking. That kamias shake was the bomb, though.

title: Soba Kamakura
reviewr_text:
On my visit back to Cebu I finally decided to make a reservation and try the restaurant out with my bestfriend. She says they've since expanded, but the restaurant still seats around 10 persons. The place is a little hard to find if you aren't with someone who is familiar with the area. 

Due to dietary restrictions I cannot consume raw food & seafood. That left me with the choice of the beef soba, and a side order of the tofu, topped with what they claim as "land caviar" (it is vegetarian). The food is very flavorful yet light. Truly highlights the freshness and quality of ingredients used. 

I also like that you didn't have to touch anything in the restroom - much of it has motion detection, including the toilet bowl. 

Beautiful interiors, excellent dishes and a quick journey to Hokkaido with Soba Kamakura!

title: Nonki Japanese Restaurant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Felix A."},{"reviewer_name":"Christine C."},{"reviewer_name":"Rocky Betty Jo P."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris M."}]
reviewr_text: I loved to eat here during my two week stay in Cebu.  I tried many of the rolls and was pleased with all.  Service is good and the food was all tasty!  Try the tofu!

title: Dimsum Express
reviewr_text: Dimsum Express does not leave up to its name. Everything needs 10-15 minutes to get served! They should just remove Ecpress from their business name because it's misleading! If you're super hungry don't make the mistake of eating here because you'll surely starve before getting served your food.

title: House of Lechon

title: Lunhaw Vegan Cafe
reviewr_text:
Finally a vegan cafe in Cebu.  Of course I had to check it out to see what they served.  Had the vegan Sisig which is made up of mushrooms and tofu with peanut sauce.  There's also green chilli peppers so be careful cus they're pretty hot.  I like the sweetness of the sisig.

My friend had the garden pizza and it reminded me of Mamas pizza on the street as a kid which was a score cus I love mamas pizza.

Definitely coming back to try the rest of the began dishes especially their air fries which they air fry.  Totally curious about that.

title: House of Lechon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]

title: McDonald's
reviewr_text:
Curiosity.  Curiosity is what caused me to drop by this McDonalds at Ayala Center.   I was curious to find out if the little cheeseburgers I liked in the U.S. would be as tasty in the Philippines.   

Had to wait for awhile to find out cause they were super busy.  There was a section for placing Take Out orders, and a section for Dine in orders.  Both were swamped with people.  Line went fairly quick.   Ordered my Cheeseburger plus fries and drink for 119 Philippine Pesos (a little over $2 USD).   

Cheeseburger tasted just the way I like it in the States.  Fries also had the same yummy taste.  There are a bunch of other goodies on their menu that are not found in the U.S.  I might be back to try some of them before we leave Cebu.

title: Phat Pho
reviewr_text: Our first time here last week. The soup was too salty. Hope u guys do better. We ordered special pho and I was feeling sick and crave for some pho I couldn't eat it because it was too salty :(.

title: Yolk
reviewr_text:
This is my favorite breakfast place in all of Cebu. Both the coffee and the drinks are delicious, and the service is impeccable. 

The place itself is a cozy little cafe that caters to big and small groups alike, without sacrificing its laid-back and relaxed vibe. It's very well lit and the music isn't too loud, making it conducive for work or study. 

For food I highly recommend the chorizo and eggs in a pan, or any of their silogs. Their silogs are a bit pricier than your typical ones, but trust me, it's definitely worth it. For the full experience, pair your breakfast with coffee. I usually get the pour-over coffee, but their other coffees are also amazing.

If you're in Cebu for just a few days, and you wanted to have a great breakfast out, I highly recommend you check out Yolk!

title: Isla Sugbo Seafood City

title: Sunburst
reviewr_text:
Whenever we travel back to Cebu, there is always one restaurant chain that I have to visit.   Sunburst Fried Chicken is the place!!  To my delight, there was this branch of Sunburst at Robinsons Galleria Mall.

They have both indoor and outdoor seating available.  We chose to eat indoors.  I ordered my favorite item Chick'n Cracker or as I like to call them Chicken Skins!!  I love the yummy crispiness of the chicken skins dipped in banana catsup!!  Had it with some tasty Lomi.

The meal did not disappoint.  Wish they had Sunburst Fried Chicken in the States.  Cebu is a long way to travel in order to satisfy my chicken skin cravings.

title: Nonki Japanese Restaurant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Felix A."},{"reviewer_name":"Christine C."},{"reviewer_name":"Rocky Betty Jo P."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris M."}]

title: Surfin' Ribs
reviewr_text:
I used to love the ribs spicy paired with rice but this time, the ribs was burnt. Be sure to tell the crew not to burn your ribs. Service here is really fast! So if you're running late, this is one of the best place to dine! 

However, only two stars because the place is awful. We used to eat at surfin' ribs near Ayala but its now closed. When I saw they have another branch here I was happy but the place sucks. If you want to dine inside it lacks ventilation so the smell of food would stick on your clothes. Also, if you dine outside, you'll be accompanied by flies later on and its not that kinda fresh air because smokers are also outside. Lastly, i was surprised that my plate was served cold. Like how? Not coming back here again.

title: Tony G's Foodcourt by Ned Nanay's Grill
reviewr_text: The name is very long for a short order place. Its street food and it looks like a neighborhood favorite. Don't be suprised if you get a plastic glove to eat your food, i guess thats the fancy way as opposed to eating without a glove. Its basic filipino bbq and it gets the job done.

title: Maco Manok Litson Native Chicken
reviewr_text: If you want good native chicken and exceptional roast beef then maco Manok is the place to be.  Also their garlic rice is off the hook and it's definitely authentic filipino food.  A must try if you're in Cebu.

title: Cebu's Original Lechon Belly
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jefferson S."},{"reviewer_name":"Abbys A."},{"reviewer_name":"Gio G."},{"reviewer_name":"Gil M."},{"reviewer_name":"Anneke D."},{"reviewer_name":"Barry T."},{"reviewer_name":"Maputing E."},{"reviewer_name":"Mike M."},{"reviewer_name":"Swan L."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."}]
reviewr_text:
Having been to the Philippines and now Cebu on a number of occasions, my hosts decided that it was time I try lechon (boneless pork belly--a Cebu specialty).

It looks like a fast food joint, with few tables and hard booths--and an outpost downstairs where you can eat on stools outside, facing the parking lot of the Time Square complex. On the menu: lechon, lechon, lechon. And bottomless servings of rice.

Like a fast food place, it's served quickly from behind a counter, and with disposable packaging: straw "plates" on which to place your round wax paper cut-out and, oddly, plastic gloves. Lechon, which is traditionally eaten with bare hands, left workers' fingers greasy after lunch breaks so, following complaints, the restaurant decided to issue thin gloves to its customers. Many of the locals in the restaurant (not on their lunch break, and with their families) decided to forego the gloves. We, seriously considering a karaoke night afterwards, decided to use them.

The issue with the gloves is that, once you've helped yourself to rice (steamed and served in woven banana leaf pods) and that scrumptiously greasy lechon (I wasn't a fan of the skin and thick layer of fat that came with each piece, but even if you avoid those it gets oily), your gloves lose all manner of grip and you have trouble opening your subsequent rice pods.

Logistics aside, the lechon was an experience and the restaurant fine, but I wouldn't be in a hurry to go back. Instead, I'd spend more time at AA BBQ: goo.gl/bgeKOo

title: Blue Elephant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"PatrickJ T."},{"reviewer_name":"Clydelle M."},{"reviewer_name":"Arnel E."},{"reviewer_name":"Dexter V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sandrine G."},{"reviewer_name":"Steve F."},{"reviewer_name":"PGreg H."},{"reviewer_name":"Dee S."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]

title: Anzani
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Bobby L."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Katherine O."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Scott G."},{"reviewer_name":"Cathy M."},{"reviewer_name":"Kartik K."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael W."}]
reviewr_text:
My higher score is most definitely for the ambience of this place! When I lived in Cebu, my friends and I  met once a week here for drinks, sunset, and dinner. We always sit outside on the plush lounge couches for a great view of the hills. It's pretty hot here, still though, so be prepared for that- and for the mosquitoes that don't really lessen up until about an hour after sunset (I do wish the restaurant could do something a little more about that). 

Usually, we would sit outside in the Anzani area and grab a menu from Bellini's as well because their menu is a little bit cheaper (You can order from either restaurant). Make sure to ask for the bread pots because they usually don't give to you unless you ask- they're actually super delicious. 

It's of course, very pricey, but very delicious and obviously, one of my favorite views in Cebu!

title: Osaka Takoyaki
reviewr_text:
I first spotted this outfit at a japanese festival held at srp. The line was riduculosly long throughout the whole day so never got a chance to give it a try.
I've been wanting to go to Japan, but unfortunately, I am unable to go at this time. So to compensate, I've been visitonf alot of Japanese restaurants lately.
I did notice that they had a spot at island central mall on mactan and would now be . opening. 
Build it and I will try it, sure enough the SM seaside location is open and I'm here on the first day.
Of course I had to try the Osaka takoyaki and their tonkatsu. I even ordered dessert.
First impressions, the broth and ramen of the tonkatsu was flavorful and nice texture of the ramen. The takoyaki was delicious on par with sachi which I also consider to have good takoyaki.
The anti climax was the dessert, I ordered the green tea ice shave. Presentation was not so great, I could not taste the green tea as it was overpowered by sugar and condensed milk.
However overall a great experience, I would come back again to try other dishes such as the yakisoba.

title: Cafe Laguna
reviewr_text: Came here for lunch while on vacation here in the Philippines. The food here is fantastic. I had some lechon kawali and some lengua estofado (braised ox tongue). So tender so good. I'll be back before I leave.

title: Chicken Deli
reviewr_text: This is a bacolod based barbecue. chicken joint. The leader and originator is mang inasal which is very popular and always busy. This place seems to be ok, but for a place to be new and have flies inside seems to be a turn off. The positive is since the place is not busy the chicken is served hot unlike most mang inadal places where they have ovens warm the food to keep up with the customers.

title: Puso Bistro and Bar
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jessica S."},{"reviewer_name":"Sivilay T."},{"reviewer_name":"Cha S."},{"reviewer_name":"Ian Jude F."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."}]
reviewr_text:
We arrived about 6:15 pm and took a peek to see what the buffet offered. At quick glance, roasted pig, BBQ, sushi, cook to order sinigang (filipino sour soup), sashimi etc. We decided to have a go at it as we were celebrating a birthday in our group. 

The buffet had a juice station that had 3 varieties (orange juice, dalandan, and I forgot the 3rd kind) to choose from. I opted to try dalandan as I never had dalandan juice before. I took a few sips and strangely an odd after taste became apparent. I had my wife taste it as she said she's had dalandam juice before and she immediately said, "don't drink that anymore. Either the cup is dirty or the water they use has an odor." eeeek!! So I ended sticking to water (which didn't have any noticable odors or strange tastes, so maybe it was the cup?!). *gasps*

Now for the food. Cold, cold, and cold. I browsed around and cherry picked what they offered and sadly everything was cold. My dad ordered a shwarma with fries and it was cold, almost frozen. The sushi wasn't fresh. The rice was almost crispy like. Tuna sashimi didn't taste that great, seemed like it came from laying on ice then transferred on a serving plate but then left to fend for itself. What was meant to be hot was cold and what was meant to be cold was luke warm. The receptionist indicated that they opened at 6 PM for dinner, but all the food seemed as if its been left out for quite sometime. I expected the food thats intended to be hot would be piping hot as they did just open. Unfortunately not. Now I will say I was a big fan of their sinigang. Just the right tartness and super hot. We ordered a plate of bam-i which is like two types of noodles stir fryed. It was super salty. Their roasted pig tasted alright but you can tell its been sitting there for awhile as its gotten super dry, almost like a leather look. The BBQ was cold which was a huge turn off. The food was either dry, cold, warm or not fresh at all. I bypassed the salad bar as I noticed a fly just cruising through their leafy offerings. They had what appeared to be pastrami but when I tasted it, it was super spongy and dripped wet. *yuck*

For dessert, they had a variety of offerings but mostly local fare. I tasted the bread pudding and it was super dry, no sauce for it. Ice cream was pretty good and toppings can be found towards the salad bar. They offered conchenta (a brown jelly like dessert topped with coconut shavings), a casava dessert with caramalized coconut strands, chocolate fountain (but the liquid didn't look like chocolate, had a pink color), and small cake cuts normally found in average chinese buffets in the States. They also had a crepe station.

Staff: When we first were seated I got the feeling as if the person putting water in our glass was not ready to be bothered with. He didn't say anything and seemes to just want to get his duties over with. The rest of the evening waiters were attentive and kept making sure the cups were filled with water. Totally different attitude from the original guy who first filled our cups. I did mention to a lady, whom appeared to be a manager, that the dalandan juice tasted funny and that I will only be having water for my drink. She just stared at me and didn't say anything. *shrugs* It also appeared that they may lack in food prep staff as there were scarcely any attendants at the "cook to order" stations. 

As mentioned in the title, the restaurant itself was beautiful and nicely layed out (floor seemed to be newly mopped but no caution signs, so tread carefully). We didn't come here to observe the decorations. We came here to eat. Unfortunately, I was disappointed at the quality of the food that was offered.  I'm not sure if they had free wifi, I didn't have time to check. Birthday celebrants are free (with i.d. and given a slice of cake, thank you) and each adult was 850 pesos. We were told senior citizens also get a discount (with i.d.). Free parking.

title: Casa Verde
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jay K."},{"reviewer_name":"Thunder H."},{"reviewer_name":"Joe T."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Ray J."},{"reviewer_name":"Dale E."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheika G."},{"reviewer_name":"Jodie S."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text: Giving them 4 stars because through out the years, I feel like the service and food has been declining in quality. The waiting time is ridiculous when its weekends and dinner time (even on weekdays). The portions are huge and they're still affordable so 4 stars for them.

title: Sweet Little Things
reviewr_text:
Who doesn't like sweet little things?  At Ayala Center inside Rustans Supermarket, there is a little spot called Sweet Little Things.  They have one display case filled with beautiful looking cookies, cupcakes, and cakes.  So hard to resist these beauties.

My wife tried their Mango Float Brownie a' la mode.  It tasted decent to me.  We ordered 3 cupcakes.  The Ube cupcake was good.  My niece really liked the Lemon Poppyseed cupcake.  The Dark Mud Pie cupcake was good too.  The cupcakes were a bit dry, but the icing for each helped balance the dryness of the cake portions. 

It was good to try Sweet Little Things.  Might be a regular if I lived in the condos close by.

title: Lai Garden
reviewr_text: Not good. Expensive yet food is meh. Don't even try to eat here. You'll waste money. Try Chowking instead. You've been warned.

title: Acacia Steakhouse
reviewr_text:
My friend really wanted to try this place out. I was worried about the quality of steak, however it didn't disappoint. Ordered several different cuts and types of meet.

Be prepared for cute stray cats  asking for food under the table. They do accept card, and have a good breeze fan outdoors for warm nights.

Wish I could've taken pics but I was starving and destroyed my plate upping arrival of my presence.

Awesome for friends or a date.

title: Kuya J's Restaurant
reviewr_text:
Kuya J was one of the MUST EAT recommendations of our hotel and friends. I think it's been one of Cebu's little dining secrets for the longest time. But, now, I'm seeing more branches opening in Manila.

This branch was one of the original restaurants. It didn't seem like much from the outside. Once you enter, the place is very clean and has modern interiors. You have 2 choices where to dine: the air-conditioned area and the al fresco area. We stayed in the air-conditioned area because it was hot that day.

Kuya J serves Filipino dishes such kare kare, crispy pata, and pochero. If I were you, skip all the meat and go straight for the Grilled Scallops! This is the best-seller and most popular appetizer. It's a simple dish actually. Scallops are topped with cheese and BUTTER then grilled. Served hot and fast, it only costs Php210 (4.51USD) per plate. We ended up ordering 3 plates. LOL! Other dishes you should try: Chorizo Dinamitas (chilis stuffed with chorizo meat), Lumpia Presko, and, for dessert, Tablea Flan with Coffee Syrup (chocolate flan with coffee caramel). Also, try their Dalandan Beer :)

Overall, it was a pleasant surprise and we enjoyed our meal (even though it was mostly the Scallops!). If you're in Cebu, you should eat here! :)

title: Washoku J
reviewr_text:
Very bad experience at this restaurant.  Came here during Good Friday since this was one of the restaurants that was open.

Our food took more than an hour to cook and their vegetable roll was a rip off.  We had to follow up so many times to make sure we get the rest of the food.

Would never come back here again.

title: Tsay Cheng
reviewr_text: First impressions, one of the best formal chinese restauranta Ive been to. they had a fried chicken dish with kropek that was close to the same dish i had in new york city chinatown. The pata tim and other dishes wrre on par for a nice restaurant like this.

title: Birdseed
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"John L."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Maya S."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Alan S."},{"reviewer_name":"Carl V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Rustum N."},{"reviewer_name":"Cha S."},{"reviewer_name":"ravi b."},{"reviewer_name":"Paula T."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris M."},{"reviewer_name":"Pablo G."}]
reviewr_text: We tried this place on a whim and loved it!!!! The food was delicious and the coffee  was smoooooth. The staff was very attentive and friendly. Will

title: La Vie in the Sky
reviewr_text:
Warning : if you come here late night, Grab will not show up all the way up the hill. So either bring a car or ask for a ride down the hill from someone in the bar.

This is a French theme joint. Pay a 10 peso entrance fee. 

Great wine selection, very fruity wine. If you don't like alcohol they serve some house wine that practically taste like strawberry soda. Some good food, with plenty of ice cream.

You can also walk up a bit higher and see the top of cebu. Relax and have another drink at different bars. Overall a good experience  to be with friends or chat up a date.

title: Parilya
reviewr_text:
After seeing reviews and photos of Parilya, I knew that we had to go and try it out before leaving Cebu a few months ago. I was a bit worried that the place would be packed, but thankfully, that wasn't the case - it may be either because the place was very new at the time, it was a week day, and the fact that it's quite far from the city. Or a combination of some of those things lol.

We ordered halo-halo, baked scallops, sukwate, calamares, soup (can't remember which one), and turon.

I only got to try the baked scallops and calamares. I like how cheesy the baked scallops were, but I wasn't satisfied with their calamares - it wasn't really that crunchy which was a bit of a let down for me.

The place was great. Initially, we sat outside but there seemed to be a lot of flies there so we transferred inside - anyway, from our table we could see the same view. Service was alright too. Prices are a bit on the high side.

title: Off Roads Cafe
reviewr_text:
Dined here early morning as soon as the restaurant opened on a weekday. Cheap and quite convenient spot to dine in or takeaway. I personally didn't have a problem with my food but my friend had with his silog. With just one human hair, all hell broke loose and for that there's no going back... Firstly, the cornsilog seemed old and to his demise, found a long black hair in the cornbeef! Yikes! I finished my food (tocilog) with no errs and my black coffee...

But! I'll give them credit for my breakfast (although very small portioned) and for the fact that they have wifi to work with without asking for a password. The CR was clean too. Ladies were polite as well and handled the situation in a calm matter whether it was because they didn't know how to relieve the mishap or whatever the case was.

title: House of Lechon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]

title: Red House Shabu Shabu
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Colby W."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Thomas K."},{"reviewer_name":"Angela L."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text:
The sizes are big and the variety is excellent. I make sure to go here every time I'm in Cebu. Make sure to get some chopped chilis and garlic from the center table, they really kick up the flavor. 

This place can be a little hard to find as its on a small road off the main road. Every taxi I've taken here has gotten lost or drove around in circles trying to find it. But persevere, it's worth it.

title: Sunburst
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Britt H."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Nina M."},{"reviewer_name":"Stewart O."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."}]
reviewr_text:
One of the best chicken places I've ever been to! So tender and juicy. Skin was crisp- just the way it should be. Didn't care for the sides but their chicken is everything! 

Other entrees were good so no complaints there. They were out of a few of the choices at the time and it wasn't even near closing time. 

Still, can't stop raving about that chicken.

title: Anzani
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Bobby L."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Katherine O."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Scott G."},{"reviewer_name":"Cathy M."},{"reviewer_name":"Kartik K."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael W."}]
reviewr_text: The restaurant is situated at picturesque spot in Cebu, it's on the hill side looking at the valley. The patio seating is best option. The food is Mediterranean  and Italian. Though restaurant claims to be Mediterranean it's menu is skewed towards being more Italian. They have great selection of whisky' and wines, the menu is a digital tablet with almost 15/20 sections. They have options of 2-4 course menu meals or a la carte. A la carte is recommended. Their soups are excellent and so is Australian beef carpaccio. The pastas for main course with fresh cheese will keep your Italian loving  guests happy.  The Service matches the price and ambiance.  This restaurant was started by chef anzani and his chef wife. They also own gusto restaurant  in IT park in Cebu and chefs were at Shangri-La before starting anzani. If you are looking for great experience for you  and your guests, you won't go wrong with this spot.

title: Tim Ho Wan
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Marissa S."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Cynthia Q."},{"reviewer_name":"Tracy N."},{"reviewer_name":"Ray J."}]

title: Puso Bistro and Bar
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jessica S."},{"reviewer_name":"Sivilay T."},{"reviewer_name":"Cha S."},{"reviewer_name":"Ian Jude F."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."}]
reviewr_text:
There is a lot of buffet competition in the area. However, this place has competitive pricing especially when they have promotions.
During breakfast time, they are known for the good tasting bacom and for dinner they recently had turkey and beef for the thanksgiving theme.

title: Yakimix
reviewr_text:
I went here with my friends for dinner on Friday, because we didn't make a reservation so we had to wait around an hour to get in. So if you want to eat here, make sure you have a reservation before you come, especially at the weekend. 
 The price is reasonable, staffs are friendly and sing so well (coz they will sing happy birthday song to you if it's your birthday) food is okay, some dishes are too sweet. Anyways, i think this restaurant is the best restaurant that i have been in Cebu so far.

title: Banri Noodle House
reviewr_text: good japanese food right below our BnB. It was better than expected! The service was great and it wasn't too crowded. Would definitely recommend this place. especially for people staying at the BnB above it.

title: House of Lechon

title: Isla Sugbo Seafood City
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"David P."},{"reviewer_name":"Gregory C."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Danie S."},{"reviewer_name":"Erica V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Jennelle L."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Jo Anne G."},{"reviewer_name":"Laura A."},{"reviewer_name":"Rocky Betty Jo P."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco F."}]
reviewr_text:
Amazing. You choose from the freshest of live seafood  The waiter serves you. Not just bring your food, but will prepare soup for everyone, crack your crabs, bring around the dishes to serve your party one by one. Literally, everything was amazing. 

Also, the bathrooms are clean and offer toilet paper, lol.

Glad I got to try this place!

reviewr_text:
I was so excited to go here an check out the place. Everyone seems so hyped about this place so i made a reservation.
We had the 6-course menu, it was okay.
The restaurant needs some minor repairs and staff needs to know some etiquette-- shouldn't use a chipped plate. There were no paper towels available in the bathroom, bathroom door is broken and the water from the sink won't close properly (waste of water).

title: Laguna Garden Cafe
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Kimberly T."},{"reviewer_name":"PatrickJ T."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Ken S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Sherwin T."},{"reviewer_name":"Andrew M."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text:
Best Filipino food I tried so far! No matter what you order, it is done to perfection. Lapu-lapu fish, crispy pata or just kinilaw tanigue - all is delicious. I strongly recommend it to all visitors to Cebu.

And one of the most fairly priced restaurants in Ayala. The portions are big and good for 2-3 people to share.

And of cause, the service. The waiters are knowledgeable about the menu, fast to serve the food and rarely missing items from the menu.

title: House of Lechon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]
reviewr_text:
Cebu is known to have the best Lechon in the Philippines.  When you enter The House of Lechon there is a large room where the Lechon is prepared.  There is a large stainless steel counter & glass ceiling to counter where about 3 or 4 guys prepare the Lechon to be served.  They take the crispy skin and scrape the fat off the back so you end up with a nice crispy skin with almost no fat on on the back.  It's absolutely delicious.  The meat is fairly lean and seasoned to perfection.  Lechon 5 Stars
Salmon sinagong - this dish was tasty, but too salty for my palate. Salmon Sinagong 3 Stars because of too much salt
Pansit Guisado was absolutely delicious 5 Stars
Scallops w/melted cheese.  The picture looked good, but they sucked.  There was one tiny little scallop covered w/melted cheese.  Way too salty I would recommend against getting this item.  1 Star - Pricy and not very good.  
Calamansi juice was absolutely delicious with a nice citrus after bite.  Yummm I want some more now.  5 Stars

The dining area is very nice, good service.  It was funny watching people after eating sitting back and just enjoying the moment of a great meal
