title: The Pyramid
reviewr_text: As soon as we arrived our orders were taken by the server. Ordered Beer and it was served after 30mins. The manager told us the turn around service is 35mins. Including drinks? Seriously? After 30mins we were told Chicken Wings is out already...  and we were told that the list of our orders was lost. Very disappointed

title: Domings Ngohiong
reviewr_text: Still one of the best ngohiongs in Cebu. The place is always packed especially during lunch hours and even on a weekend. Don't expect the place to be a fancy schmancy restaurant. This place is located right in their house. If you don't mind that, then be prepared for one of the best meals of your life! Simply delicous! I've been coming back here lots of times already and they have always been consistent. Order a few puso (hanging rice) and a bottle of soda and you're good to go.

reviewr_text:
Not the best food. The Pad Thai was both vinegar tasting and fishy. My friend ordered the Pha Ga and enjoyed it. 

Came in a second time for lunch and was seated near the kitchen. Sat for 10 minutes waiting for someone to take my order with an empty restaurant. I walked out.

title: Ramen Kamekichi
reviewr_text: A little bit off the beaten path, but they do have parking and a spacious interior. The ambiance is also nice. On a budget so went with the tongkotsu chasumen P378, which they say is an upgrade since it had more pork slices. I like the broth, tastes more natural compared to most though not as creamy, the lack of egg? The noodles seem to be ordinary. The service attention needs work but they have sign they are in "dry run". Overall its a place to go to if you want to take a break from the mall.

title: Luzern Steakhouse
reviewr_text:
Had our Valentine's dinner here. We weren't able to make reservations but fortunately the waitress made a way and find us some chairs and tables. 

They had imported beef from US. We tried the rib-eye, wagU, and pork steak. It was all delicious. The sauce however was too spicy. 

The staff was a little busy and strict tonight maybe because they were many customers because it's Valentines.

They also have other menu and some are cheaper. The imported meats however were more expensive.

title: Washoku J
reviewr_text: This adorable restaurant is very authentic. The zaru soba is well presented and delicate. The side of tempura shrimp I thought was also very great (the batter seemed thicker than most in the USA but not in a bad way) and the cold tofu was clean and sauce was delicious. Definitely a highlight is the lotus root. It was boiled enough to remove all starchy taste yet not too soft. You can also buy some beautiful Japanese ceramics here!

title: The Pig & Palm
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Tricie C."},{"reviewer_name":"Jacob C."},{"reviewer_name":"Kevin G."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Daniel S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kristine S."},{"reviewer_name":"Carl I."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Dan P."},{"reviewer_name":"Cynthia Q."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text: The Pig and Palm. This restaurant is one of the very few establishments that offers casual refined dining in Cebu City. Service is amazing (waiters and the staff are quite attentive to your every need), food is quite well rounded and reasonably priced compared to other Michelin star rated establishments that I've been to (Paris, London, Napa Valley, Italy, etc). The owners are  nice and are always quite welcoming.  Ambiance is quite awesome. It has the feel of a London establishment  with its the dim lights and brick walls. Overall The Pig and Palm is a must try in Cebu.

title: Acacia Steakhouse
reviewr_text:
Just had our recovery dinner here after a very tiring and long exam and it was the perfect place to sit, dine and relax. Yes the place was very relaxing coupled with an instrumental music that could really change your mood from "maoy" to relaxed and free. 

The food was also delicious and with a very reasonable price. They already phased out the rosemary porkchop because the meat was not tender and did not pass their quality. They would try their best to find the perfect meat first before restocking.

We had so much fun and left with a full stomach and a happy heart. We will definitely come back soon and try the other dishes.

title: Handuraw
reviewr_text: Had the Handuraw special pizza and chili wings....both were good....real mozzarella on the pizza and a crispy thin crust...one of the best pizzas I've tasted in the Philippines since everywhere else use fake cheese and sugar sweet sauce....only issue I had with the place was the lack of service...the waiter was more interested in watching tv than taking my order and bringing me the bill...I had to get up and go to counter each time....but customer service is terrible throughout the Philippines so I was not shocked...( to clarify this is the small outlet at JY mall in Lahug)

title: Punko-punko Sa Fuente
reviewr_text:
Punko-punko, is a local favorite with the Cebuanos  (local residents). Almost all of their customers are local,  and hardly any tourist come here because they have no idea it exist. The meaning of  "Pungko" in Cebuano is to squat or crouch. "Punko" are business stalls around streets of Cebu that basically sells random deep fried food.  Food like Lumpia,  chicken wings, roasted pig, deep fried pig intestines and ears and so on. They are accompanied with vinegar dipping sauce with chilli, garlic and onions,  to cut the fat and to enhance flavor. I prefer a lot of chili on mine and it was delicious. There are no utensils. You will eat with your hands, but you are given a plastic bag to cover your hands so you never get your hands greasy or dirty. 

My Aunt's nephew,  who was our tour guide and tours visitors for a living took us here, after he learned I am a foodie, and much prefer to dine locally, and eat where all the locals go. 

If you are ever in Cebu City,  this is one area in Fuente I highly recommend you pay a visit. It gets pack for lunch as almost all the locals here comes  to eat. Note that you may be sharing your tables with strangers,  but I think it's the best way to get to know the people of Cebu.

Cheers!

title: 10 Doves Street
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Kristen T."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Hazel L."},{"reviewer_name":"ravi b."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Myles C."}]
reviewr_text: 10 Dove Street has been opened for quite a while now. This (10 Dove Street Confectionery) on the other hand is kinda new. Also located within Oakridge Business Park, they offer mostly cakes, cupcakes, coffee, sandwiches like panini, and other desserts. What I like about the place is the ambiance. Looks cozy to hangout and grab a slice of cake to eat. The lighting is pretty good as well. The employees are really attentive, accomidating, and hospitable as well. One of my favorite is their chocolate decadence cake. It's really rich, creamy, and moist. Ube cake is also one of my favorites as well as the mixed versions including ube-mango. And let's not forget their seasonal avocado. Aside from cakes, they also have cupcakes, mini cheesecakes, paninis, and coffee based drinks. I ordered out the chicken panini to eat later. For me, their cakes is one of the best I've had here in Cebu. I haven't tasted everything but I would definitely come back again for more.

title: Everything Yummy
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Pier View P."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Jo Anne G."},{"reviewer_name":"Yna C."}]
reviewr_text:
When you are craving for home-cooked meals, this is the place to go. The resto is conveniently located in EBloc2 and boasts of its tasty meals. They serve fast too. Been here a couple of times and I don't have to wait long before my order is served. The crew is very polite and accommodating too.

You can choose from a variety of dishes. I would always go back though for my all-time favorite, the Adobomb! It's their own recipe for the traditional Filipino adobo. Slow cooked and the flavor seeped in the meat. It is served with two eggs cooked the way you want it (except boiled). I hope it can be lenient enough to do boil egg soon.

Their chicken inasal is also a must-try.

reviewr_text:
Was craving a US size, juicy cheeseburger. So the hotel staff suggested Big Tom's and it was a big hit!

Located a few minutes walk from my hotel and it wasn't busy. There was group of 4 ahead of me so my order was delivered within 10 mins.

The patty was cooked well done and the cheese was oozing everywhere. Just the way I like it. The fries were crunchy on the exterior and tender on the inside. However the quantity was on the low side

The price was reasonable, it was around P370. Great neighborhood find!

title: Handuraw
reviewr_text:
Cebu's hidden puzza and beer garden! Handuraw serves all day breakfast, pizza, pasta, and other popular dishes with a Cebuano twist.

Try their Handuraw House Pizza for a truly filling Gastronomic delight and their Humba special although you'd have to prepare yourself to be disappointed as it's almost always not available because of its popularity to local diners.

Highly recommended!

title: Cafe Laguna
reviewr_text: Filipino food in its best form! The original is in ayala, but this place manages to keep the standard. I recommend the crispy pata, fresh lumpia, and the freah fruit shakes!

title: Domings Ngohiong
reviewr_text:
Seeing the photo in my camera roll just made me want to eat these tempting things.

First of all, for those who do not know what Ngohiong is (like me at first who just ate it without knowing what it was. Thought it was some sort of fried seaweed or something) its actually a mix of singkamas (jicama) and ubod (heart of the coconut). Add up a mixture of 5 spices, garlic, pork, shrimp or both etc and that pretty much makes up for this well known Cebuano street food.

This particular food spot however is known by word of mouth from the locals so at this time it's still a hidden gem. Especially since it's not easily accessible and is really just the "front yard" of a private house at this point. Who knows in the future. Doming's really serve very good ngohiong. The crunch is perfect, the seasoning good and the sauce, which is essential, is on point. Ngohiong may not suit everybody's tastebuds though. Honestly, i wasnt a big fan at first but i guess there was something about the wrap and the sauce that just makes me want one every now and then. 

Still a must try for those who havent had it yet! 

(PS: cant say much for the rest of the food since i only get these when I eat here)

title: Master Po
reviewr_text: This place is new and nicely setup. They offer short order  chinese food at very reasonable prices. The place it is located in is very new, so everything is in good shape. In regards to food, im a fan of the beef hofan and i find the fact that they have red bean bucci interesting.

title: Boosog
reviewr_text: Food was good. Ordered the paella rice, stewed fish and eggplant. Eggplant serving was small but everything else can be shared for two people. You can even order fresh buko in  a shell here. Moderately priced.

I've never been to any lechon place in Cebu so this is a wicked first try. And it's wickedly delicious!! Too bad I had food coma already from the many days of pigging out in Cebu I simply can no longer stuff in more meat down my throat! My boys loved everything that's served even the kangkong appetizer. The mussels were divine with the cheese-like topping.

My friends and I also ordered mango shakes and beer to go with everything on the table. 

This is an absolute must-go in Cebu and I for sure will be back again whenever we're given the chance to!

title: Matia's BBQ
reviewr_text: My family said Matias was a must in Cebu, so naturally it was our first stop as soon as we arrived. We got there around 1:00 in the afternoon and it wasn't too crowded luckily. It seemed like a free for all, just grab what you want and give it to them to cook for you. Somehow they magically know which plate belongs to which table and they'll bring it out to you once everything is all cooked. Luckily I was with Matias experts so they knew all the ropes! Don't expect anything fancy, it's literally just some good ol fashioned home style bbq with classic vinegar and soy sauce. Everything was delicious but the chicken was probably my favorite. So tender! Don't forget the puso, or hanging rice either! Add on a mango shake, you won't regret it. We had almost a dozen different mango shakes during our stay in the Philippines and this one was easily in my top 3 favorites.

reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]
reviewr_text:
Came to Cebu for the lechon and this place was highly rated everywhere. One of the waiters (trainee) at the podium seated me & my husband and pretty much rushed us to order the lechon. He kept saying there was only half of the lechon left and everything else is spicy. To reserve the regular lechon we would need to place an order right at that second so he can hold it for us. I asked if we could do half portion of each. He says yes. My husband points to the menu and clearly said we would like 1/8 kg of each since we're only 2 people and planned to order a couple of other dishes. He just said "yes, half and half". He then says our assigned waiter will come by to take the rest of our order.

A few minutes later, we realized that the waiter may not have fully understood us. My husband went looking for him. The waiter said the orders for 1/2 kg of each are already in and the meat is chopped. There's no going back. Dude, did you really expect a party of 2 to finish 2.2 lbs of meat? The waiter came back momentarily and repeated that he could not cancel the second order of lechon. 

We sat there pretty upset, but readied ourselves for all that meat. In the 10-15 minutes of waiting for the "already chopped meat", the assigned waiter never came by to take the rest of our order nor ask us if we'd like drinks. You could clearly see him looking glum walking aimlessly around the room.

The lechon finally came out and management approved cancelling 1 of the orders for us. Thank you, ma'am. The meat was tender & delicious. Gravy was super salty, though. I recommend eating it with the vinegar on the table & some gravy and a bowl of rice. If only we didn't have so much meat, we would have ordered a vegetable dish, a seafood dish, and dessert.

Oh well! Time to try another lechon place.

title: Larsian BBQ
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Julia C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christopher C."},{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Matthew S."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"JessicaAllyn C."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Carlo L."},{"reviewer_name":"Fedd F."},{"reviewer_name":"Jeelyn D."},{"reviewer_name":"Janine D."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."},{"reviewer_name":"Emma D."}]
reviewr_text:
I was told that Larsian was born sometime in the 1980s when Larry and Siana were selling their street foods to local residents.  They were famous for their "inihaw" BBQ seafood, and soon thereafter, all the locals followed suit.   They got so busy and famous that they eventually found this huge plaza, and turned it into many small business vendors to accommodate the crowd that comes here for lunch, dinner and late snacks daily.  Hence, the "Larsian" BBQ name was formed with their names Larry "Lar" and Siana "Sian."

I suggest to travel here with a huge group.  It's a lot more fun.  The way you order is you choose a vendor where you will buy your seafood and meat.  They will hire the guys to grill them. Certain tables are owned by certain vendors and they will direct you to a table that is theirs. My favorite has to be their grilled stuff squid.  It was so good and you can really tasted the charcoal grill.  

They get very busy after 6pm to midnight everyday, so make sure to arrive early to get the best fresh seafood daily.

Cheers!

title: Coffee Prince Cebu
reviewr_text:
It's a cozy little cafe patterned from the famous korean soap of the same title but one big difference is the ambiance - this coffee prince has a younger feel to it. I like the original coffee prince more but this is still a great place to hang out though a little too crowded if you just want to sit down for a cup of coffee. I don't suggest that you go there alone.

The food, I am NOT a big fan of, which I am quite surprised because I like Korean food. I'm also a big fan of desserts but theirs did not really hit the spot for me. However, I will give 7 out of 10 for their drinks especially with their cotton candy addition. If they downplayed the sweetness of their offerings I would rate them higher.

Service is probably the highlight of this little cafe. They have great, happy people working for them & that makes a big difference.

title: Juiceria Juice Bar
reviewr_text:
The Juiceria is a cute, delicious little juice bar that's located on the ground floor (right side) of the Bonifacio District (right below my dentist Dr Rose). It's a perfect stop if you're in the mood for a healthy, cold drink.

The cafe itself is very clean and super adorable with peach and gray decor. You'll be met with a healthy vibe to go with the healthy veggie and fruit smell, right as you walk in. There is plenty of seating so meeting friends here is definitely an option.

They have reading materials to use while you're there and some plants and healthy foods for sale. They offer energy bowls, smoothies, teas, Adlai bowls, toasts, cold pressed juices, and other refreshments. Try the Big Green Smoothie. It's delish! 

We like this little juice spot. Hope you do, too!

See ya there!

title: Laguna Garden Cafe
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Kimberly T."},{"reviewer_name":"PatrickJ T."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Ken S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Sherwin T."},{"reviewer_name":"Andrew M."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text:
Having lived in Cebu City for a year and a half, I always needed a place to take family and friends from the U.S. when I wanted them to try Filipino food. Laguna Cafe is a must! You have such a diversity in the food offered, and it's arranged in delightful ways. It's a great restaurant to introduce foreigners to Filipino food! 

Also, attached to Ayala Mall, the possibilities for things to do before and after are great.

title: Yumeya Kihei
reviewr_text: Best japanese cuisine i have had in cebu by far!! Very fresh and tempuras are great!! I cannot find fault at all with the service and the food and could have easily given this place a 5 star!! My only gripe is the overpowering smell that is emitted from their floor carpet tile... u cannot ignore it once you stepped in the door... that wet rag never got dried properly stench!!! If they could just replace the whole flooring with regular tiles that would completely eradicate that stench.... hard to enjoy the meal when that smell is overpowering... maybe its just me, but i cant stand that smell..

reviewr_text: Its the standard dimsum break chain but open 24 hours amd they have a breakfasr menu. The place can easily get overrun during call center breaks. Not bad, though the constant existence of flys inside dining area a turnoff since its a fast food chain compared to outdoor carenderias.

title: Hukad sa Golden Cowrie
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jonny M."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert N."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael H."},{"reviewer_name":"Totong B."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jenny C."},{"reviewer_name":"Swan L."},{"reviewer_name":"Emma D."},{"reviewer_name":"Keisha R."},{"reviewer_name":"Liza M."},{"reviewer_name":"Thomas L."},{"reviewer_name":"Nataraki T."}]
reviewr_text: Poor service + food that you throw up 1 hr later = a one star review.  8 empty glasses sitting on the table after the last of the food was delivered about 30 - 40 min after ordering.  Water delivered at the end of the meal which I didn't take a sip of since it was service water and I didn't want to risk illness.  So much for being safe.  Never asked if everything was ok.  Our table had a lot of different dishes.  None of them were very good.  Wonder which one was their mystery "make you sick" food.  Still the next morning, my stomach wasn't right.  I wish you could a negative star review. This would be the first I've experience in a long time.

title: Chowking
reviewr_text:
Chowking Parkmall really leaves up to its fastfood category as the service is superfast. The staff are friendly and chatty to the point that you don't even have to explain what you have in mind as they seem to know the menu by heart. 

Food selection is nothing to harp about but if you're thinking of having dimsum or anything chinese served lightning fast, this is where you go.

title: Big Tom's Charbroiled Burgers
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Dexter S."},{"reviewer_name":"William E."},{"reviewer_name":"Dean S."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert C."},{"reviewer_name":"Craig F."},{"reviewer_name":"Danny G."},{"reviewer_name":"Leah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Mike M."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheika G."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris M."}]
reviewr_text: I actually thought they used imported beef, but found it was local hamburger meat. it was as delicious as the hamburgers that are in the U.S.  Infact, this is our go to despedida location before my friends head back to Los Angeles, CA. It's a small tradition we started and always makes me homesick.  The menu is creative with great combinations and classic flavors. Their orange hot sauce is incredible! It's hot, bold and takes the hamburger to another level. I highly recommend the Jalapeño burger.  Find their original location just off Escario or their new location at Oakridge on A.S. Fortuna. Oh and their Mac & Cheese is an awesome side dish!

title: Planet Vegis
reviewr_text:
You have to fight for your right to vegetables in The Philippines. No, I'm not kidding. Sometimes it seems like everything in the country is deep fried, rice, or a noodle. 

That's why my coworkers and I, none of whom are vegan, were so excite when we found this place. We LOVE it! We order gems like cauliflower casserole, Mexican Nachos (which aren't Mexican but are still very good, the Vegan stew, and more. You can see the pics I've posted to get an idea of their offerings.

So, please go here if you're anywhere near Park Mall. Or go here even if you have to jump in a taxi. Definitely go here if you are Vegan, vegetarian, or just like veggies. Their food is great. And we want them to stay in business so we can eat there on each trip to Cebu. LoL

Definitely see ya there!

title: Maya Mexican Restaurant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Susan D."},{"reviewer_name":"Elee J."},{"reviewer_name":"Bobby L."},{"reviewer_name":"Verne A."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco F."},{"reviewer_name":"Jay H."},{"reviewer_name":"Randy H."},{"reviewer_name":"Becky C."},{"reviewer_name":"john b."},{"reviewer_name":"Jorge B."}]
reviewr_text:
This Mexican resto is okay. Service is very good. Place its self is excellent. Giving a 4-star is due to the following based soley on my opinion.

Tacos - the carne asade while tender, should be sliced a bit more into smaller pieces. Taste wise it's not close to the mexican tacos I have had. So sorry but even the tacos from a food truck taste way better. 

Fajita Ajo - very very good chicken. It was tasty and tender. No complains there.

Fajita Carnitas - good but not spectacular. Baked beans was a let down. 

But overall food is good. Hence, the 4-stars. But for a mexican restaurant locally here in Cebu it is the best. 

Should add some Oaxaca dishes, now that is authentic Mexican food. And a lengue taco would be so awesome.

reviewr_text:
My sister found this place on TripAdvisor and even though it was on the opposite part of the island in which we were staying, it was worth every minute of travel and dollar spent. 

It's buffet style, with fresh seafood you choose on the spot and they cook to order. From fish to scallops to shrimp to oysters, and different ways to prepare and season, everything tasted delicious. They also have lobster and king crab for an additional price. Drinks are not included but can be added for a small price. 

The service was also superb with different people checking in on us throughout the meal, asking for additional drinks and warning us when it was last call for the kitchen. 

For those who are considering going soon, they have a discounted rate until April 26, 2019 for the buffet. If you're in the area or coming to visit, I'd definitely recommend you check it out!

title: Buffet 101
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Cha S."},{"reviewer_name":"Alvin K."},{"reviewer_name":"Wok Star X."},{"reviewer_name":"Rhoel P."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."}]
reviewr_text:
As a balikbayan who has experienced food from around the world it can be said that while buffet 101 lacks in authenticity makes up for in quantity and surprising quality for a buffet. Buffets are not my thing so bear with me. 

The ambiance is has a very high end feeling and staff was attentive so yay for that.

First off let me say the draft beer and sangria on a self serve tap is genius and would probably be illegal in Canada. However the sangria was not the greatest, could be sweeter and colder. The beer is SM so basically piss. If it was flavoured (Apple) I'd be happier

Standard mix of Japanese, Chinese, and western. Lamb roast was dry my exes personality. Pizza was soggy. However the fish is great as they are made to order. 

The noodle bar is limited however worth a try. Avoid sashimi as it may cause stomach problems being of a lower grade cut 

Buffets are about quantity not quality. However if you look hard enough buffet 101 has a few hidden gems

reviewr_text: This is serious food here! I cant believe they have the foods that I've been eating from my childhood but have been elevated to the next level. The restaurant is adorable, love the ambience. It feels very fresh and modern but warm and welcoming. Got lucky to taste a lot of the food from the menu and I cant pick my favorite, everything was  good  and affordable. Oh! And their coffee was great! If you are in the area its a must to visit this place.

title: Luzern Steakhouse
reviewr_text: If you love steak then this place is the place to have steak.  I didn't have it but my sister had it and enjoyed a lot from the other steak places in Cebu.  Another hidden gem in Cebu.

title: Olio
reviewr_text: My favorite fine dining / steakhouse in my hometown City of Cebu! Food never fails to satisfy me And steaks are always done to perfection! Some might find this place pricey but i think it really worrh it!! I believe the owner js the masfer chef..... dont forget to try this place for your special occasion or with that special someone...

title: CoCo Ichibanya
reviewr_text:
This is an international chain restaurant based in Japan featuring Japanese curry meals. You can select the level of spiciness for the curry. Firsr impressions,  the place is well kept, despite the uptight supervisor, service was good with the staff. I enjoyed my pork cutlet with vegetable curry paired with ices coffee and mini salad.

I would come back again and try perhaps i higher spice level of curry than the standard which i selected, I also plan to try an omelet dish in future, since it seems they cook onelets in Japanese style.

title: Pueblo Mexicano
reviewr_text: Okay yes their food is great. But can I point out how amazing their desserts are? They have fried coconut ice cream that is fantastic but also this gooey fried french toast kind of thing with ice cream (I have no idea what it's called) that was to die for. If only I had more room after the giant burrito I ate there... Their chips are housemade and much thinner than any that I've seen in America but the crunch and aftertaste were delicious.

title: Ulli's
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Jini O."},{"reviewer_name":"Jo Anne G."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Lisa K."}]

title: Neo Neo BBQ Grill
reviewr_text:
No frills, no thrills, no recommendations: upgrade from 2.5 to a reluctant 3 to be fair because the standard fare was nicely cooked, but just about as boring as every other such grill house in the Philippines.

We walk in hoping for something outstanding, but sadly, it's just the same moderately-flavoured stuff: ordered the grilled boneless bangus (milk fish), lato beaded seaweed 'salad,' grilled pecho (breast/winged) chicken, and a green buko (coconut) juice drink with the usual wee bit of soft flesh. All was okay, but no being able to apply spices and herbs beyond the predictable raw onions, scattered raw semi-hot little peppers, soy sauce and whitish vinegar means that the relative tastelessness of it all lands flat as if into the swamp from where some of it sprang.

Too bad, but Neo Neo by Jing Jing at the J. Centre Mall - this specific venue - is in a bad location, and as per the food, wouldn't cut it at any chicken or seafood operation in the developed world. If you want better grilled chicken, try the tastier Jo's Inato in the Visayas (but not Manga Inasato).

Sorry readers, but if you dislike mediocrity, skip Neo Neo!

title: Max's Restaurant
reviewr_text:
In college my favorite place to hang out with my friends was PF Changs or the Cheesecake Factory. As a Filipino teen, my mom hung out at Max's. It's her first stop whenever she gets off the plane because she's absolutely obsessed with their halo halo.

And I have to admit, Max's is the BEST halo halo I've ever had. From the perfectly crushed ice to the cubed jelly, ube jalaya, flan, red beans, white beans, pinipig and the humongous scoop of ube ice cream on top eating a bowl is truly a treat yourself moment. While you may be tempted to share a bowl with friends, I highly recommend getting one for yourself. Besides, you are paying in pesos so it's literally pennies!

While I'm team Chicken Joy for life, Max's makes a pretty mean rendition too (it's what they are famous for). Super crispy and not super big and hormone loaded like American chickens. 

Service here, like everywhere in the Philippines is super slow.

title: Hai Shin Lou
reviewr_text:
I left this place absolutely furious. I ate alone. My family stayed up in our rooms, tired from a day of touring. I was rushed to order, first in tagalog (of which i don't understand much as an American), then in English. 
I ordered a pot of green tea, and they brought me a cup of jasmine tea. I was confused, but i accepted as I'm not one to be too picky.
When I asked for a recommendation the waiter nonchalantly pointed at some pork dish, which happened to be the cheapest thing on the page. I didn't go for it. Instead, I ordered fried noodles, barbeque pork, and rice. I had no intention of finishing it all. I wanted to bring some food back to my family. 
The staff stood around me staring at me and whispering to each other as I ate. Three different servers came to my table and all spoke to me in tagalog, forcing me to inform them that I only spoke English multiple times. 
The absolute worst part was when I tried to bill the food to my room, they informed me that "the system was broken" and I would have to pay cash/card. This seemed like an obvious ploy to make sure that I wasn't scamming the restaurant. I left the place insulted, uncomfortable, and actually full on a decent meal. The service was abhorrent and not representative of any respectable hotel. Do not eat here.

title: Teppanyaki Brothers
reviewr_text: The food  is okay. We ordered beef teryaki and pork chops i think? It was the normal Japanese taste. It was not that extraordinary. I consider it pricy because they have small servings. It's also fun to see your order being cooked in front of you. The service was also very fast. So i can rate 3 stars for all the experience.

title: Yakski Barbecue
reviewr_text:
Yakski barbecue is a really cool outdoor space, where you can eat and drink! 
 My friend and I came around 7pm, we waited in front and got to see all the meats they had and placed our order. 
all the good stuff like the chicken heart, tuna belly and liver were sold out for the day, so we ended up getting the chicken thigh, chicken breast, chorizo, pork skewer, and ribs I believe. 

As we waited for them to grill our food, we picked a table and the waitress came over and took our order for rice and beverages.  About 10-15 minutes later we have our rice and bbq meats!

The meats were tender and fell off the bone, they were perfectly cooked! The bbq sauces were delicious , it had a nice sweet Smokey taste. 

We literally spent about $15 for everything.

This place is a must try if you're around.

title: Lamesa Grill
reviewr_text:
Lamesa Grille serves sumptious meals great for family gatherings! We had pinatuyong adobo, liempo steak, crispy crablets, bam-i, and pinakbet for the main dish and ordered sisig and tinapa rice and every single one of them is superb! 

The service is exemplary and the dining experience truly a treat to the palate. Highly recommended!

title: The Buzz Cafe
reviewr_text: Coffee is fantastic, super strong, really tasty, and not acidic, so just to my personal liking. The food was pretty good, but pricey for what it was. We had the pancakes with bacon and the farmer omelet with homemade wheat bread. The pancakes were nice and fluffy and the bacon was cooked well, but they charged extra for syrup and provided no butter. Fortunately we also had butter and jam from the other dish which was used for the pancakes, as the bread was really dry and did not improve with an application of butter and jam. The omelet started off great especially when looking for a meat-free meal, light, tasty, with a bit of ooey gooey cheese, but when I cut into the omelet the eggs were uncooked and not in the good way, It's a great early morning breakfast spot, but be prepared for a pricey less than perfect meal.

title: Dolce
reviewr_text:
I ordered a slice of tiramisu and caramel iced coffee. 
It doesn't taste like tiramisu, excuse my french but it it is more like a layer of egg pie and coffee cake. coffee was extremely sweet too.

title: Carlos Special Ngohiong
reviewr_text:
I'm giving this place three stars based on the taste of nghiong. It's comparable to doming's but a more convenient location. However, you have to ask yourself if itd worth the agony of witnessing the disorganization. Despite the sign, please order here, no one took good orders unless you voluntary tell anyy of two staff that are scampering around cooking, filling existing orders, and trying to follow up on existing diners. I came in at 12/noon,  waited for soneone to take my order, i ended up chiming my order with two other people. Minutes later guy#2 announces they are all out of chicken and nghiong! 

I was only able to get an ordee of nghiong becausr a fellow customer was coureous to emphasize i waited in line before her

They realky need to get organized!

The italian owner was super nice and explained how all his dishes were fresh and homemade. A bit pricey but the food was superb.

I would definitely try the brisket in my next visit.

reviewr_text: This place is so yummy, you order what you want to eat, drinks and how many rice you want and then you get a number sign and choose your seat. When your foods ready they bring it to you, I usually don't eat pork but their pork belly was SO good I couldn't help it, we also got hot dogs and pork on a stick and grilled chicken. The grilled chicken was good but it can be a little dry without the sauce. Everything else was really good as well as the atmosphere, and the vibe. If you are around it park you definitely need to try it!

title: Harbour City Dim Sum
reviewr_text:
Our family in Cebu are fans of Harbour City Dimsum House.  This establishment is located inside the gigantic SM City Mall in Cebu City.   

Their Pork Steamed Rice is the best.  Their Cucumber salad is also good.  Really, though, everything we've tried has been tasty.

Good food at affordable prices combined with pleasant service and a clean restaurant equals return trips to Harbour City Dimsum House.

title: Hukad sa Golden Cowrie
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jonny M."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert N."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael H."},{"reviewer_name":"Totong B."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jenny C."},{"reviewer_name":"Swan L."},{"reviewer_name":"Emma D."},{"reviewer_name":"Keisha R."},{"reviewer_name":"Liza M."},{"reviewer_name":"Thomas L."},{"reviewer_name":"Nataraki T."}]
reviewr_text:
My friends went to Cebu and I tagged along. As a self proclaimed Cebuana, it was my duty to show them around. The tourist spots were easy and I know each and everyone of them like the back of my hand but when they asked me what's a nice local place to try in Ayala, I was stumped. I had to ask a friend of mine who lives there and she pointed us to the direction of Golden Cowrie. 

After a seemingly eventful morning at Kartzone we decided to head over to Golden Cowrie per my friend's suggestion. The place was full but luckily a group was on their way out when we came in so we were immediately seated. We loved the food, it's really good! Even though you can find it here in Manila, there's still something special about having it there.

If you're ever in Ayala, go visit Golden Cowrie!

title: The Social
reviewr_text: Came here last year and it was amazing. The bartender made the best drinks and the conversation was great! He even recommended great places to try being that it was my first time in Cebu. He joked about being related to Pablo Escobar and he was hilarious. This year I went to relive that experience and it wasn't the same. The waitress made sub par drinks and didn't vibe with the customers. Needless to say there wasn't even as much people there as before. The bartender needs to be changed to someone more experienced and more people friendly. Just my opinion. Food is always pretty good and I've been here a few times.

title: Lemon Grass
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Steve F."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Nichole B."},{"reviewer_name":"Alex S."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."},{"reviewer_name":"James R."}]

title: Rica's
reviewr_text:
Stayed at The Henry for 2 nights last month and this is the restaurant inside the hotel.  Absolutely 5 stars all the way!  But just a little background, I am into art and architecture so this review is largely influenced by that.  

Decor - Just like the hotel, the restaurant is downright artsy and eclectic, but yet not overwhelming.  There is a perfect balance of whimsy and structure.  

Ambience - Ate very late dinner (think 11:30 pm), and two days of breakfast buffets that came with my reservations.  Place was only 15% filled, so not crowded at all.  I actually enjoyed the somewhat empty and silent feel.

Menu - They have a good mix of appetizers, soup, sandwiches, pizza, pasta, main course, and dessert.  I personally felt the pricing was adequate, with most items in the 300+ peso range, with the exception of some main courses.  

Food - Tried the adobo flakes, calamari, and surprise, surprise - the seafood pasta...  (hint - Almost everywhere I've traveled to, seafood pasta is my go-to).  ALL WERE DELICIOUS!!!  For the breakfast, the selection consisted of typical Filipino full breakfast items, which honestly, I wanted and craved for:  Fried garlic rice, corned beef, eggs, somekind of pasta, sausage  (my kids ate and didn't like it), and my favorite - fried bangus.  They had the typical breads and a waffle maker, fruit, and so on.  Still enjoyed it. 

Service - They are friendly, and they checked to see how we were doing - something not normal in most restaurants in the PI. 

If I wasn't pressed for time, I wouldn't have mind eating here over and over again, but I was.  However, I would love to come back to The Henry and definitely eat at Rica's again!  It's probably one of the most enjoyable places I've ever been to!

reviewr_text: Great place for fresh Barbecue meats! There are many vendors in the area to choose from (it can seem overwhelming because each vendor wants you to buy from their stand). Each stand has its own seating area and once you choose your meats the cooks will immediately grill them and deliver them to your table. It is a kamayan style of eating (no utensils) and they provide plastic gloves. It's great for large groups and an overall fun experience!

title: Yakimix
reviewr_text:
Reasonably priced and desdent selection. Go early it can really fill up on weekdays.
The place feels cramped but again it gets the job done.
I dont know why but i'm a fan of the siomai and the orange slices they have when available. They also have a decent dessert selection considering the price.

title: Kuya J
reviewr_text:
I have been to many of the restaurants in this chain and am usually satisfied with the food, but when the server is inattentive and seems to have an attitude toward the guests, it makes for a poor dining experience. Unfortunately, it was some of the worst and uncomfortable service to begin the experience, but we stuck it out. Before the bad is upon the restaurant, I will review the service then finish on a good note, the food. 
The server (F) had ignored our repeated polite flagging, and we had to have another (M, Mark), complete our order. This girl was obviously having a bad day (or time) and ensured that either everyone knew or suffered along with her. It's a pity some people think that way. Enough. 
As for the food, beef caldereta was tasty and generous with chunks of meat. The tortang talong was firm but slightly greasy. It was accompanied by a sweet syrupy sauce that had mixed reviews. And the pinakbit was firm, flavorful and heaping. For me it's what I come to this establishment to eat. 
So as ratings go, food 4, and service 1 averages to 3. 
I hope that SM City Kuya J's, will consider this review and appreciate it for its value.

I've tried better. Dessert spread wasn't that amazing either. It was a good experience but it wasn't that impressive.

reviewr_text: Not a bad bowl of Pho for the Phillipines , also instead of giving the usual condiments(basil leaves,bean sprouts..etc)on the side so you can put what you want in your soup,  they put them directly in the Pho....which I didn't like...I'd rate it a 3 and half star...but if your craving Pho ..give it a try...located in the Robinsons cybergate mak across from Chung hua hospital..

reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Verne A."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael H."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Terri S."},{"reviewer_name":"Myles C."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]

title: Pepper Lunch
reviewr_text: Came here early to avoid the dinner rush. Even though it's still early (5pm), many were already eating inside. What I like here is their beef pepper rice and also their premium selections. Their beef was so tender and cooked to perfection. I upgraded my rice to their pepper rice, which was also really good. Oh and don't forget the sauces, which adds a little more flavor.

title: Matia's BBQ
reviewr_text:
One of the best BBQ places in Cebu. Be sure to get there early for lunch or dinner as they often run out of some menu items (most likely chicken). You go to the grill station and pick what you want and give it to the chef. Then have a seat at a table where your waiter will give you a plate of puso (hanging rice) and take your drink order (water, beer, soda, or shakes). Eat it with your hands while it is hot because that's when it is most delicious!
If you are germaphobe then this place is not for you. But if you don't mind eating with your hands and stray animals running about, then you are in for a treat! It is inexpensive too! I love this place!
There are plenty of pictures on google. I wish I had some but my finger are just to busy eating to take pictures.

Its tasty and filling and you get to appreciate the real taste of the sauce and mozarella cheese.

title: Tsay Cheng
reviewr_text: Overrated fine dining Chinese restaurant.  Got a chance to eat here a couple of years ago during our trip to Cebu.  We ate dinner at that time and it was acceptable then.  This time for lunch we ordered dimsum, it sucks.  Stay away from their dimsum. It's frozen and they just heat it up.  The siopao bola bola' s bun was warm but filling still cold.  Soup dumpling not authentic.  Chicken feet frozen and not palatable.  Pork spare ribs okay.  We also ordered crispy fried noodles with mix meat.  It was swimming in sauce, they should have called it soggy noodles.  Will think twice before eating here again.  Grand Majestic is close and under construction for another 5 mos.

reviewr_text: I ordered the carnitas fajitas and when the plate was brought out it was sizzling with a generous amount of pork. I thought I hit the jackpot but when I ate the carnitas I was hit with a very strong citrus taste (lemon, lime, calamansi, I don't know) which overpowered the taste of the meat. If ordering the carnitas fajitas you may consider asking for the citrus juice on the side. All in all I have to say I was disappointed. But in fairness to the restaurant I was hoping it would come close to what I'm used to in Southern California.

title: Ribpublic Diner
reviewr_text: Its not bad, the price is reasonable. This location is the original location, hate it or like it is located on a back street, but i you can find them at food fairs and I think they just opened inside a mall. Its not fancy or fall off the bone ribs but it gets the job done.

reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]
reviewr_text: Brah, this place was so good that I don't even feel that this post does it justice! The portion sizes were excellent, the food was out if this world delicious, and the customer service was on point. All in all, this place did not disappoint! Highly recommend! Can't wait to come back to Cebu and dine with yall!

title: Vikings
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Cha S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kimberly T."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco F."},{"reviewer_name":"Chi Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Scott G."},{"reviewer_name":"Samson C."},{"reviewer_name":"Lizell L."},{"reviewer_name":"Mac H."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael W."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Alvin K."},{"reviewer_name":"Chato M."}]
reviewr_text:
Came here at a lunch time at exactly 12. No lines yet there were plenty of people inside already. I guess reservation is highly recommended since they get full pretty fast. 

On entry you can already see an array of food. You are greeted first by their display of desserts. Makes you want to rush eating to get to them lol as you move to the right side you can find a great number of delicious food from tapas, spicy paella, assortment of seafood, roasted pork, steaks and a filipino food station. Their is also sushi, chinese station, italian station, and during lunch time they also offer a good number of breads. 

I was amazed by the number of drinks they have mostly healthy too. From watermelon to lemon infused iced tea, guava, papaya and even cucumber which i found really refreshing. There is also sago and gulaman which is not so healthy but definitely pleasing to the taste buds lol and last but not the least my favorite part when eating...dessert! Ooh how i loved their taro panna cotta and their ube pao (i made that dessert lol). Today they had unicorn cupcakes but i was too full i didnt get to try it. It looked moist and yummy.

There is such a huuuge selection of food and i have not seen anything in comparison to this in the US. That being said i believe this would probably be one of the things i'll miss now when we leave. Definitely a 5 star and a must try place!

title: Bake & More
reviewr_text: Cute little bakery shop in streetscape with a range from cakes, macaroons and bread.  The people there are friendly and the kids enjoyed their macaroons.  Will have to come back and try their coffee.

title: House of Lechon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]
reviewr_text:
A visit here was the New Year's treat for my Filipino wife and a treat it was indeed!  I know it is hard to believe, but you can get some pretty doggone good Lechon here at House of Lechon.  It met, if not surpassed my wife's high expectations for Lechon.  

She enjoyed the chicharon bulaklak as well.  I had the Gambas ala Concasse, which were fresh medium shrimp cooked in a sweet mixture of something.  I don't know what the mixture was, but it tasted great.  The food was outstanding and the people were very nice.  This place is a keeper.

Like the Terminator, I'll be back (in a while).

title: Hala Paella
reviewr_text:
First impressions, you get that cozy hole in the wall feel since its basically a kiosk with walls. There is indoor and outdoor seating. You walk in and they have Spanish music playing and a display of the available paella combjnations. The display looks great ans decor is festive.
I went with the chicken and chorizo paella, lengua, and churros for dessert. The flavors are there for the paella, the lengua gravy tasted commonplace borderline like jollibee gravy. the churros were good though slightly undercooked imho, but at least did not taste greasy or soaked in oil. the chocolate dip was really good and i would order everything again but maybe try the different paellas.

title: John Michaels Travelers Restobar
reviewr_text:
If you're looking for a 'western retreat' from the lovely chaos of Cebu City, you may want to check out John Michaels Travelers Restobar.  We've stopped in a few times to meet other travelers, network, and best of all, have some great grub.  

The service is friendly, food is delicious, and the atmosphere is laid back.  They have live music some nights and will sometimes surprise you with an amazing American-style apple pie.  My favorites include their salmon dish and their Caesar salad. They have other American and European options.

We recommend it to those looking for great food and a break from traditional Filipino food. 

Might see ya there!

title: Laguna Garden Cafe
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Kimberly T."},{"reviewer_name":"PatrickJ T."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Ken S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Sherwin T."},{"reviewer_name":"Andrew M."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]

title: La Maison Rose
reviewr_text: To be honest, I don't understand why the prices are so high! I don't mind paying fair price, but it has to be combination of the following: ambiance, food quality and service. This place lacks all three of them. If you are looking for the French food, definitely not it.

title: Sachi
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Ed T."},{"reviewer_name":"Keisha R."},{"reviewer_name":"Myles C."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris S."}]

title: STK ta Bai!
reviewr_text:
This restaurant is so beloved that they have two locations, right across the street from each other (kind of like Ravi Kabob, here in Arlington). The ambiance is upscale homey - - like having Christmas dinner at an auntie's house. Intricately carved hardwood furniture and vintage memorabilia is everywhere you look.

The dish to have at STK ta Bay! (emphasis on the exclamation mark) is their tuna panga aka: grilled tuna jaw which is served with soy sauce and kalamansi for dipping. I had never had tuna jaw before and was surprised by how humongous one portion of a fish mouth could be. It was like the biggest steak I've ever eaten times three! They grill the jaws right outside the restaurant so you are already salivating by the time you walk in. I'm used to eating my tuna raw so I found the jaw to be drier than I would have liked it. It had a very meaty quality and was devoured by the table.

To me the real stars of the show were the side dishes we got (which by the way we ended up with tons of leftovers since the tuna jaw was so big). The bulalo was like nilaga, a traditional Filipino beef stew only the flavor was amped up by a thousand thanks to the addition of bone marrow and brightyl colored vegetables. It was even a bit spicy which gave the whole dish a nice kick. Move over sinigang, I think I have a new favorite Filipino soup!

I also really loved the crispy kang kong which was lightly battered and fried and served with a creamy and cooling dipping sauce. I can definitely see why my family loves this place so much!

title: Hala Paella
reviewr_text:
This is a quaint little place whose menu revolves around their three main paella dishes - negra, valenciana, and lechon.

Paella Negra is all about its squid component, hence the black color while the lechon version, as the name suggests, highlights the Cebuano favorite as it's center. The valenciana, on the other hand, has mixed seafood in it.

So far, I have tried paella negra and valenciana and both are so damn good. Although I forgot to note the price of each, valenciana is the most expensive of the three varieties, at P148 for the solo meal (no drinks).

If you're with a group, they also have a choice of going for a bigger serving than a solo as you could go for the bigger platter that is good for 2-3 persons or the biggest, which is good for 4-5 persons.

As there is not much on the menu other than these paella dishes and some sides, it's very nice of them to allow food to be brought in from outside at no extra charge and no fuss.

I was with a friend who didn't feel like having paella at that time so he ended up buying a takeout from a nearby restaurant and eating it with me at the Hala Paella.

So far, my experience with their dishes has
been amazing and I'll definitely go back again and again. 

On a side note, they used to have a stall at the Sugbo Mercado in IT Park but I haven't seen them there this week.

title: Birdseed

title: Larsian BBQ
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Julia C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christopher C."},{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Matthew S."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"JessicaAllyn C."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Carlo L."},{"reviewer_name":"Fedd F."},{"reviewer_name":"Jeelyn D."},{"reviewer_name":"Janine D."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."},{"reviewer_name":"Emma D."}]
reviewr_text:
Where else can you find good street meat for cheap prices? None other than larsian.

you can get a stick of chicken skin, chorizo, hot dogs and so much more.

If you love meat then this is the place to be. This is what true filipino food is about. It's not the nicest place to be in but the food is worth it!

title: Fung's Noodle House
reviewr_text: This may be the only place i know of that has siao long pao (soup steam buns). My other favorite Choi City is now closed. The place is small and cozy, staff is accomodating. This place can be busy during lunch time.

title: Cafe Elim
reviewr_text:
Trendy cute and so picturesque! If you love the glizty pink life, Cafe Elim is definitely your spot! If you love Japanese sando and toast, this place is also for you!

I couldn't resist trying these huge egg-filled toasts. Apparently they're a Japanese thing and I needed to try it while in Asia. I tried their wasabi tuna toast and to this day, I can't stop thinking about it! It was so good as a breakfast sandwich paired with a nice hot Americano! The bread and eggs are nice and fluffy. The ladies working there were also very sweet! They gave us matching cups to compliment our meal. I would definitely come back in a heart beat when in Cebu! They also serve sweets like macarons and cake.

Lots of seating.
Picture worthy.
Good option for breakfast. 

Mangaon ta!

title: UCC Cafe Terrace
reviewr_text:
UCC is a Japanese coffee brand, and IMHO,  one of the best cups of coffee I've had. They use the "siphon"  method of brewing coffee which is fun to watch.

They also offer meals amd desserts. Their "halo halo" is also one of the best I've had in the area. 

For sure, you've got to have at least one cup of coffee if it's your first time. From houseblend and up on menu, you can't go wrong. just be aware its premium coffee and premium process the a cup of coffee starts at 119 pesos, but worth it IMHO.

reviewr_text: Great views..outdoors for drinks the to a table for dinner.  Amazing dry aged rib eye.  Could not have had a better birthday dinner

title: Big Tom's Charbroiled Burgers
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Dexter S."},{"reviewer_name":"William E."},{"reviewer_name":"Dean S."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert C."},{"reviewer_name":"Craig F."},{"reviewer_name":"Danny G."},{"reviewer_name":"Leah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Mike M."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheika G."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris M."}]
reviewr_text: This is my favorite burger place in Cebu. Hands down. I love their Double Decker and Jalapeño Burger.. The service is awesome and really fast. Cebu's gem for sure. Will eat here again as soon as I get back in Cebu.

main: Tony G’s Foodcourt by Ned Nanay’s Grill
title: Tony G's Foodcourt by Ned Nanay's Grill
KPub BBQ
reviewr_text:
Holy Crap! This place was crap!

The meats were obviously frozen. Very tough and stringy. And no flavor, at all. 
And how about putting up some more light for the tables? We couldn't even see what we were cooking.
The ban chan was all over the place. And none of it was good. And I love japchae, but theirs was absolutely horrible. So salty and blech.

I can appreciate the K-pop theme, but you need to increase the quality of your food.

title: Hai Shin Lou
reviewr_text: I've been here for 30 minutes after ordering. I've seen multiple tables get their food. Maybe it's because I'm an American woman traveling alone for work, or maybe it's because I rank low on their list of priorities. Either way, this is not professional. No one has even come to say a thing to me. Horrible experience. The food came finally after many dirty looks, it was good. I asked for it spicy, it wasn't at all but at least palatable. Be cautious here.

title: Shaka Hawaiian Restaurant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Tomoe S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kristine A."},{"reviewer_name":"Josh M."},{"reviewer_name":"Amy J."},{"reviewer_name":"Larry Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Biba M."}]
reviewr_text: What can I say. The setting looked nice and promising. However, the food disappointing big time. We ordered the Huli huli chicken, chicken wonton soup and chicken skewers. The huli was partially burned, the soup had no wonton and was extremely salty...you will do better and way cheaper buying an instant noodle soup at 7 eleven. The skewer were not cooked thoroughly. Horrible food!!! And expensive for what you are getting.

title: Treat Street Cafe
reviewr_text:
Treat Street Cafe is owned by the great Trina Ang! Who is also known for baking excellent wedding cakes!

I was thrilled to know she is opening a cafe as it would mean easy access to her cakes lol i love the texture of the pastries she makes and one of my favorites is their classic chocolate cake. It is not too sweet, icing is made smooth and delicate and texture is just right. The green tea and sesame cake had a chiffon-cake texture but surprisingly it blended pretty well with the icing/mousse that it was such a joy to eat.

I can't say much for the coffee as i havent tried it but i bet they are pretty good as well. I expected nothing but the best from Trina. Treat Street is definitely worth trying!

title: Ice Castle
reviewr_text: This place is practically an institution. This place has been around for a long time and the brand is pretty established. Don't expect this place to be fancy, but for sure its a local favorite and can be busy during snack times. The halo halo is their signature dessert, but the also serve short order meals.

reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Kristen T."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Hazel L."},{"reviewer_name":"ravi b."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Myles C."}]
reviewr_text: A quaint dessert shop that also serves meals usually in the form of a sandwich. I ordered the a set meal which allows me to choose my soup, salad, sandwhich, and dessert at a very reasonable price! The star of the place are the desserts! I had a slice of the opera came and was amazing. Moist yellow cake, with icing that had the right amount of sweetness and a layer or chocolate cream in middle. Whether you come in for a meal or dessert, I highly recommend!

title: Larsian BBQ
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Julia C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christopher C."},{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Matthew S."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"JessicaAllyn C."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Carlo L."},{"reviewer_name":"Fedd F."},{"reviewer_name":"Jeelyn D."},{"reviewer_name":"Janine D."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."},{"reviewer_name":"Emma D."}]
reviewr_text:
Amazing. 
If you like barbecue. Then come here please. You pick the meat or fish you want them to bbq for you. And then they bring it to you and eat. You can also have the fish either grilled or turned into soup. It is an experience i haven't had before and i am glad that my friend brought us here. At first the place looked skeptical because it definitely looked like a wet market. But from my experience, skeptical usually means great food. 
Place can be crowded and loud because of people barking at passerby's in an attempt to get them to eat at their stalls. There are also alot of flies because it is outdoors and the place is a bit dirty lookin. 
The great side about this place is that the food is cooked deliciously!!! It was amazing.. i kept eating and eating. I was definitely surprised on how good the food came out. 
If you are a picky eater or someone that may want to make sure what you are eating is 100% taken care of an sanitary. You might lose your mind in this place cuz i personally doubt that this place is clean, but it is probably safe to eat to some extent. Place gets crowded late at night. 
I'd come back here. I'd even bring my family

title: Harbour City Dimsum House
reviewr_text:
I may be wrong, but I believe that this is the Harbor City Dimsum House that delivered to us.  I apologize if it is not the correct branch.

What I do know is that within 30 minutes of making that phone call, the food was delivered hot and fresh.  I only ate this delicious soup with noodles and meat inside.  Sorry. I forgot the name.  The Siopao Bola Bola was delicious and paired well with the soup.

Good first time trying their food.  Bodes well that we would try more next time and eat at their restaurant.

title: Big Tom's Charbroiled Burgers

title: Banri Noodle House
reviewr_text:
Ramen has been around for quite a while, anyone who was ever looking for a quick meal..I'm sure has come across dry noodle wafers with a flavor packet usually in the form of the Lucky Me Brand. 

But what if you decided, to really appreciate the ramen and went for something where more time was spent in making the noodle and broth that went into it?

This brings us to the the ramen shops where people come in to appreciate such work. You step into this place and you get the impression, they know what they are doing and it seems they do, since I notice people that look like regular customers. In addition, the place has been in the area for a while. 

You can't really go wrong with any of the choices, but I went with the ramen tonkatsu since it comes with some slices of pork along with a side order gyoza. Be sure to look a the menu, since it gives a description on what each ramen bowl offers in flavor and the staff is more than kind to assist in helping you choose the right meal for you. To me its about the noodle texture and the broth. As you slurp in the noodle and take in some broth, you can't help but feel a sense of comfort.

title: Phat Pho
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Verne A."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael H."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Terri S."},{"reviewer_name":"Myles C."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text: Best Pho in town! The flavors are fresh, clean, and balanced. This restaurant has been opened for a few years now and I have to say they are consistent in their cooking. Owned by the prestiged abaca group, this is one of the variety of restaurants they have. When you come in, you are warmly greeted and welcomed by the friendly employees. The place seems to be packed most of the time especially on a busy weekday lunch hour. No need for fancy booklet menus, their menu is on the board. Every now and then they introduce something new and/or a special item for the day. You can opt to ask if you want coriander on your pho or not but for me, I like it "everything on it". Condiments are placed on top of your bowl of pho, but you can ask them to separate it on the side, while the sauces, pickled garlic, and lime are served on the side. The place seems to be pretty clean and the service was great and fast. Airconditioning and ventilation was good as well. I would definitely recommend this place to anyone who is looking and craving for some pho/vietnamese food.

title: Mr A Bar and Restaurant
reviewr_text:
We've been here multiple times before and it's been almost 2 decades since we've been here. We're so glad to be back as it brings good memories. It's still a very good place to hang out with family/friends. Food is still very good (Filipino cuisine), lots of choices. They now have a sports bar with pool tables. You also have a choice of indoor/outdoor dining. They have a karaoke room. Good location overlooking the City of Cebu. A Must visit if you're visiting Cebu or just for a romantic dinner, but definitely at night and on a good weather.

Wonder why the lack of detail in food review, well, everthing we had was good and flavorful.

title: Shakey's Pizza
reviewr_text: Excellent hand tossed pizza I am an american and found their pizza to be as good as most back home Visited Christmas day with s party of 12 Got seated quickly but service was slow Can not penalize for the service after all it was a holiday Will be back

title: Laguna Garden Cafe
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Kimberly T."},{"reviewer_name":"PatrickJ T."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Ken S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Sherwin T."},{"reviewer_name":"Andrew M."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text:
It's weird that they would put another Resto of theirs right across the terraces. I actually visited their original one, Cafe Laguna. Same menu from what the wait-staff has told me.

Got to try their Merienda section's Puto Bungbong; with a cool Four Season Shake on the side. I actually have asked if I may get the shake's white sugar on the side and mix it on my own. But when it came in, it was still the syrup mix; at least it was on the side... never to be touched.

The Puto Bungbong was so-so. I've tasted better. It came wrapped in foil. From that, it seems they have baked it(?) Somewhat of a drier texture that I'm used to. Took out a star because of that.

The service is good though. Friendly and knowledgeable staff. Will go back again to try their other offerings and hopefully get my rating up for them.

title: Timeout Sports Bar & Resto
reviewr_text:
It was Saturday night and we were looking for where the peeps hang out.  So when we heard someone singing, we followed the vocal cords to here, Timeout Sports Bar & Resto.  

Located in a business park on the upper level, the place seemed to be attracting all those nearby because of the lead singer, belting out on the microphone.  Once we arrived up there, we got one of the last group tables of the place, watching the live band jam out.  

I only drank beer here, while my relatives ordered some bar food (chili cheese fries and sisig).  It's a bar and there's bar food here.  If you're looking for actual good food then Timeout isn't your place.  It's known for the fun, lively environment that it has, with a live band playing metal rock, where the entire audience sings along while the lead singer whips her hair back and forth and often sings, standing on the bar!  It's a fun place!  Come for the experience!  
 
Despite how busy the place got, service was always on point.  They even offered free shots of vodka for the entire place, going around to all the tables, pouring a shot for all those willing to party.  Timeout is where to do it on a Saturday night.

reviewr_text:
The buffet seems to be a slow but rising trend in cebu. A few months ago it was buffet 101 and now vikings, the other place claimed hotel ambiance while this place claims luxery. The ambiance is definitely more upscale. The are located in sm mall which already makes them convenient to all, if i'm not mistaken they even plan to open  a place i. sm seaside. In regards to food they have a great spread, they even have lamb! The dessert offering seems to be dissappointing to both.
Since its new as of this posting, you'll want to make reservarions. I'm a walk in at #34 and i came in at 1145, they open at 1130.

title: Zubuchon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Jacques I."},{"reviewer_name":"Tellie N."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Ron Z."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Lillian C."},{"reviewer_name":"Linda P."},{"reviewer_name":"Benjamin C."},{"reviewer_name":"Cris T."},{"reviewer_name":"David L."},{"reviewer_name":"Kathrine P."},{"reviewer_name":"John A."},{"reviewer_name":"Barry T."},{"reviewer_name":"Aileen B."},{"reviewer_name":"Angeli Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Ian Maren C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Geoffrey U."}]
reviewr_text:
Not the best lechon I've ever had, but definitely the best pork skin.

We had the classic Zubuchon Lechon, along with the scallop appetizers, and garlic rice.

The lechon meat was very good. Juicy, chunky pieces. But the best part was the crispy, deep fried skin. So full of flavor, and not chewy at all. 
The scallops were a let down, especially after having them at Kuya J's. 
I would go back, if I were to ever return to Cebu, which is probably never.

title: STK ta Bai!
reviewr_text:
We love this restaurant and their food! My family and I made it a tradition to always dine here when we arrive to Cebu from Los Angeles, California! It's like dining in a traditional family home . We are 3 generations of U.S.-Born FIL-AM's and we all love this place!r I recommend their Tuna Pangga, Kinilaw sa Gata and Baked Scalops. SARAP! But all their dishes are pretty delicious.  Their Lemonade Cooler and ripe Mango Shakes are yummy and refreshing. Best part is; Prices are resonable and a good value!!
Just like eating Lechon when in Cebu. NO visit to Cebu is complete, without a stop at STK Ta Bai!

title: Shakey's Pizza
reviewr_text: I like the thin crust pizza. However, the sizes are really small. They have a cucumber lemon drink that I enjoyed the other day. However, today it's super sweet and I had to dilute it with the service water. Still too sweet.  Lots of toppings, on the salty side. I enjoyed the Greek salad. It's a good size.

main: Ipar’s Restaurante Y Bar De Tapas
title: Ipar's Restaurante Y Bar De Tapas
reviewr_text:
Very customer service friendly.  Food was deliciously prepared. Sangria was great.  Im visiting from the USA and really was in search of some good seafood.  I checked yelp and was pleasantly surprised to find out this location was in walking distance of the hotel I was staying at. This was one of my best meals in the Philippines, I give thanks for the opportunity to dine here. 

I must admit I was hopeful to meet the owner who was not around.  Oh well, a gurl can't have EVERYTHING. LOL. They did have WiFi. Go Ipar's!!!

title: Blue Elephant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"PatrickJ T."},{"reviewer_name":"Clydelle M."},{"reviewer_name":"Arnel E."},{"reviewer_name":"Dexter V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sandrine G."},{"reviewer_name":"Steve F."},{"reviewer_name":"PGreg H."},{"reviewer_name":"Dee S."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text:
They have 1 vegetarian dish which was quite tasty. I went for my lunch break today as I was doing the day shift at work in IT Park. I am not a fan of their hours but that's because I'm usually on the local night shift. They close at what is expected for restaurants in the US. However, given their location, I think they are missing the majority of their business as there are so many night shifters.

Their menu looks good given you eat meat. I was a little surprised by eating at a Thai place as I'm from the US. In the IS, all Thai restaurants let you pick a protein with a km most every dish and also a spice level. Nope. You get what's on the menu. I bet you could substitue, but I didn't ask.

The food was not really what I expected for thai. I had the mixed vegetables. The sauce was quite delcious....but when I eat Thai I expect some kind of heat. White rice was an add on  for 40 pesos....and that is quite an expensive for white rice in the PH. I can find it for 10 pesos or less almost anywhere else.

It was clean, the air con was cold, and quite comfortable seats.  If you're working in IT Park frequently, it's a good stop. If you're visiting Cebu as a tourist, I recommend the Blue Elephant in the Red Apple building in Cebu Business Park. It's on the top floor, has same food and prices, but comes with an excellent view.

title: STK ta Bai!
reviewr_text:
Sister highly recommended this place and it was a good choice for a family dinner.

We were a group of 9 people so we needed a place that is not so expensive but good and STK ta Bai delivered.

The fish cheeks were awesome that we decided to get two. My sister , T and I basically went to all the nook and cranny of cheeks to find the last bit of meat in it.

We also selected some fresh crab and fish and ask them to cook it for us. 

Food arrived in a decent amount of time, and really good.

Everyone enjoyed the food and we still got some remaining dishes that we took home with us.

I highly recommend this place if you are ever in Cebu City.

reviewr_text: This review is long overdue. Came to this place to meet my friends for dinner. It was my first time to try this place & I immediately liked what I felt when I walked into the restaurant. It felt homey and comfortable at the same time. I didn't know what to expect food wise. So we ordered several dishes pasta with meatballs, pork belly with basil pesto sauce & garlic rice, salmon in mornay sauce with green salad, brisket kimchi fried rice & chicken fingers with fries. Everything we ordered was to our liking and tasted delicious. If ever I'm back in town I would like to visit this place again.

title: Larsian BBQ
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Julia C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christopher C."},{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Matthew S."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"JessicaAllyn C."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Carlo L."},{"reviewer_name":"Fedd F."},{"reviewer_name":"Jeelyn D."},{"reviewer_name":"Janine D."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."},{"reviewer_name":"Emma D."}]
reviewr_text:
Cheap place for a barbecue. The place is like a mini market where you pick a store who sells all kinds of barbecue, choose from their menu selections and make them cook it. The one we got for example sells grilled fish for 180 ea h, isaw for 6 pesos and chorizos for 8 pesos each, etc. We picked what we wanted by hand and hand it to them to cook. Each store has their own tables where you can eat. 
Con is that they dont have a bathroom or a place to wash your hands. You can ask for them to provide you with a pail of water to do so or they themselves provide you with gloves so you can eat. Unless you order something with soup like clams tinola....they also dont provide you with cutlery. Its a real kamayan (eat by hand) place!

title: Cebu's Original Lechon Belly
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jefferson S."},{"reviewer_name":"Abbys A."},{"reviewer_name":"Gio G."},{"reviewer_name":"Gil M."},{"reviewer_name":"Anneke D."},{"reviewer_name":"Barry T."},{"reviewer_name":"Maputing E."},{"reviewer_name":"Mike M."},{"reviewer_name":"Swan L."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."}]
reviewr_text: High highs and medium lows. I've been coming to this place since I first moved to Cebu. Depending on the time of the day, or how recently it's cooked, the lechon belly's quality can vary quite differently. At its best, 'Cebu's Original Lechon Belly' is second to none. But the drawback is that they're not always serving the highest quality that they're capable of. This is probably due to the fact that at differing times of the day, their servings will have differing freshness, and the longer the pork is off the grill, the less crispy the skin is and the less tasty it is. Timing is key. Pricing is as expected for its location and quality servings.
