title: Seafood Island
reviewr_text:
Came here for lunch while in cebu and wondering the halls of the mall.  This place was highly recommended as a good sharing type of meal where its better to eat with your hands.
So we ordered a Mt. Apo boodle for the 7 of us.  The food came out quickly and it was a site to behold (see accompanying pictures)!!!  It was a massive plate of garlic rice, fish, meats, etc and soup in a coconut shell. The food was more than enough for all of us.  And it was really flavorful and delicious too.  All the food lent to each other and accompanied each other.  We also had a whole chicken which was moist and delicious as well.  The unlimited ice tea was good and refreshing especially while eating all these hot fried foods. 
Service was fast.  The people were nice and attentive to our needs.  Im sure if i ate with my hands it wouldve been even more of an experience!! Overall this place left me full and satisfied!!!  It is a must try when in cebu!!

title: Larsian BBQ
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Julia C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christopher C."},{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Matthew S."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"JessicaAllyn C."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Carlo L."},{"reviewer_name":"Fedd F."},{"reviewer_name":"Jeelyn D."},{"reviewer_name":"Janine D."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."},{"reviewer_name":"Emma D."}]
reviewr_text:
When I visit any destination, whether it be in another country or in the Philippines, I want to eat where the locals will eat. I'm admittedly a neat freak and cleanliness is a big factor anywhere I go. BUT, if the food and experience is great, I won't even care if there was a cockroach seated next to me (seriously!). Larsian is a big barbecue center located in Fuente Osmeña Circle in Cebu. As soon as you enter the center, you will be greeted by throngs of stall owners inviting you to check out and choose from their wide array of "ihaw-ihaw" or grilled meat, poultry and seafood. Basically, it is THE one-stop barbecue place in Cebu! 

Since all their meat and seafood is on display, you are guaranteed that the food is fresh. There are long tables & chairs designated to each stall; In the middle, you see all the grilling stations. I suggest you pick a stall that is furthest away from the middle, unless you want to small like barbecue too. :P When you are seated, a stall attendant will give you native plates lined with plastic, plastic gloves (yes, you are expected to eat with your hands!) & a basket of "puso" (rice cooked inside cone-shaped coconut leaves, Php5/0.11USD per piece). 

My friends and I always end up ordering the same grilled items: chicken (Php50/1.07USD per stick), Cebu Chorizo (Php5/0.11USD per piece), Bangus or Milkfish (Php120/2.57USD, depends on the size) and other grilled meat here and there! Everything is very cheap! :) I recommend that you MUST order the chicken and the Cebu Chorizo. You will not regret eat those with your hands with 3-4 puso too.

To me, dining at Larsian is more about the experience you will have while eating with your friends. There are other more mainstream restaurants that will serve better grilled dishes. But, with the cheap prices and the atmosphere, it's certainly worth the visit! Sobrang Sulit! ;)

title: TEPPAN
reviewr_text: Try one f the Okonomiyaki; they made it without the pork as I requested. I also had a calamansi drink.

title: Mang Inasal
reviewr_text:
If you want cheap sisig, I guess you can come here. I really don't know any other Filipino fast food chains that serve sisig. 

Prices are ok, though I personally think they could be a little lower considering how much you actually get.
I mean, the hot plate of sisig was pretty miniscule. I was actually disappointed.
The meat was especially chewy, and not as flavorful as I was expecting. i needed to add a lot of chili vinegar.
I also ordered the "unli" 
What is the "unli" you ask?
It turns out it means unlimited rice.

So yeah,....... "unli".

title: Casa Verde
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jay K."},{"reviewer_name":"Thunder H."},{"reviewer_name":"Joe T."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Ray J."},{"reviewer_name":"Dale E."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheika G."},{"reviewer_name":"Jodie S."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text:
If you're in Cebu and you're HANGRY, do yourself a favor and eat at Casa Verde! It's an American style casual dining restaurant. This branch is the original and was the ancestral home of the owners. The food is very affordable and the servings are HUGE (unless you can eat a 9-inch burger by yourself)! All the food they serve is good for sharing with friends. :)

When my fiancee, brother and I ate here, we were accompanied by a local. So, he ordered for us the best of the best dishes. We had Brians Ribs aka the "Once you taste me, youll never forget me..." Ribs. It's hands down their best seller! Baked pork ribs with a sweet, tangy piquet sauce served with rice and a side corn and carrots. The meat was tender and falling off the bones. Of course, the boys wanted burgers and Casa Verde has BIIIG burgers! We ordered "The Big Bang Burger" - 9-inch burger topped with onions, tomatoes, lettuce, mayo, American cheese on a sesame-seed bun. Yes, sharing recommended. :) If you think that's big, they have a BIGGER burger called "The Mighty Ton"! It's a kilo of our USDA tenderloin patty stuffed into their homemade 12-inch bun with 125 grams of bacon, an overload of american cheese, lettuce, tomatoes, sauteed onions and mushrooms. Plus, you have a choice of barbecue, cheese or sour cream fries.

To go with your meat dishes, they also have appetizers and pasta. I skipped all that and went straight to their milkshake! They serve a very special milkshake called the "Milky Way." If you look at the photo I uploaded, it is, again, BIG! They claim it's "The Biggest Milkshake In Town!" It's basically a chocolate shake with lots of extra chocolate bits added in. Best served with their big bang burger! Note: You have to ask the server if the Milky Way is available because they have limited TALL glasses. I waited for mine. Took about 20 minutes. Worth the wait! 

In the end, we ended up bringing home a few ribs and half of the burger (except for the milkshake! I finished it :P) and had it for breakfast the next day. If you're heading to Cebu, try this place. They have a few branches now but, I enjoyed eating at the original location. Again, you Must Try their all time best-seller the Brian's Rib! :)

title: Denny's
reviewr_text:
Denny's is located inside Robinson's Galleria next door to TGIF. After entering the garage to park, take a left then head straight. There will be another entrance to the mall that will get you closests to Denny's as you ascend the escalators.

I've been through many Denny's in my lifetime to say that this Denny's decor was more modern than the ones back home we frequent after clubbing. Much cleaner too. 

A quick glance at the menu were short on offerings. So it seems like it was a Denny's on the go kinda thing. Anyway we ordered fish & chips, churro waffles, a chicken fried steak burger, and arroz caldo (rice porridge with chicken). For drinks one of the few restaurants that understood water with lemon. The food arrived and everyone sampled each other's order. Consistant throughout restaurants or any food joints in Cebu I been to, salty. I mean this was way overboard salty. Like the cook relentlessly poured salt on every single micro inch of the food. We did advise the waitress to let the cook know, next time to ease off the salt. I mean they did have the standard salt and pepper shakers that most, if not all, American restaurants have at the table. So one can suppliment if one feels the food needed a boost. Aside from the saltiness, the fish and chips were good and crispy came with a wedge of lemon too. The Churro waffles were sprinkled with cinnamon and brown sugar (and enough salt that you can notice its there) and you are given a tiny portion of chocolate to dip your waffles with. The chicken fried steak burger was a little on the dry side and a portion of the burn was close to being burnt. The arroz caldo was generously topped with chicken, scallions, and fried garlic. 

Staff: All were very helpful and quick when you ask them for something. Very polite. One lady did try to sell us some type of discount membership. At 2,000 pesos (about $40 usd) you get a discount of items ordered at Denny's and TGIF. I do not frequent these restaurants much to warrant buying a discount membership, so we declined the offer. Free wifi both inside Denny's, and the mall also has its own (limited) free wifi. Mall parking is 20 pesos.

title: Sunburst

reviewr_text: Sad to say but this place did not produce the signature fried chicken I use to love growing up. The chicken is so small and not crispy at all. The crispy para was a bit on the out side. The amapalya was good. But the service was slow. Had to follow up and or order twice.

title: Gerry's Grill
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Erika R."},{"reviewer_name":"Paula C."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."},{"reviewer_name":"Dfrancisco G."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil O."}]
reviewr_text:
Gerry's is a filipino sit down restaurant chain found in major malls.  They serve the most well known of filipino classic dishes.  They provide a good sized serving.  The price is average for a sit down restaurant found in a mall. 

The location in Ayala Mall Cebu was great.  You can sit inside or outside.  Outside, you get a good view of the park in Ayala Mall, it is in the higher floor and at night it is breezy.  Inside, you get the air conditioning.  During Christmas time, they have dancing lights at the park.

We ordered the palabok, bangus sisig and garlic rice.  The palabok was very saucy.  It was a bit salty and did not have that much ground pork on top, it also lacked the chicharon.   However, the size was great and can fill you up. You can sprinkle the calamansi on top of the palabok to cut down on the saltiness.  

The bangus sisig was a bit salty as well, but that's where the rice comes in.  It comes on a sizzling plate, which is a nice sight to behold.  The garlic rice is a great alternative to plain rice.

If you just wanna chill and have a snack, they have bucket beer specials. 
This would go great with their pork sisig, which is apparently one of their bestsellers.

title: Barikata Ramen Bar
reviewr_text: This place has been around since last september. I stumbled upon it just from walking around IT Park. I went with the shiro ramen and some gyoza. I hear the broth supposed to be salty but I must say this is the best broth Ive had so far. The portion a little on the small side but then the price is also on par compared to other places for same size portion. gyoza was good and held to the standard but then havent come across gyoza that wowed me.

title: Café George
reviewr_text: I enjoy veggies and vegan/vegetarian dishes. After an 8 day stay in Cebu, I was overloaded with pork and rice. Thankfully Cafe George met my fix, and exceeded my expectations! The menu has a wide variety, and while there with my group of 12--every person seemed to enjoy what they selected. I ordered an frozen espresso and quinoa burger. One of the beat dinners all week!

title: CnT Lechon
reviewr_text: Avoid this place like the plague. They serve it cold and soggy. The meat was dry and tasteless. I hope I don't get food poisoning later.

title: Paolito's
reviewr_text:
Fast service and you'll definitely get the worth of your money. Kinda expensive but the serving is also quite big for one person. Their spicy chicken wings are to die for!!! 

P.S. Do prefer having plain rice than flavored ones because they tend to use more oil as I had observed.

title: Harbour City Dimsum House
reviewr_text: I was so excited to eat here after being away for so long and I ended up getting disappointed with the service and the food. My brother and I came here to have some steam rice, siomai, lumpia, noodles and shrimp. We waited for about 20 minutes for the server to take our food/drinks orders and another 15-20 mins for our food to come. They were packed with diners for lunch and yet they only have a handful of servers which made the service quite slow. We planned to go in and out and yet we spent about 3 hours in the place just waiting. Waiting for the server to get our orders, waiting for our food and drinks, waiting for our bill and waiting for my credit card to get returned. I'm not a fan of this place.

title: La Bella
reviewr_text: Read about La Bella Napoli in a blog comparing it to other excellent pizza places in Cebu, and went to compare it myself to Michaelangelos, which I love.  Found the pizza (I chose the Capricciosa) to be very good, perhaps not quite as good as Michaelangelos, but the smiles given out from start to finish by the waitress made the experience equally if not more rewarding. Pleasant indoor-outdoor venue near other restaurants and not far from Ayala Center. Highly recommend.

title: Casa Verde
reviewr_text:
The owner has to retrain his/her staff especially the manager. Instead of earning $$ today the owner lost $$ due to his/her staffs incompetence. We ordered their gigantic burger (thinkin this will be just like nyc) unfortunately the waiter and manager told us verbatim that we can't order the gigantic burger coz it wouldn't fit at the bar. WTF is what I was thinking  so I suggested how about we cut in half coz we're not eating it as a whole it will eventually be sliced into two by my brothers. Both waiter and manager said no and was adamant that it's huge and suggested to order something else. We all cracked up. I couldn't help it I told them "you'd be fired if I was the owner right there and there. I mean you demonstrated you don't have the greatest customer service now we've established you're completely incompetent." Not recommending this establishment! 

Ps there's more to this crazy experience but space is limited.

title: Top of Cebu
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco R."},{"reviewer_name":"Caitlin M."},{"reviewer_name":"Sivilay T."},{"reviewer_name":"Tawny T."},{"reviewer_name":"Kartik K."}]
reviewr_text: The view here is breathtaking and the food here is pretty damn good too. This is the first place we stopped at when we first landed in Cebu. It's open pretty late. They have a lot of food choices so for those of you who aren't used to eating more foreign type of foods, there's definitely things on the menu that you can enjoy. I would highly recommend everyone visit here if they're ever in Cebu, just for the view alone. I'd also recommend going at night because it's alot nicer to see the overview of the entire city at night with all of the lights from the buildings. Very romantic place also. Saw a lot of couples and even some people having their own picnics.

Try their chicken inasal, longganisa, and pork barbeque (large is php18.00 and small is php10.00).

Highly recommended!

reviewr_text: This place is amazing. Service is impeccable and the food was delicious and creative. Went back multiple times to try new menu items and was never disappointed. Amazing cocktails and a nice relaxing environment. This place makes you forget you're in Cebu City.

title: Majestic
reviewr_text:
On the window of Majestic restaurant it says "The Chinese Food We Love".  Well, I have to say that Majestic does indeed cook up some yummy Chinese cuisine.  Our group was about 16 adults, and we were able to get a reservation.  They sat us at the back of the restaurant which was perfect.  

The restaurant was jam packed with customers dining both inside the restaurant and outside.  There was no delay in the food coming out.  These folks are fast and efficient.  The quality of the food did not suffer also.  Everything we had was good.  My favorites this visit were the bread and the noodles.  Sorry, but I do not remember the name of each entree.

I can highly recommend dining at Majestic restaurant at the Ayala Center Terraces.  Even for a large group the service was good, food tasted delicious, and the prices were very affordable!!

title: House of Lechon

reviewr_text: I ordered chicharon bulaklak and 1/4 kilo of regular lechon. The lechon was super delicious. The skin that I am always looking forward to eating was so super crispy and tasty. My husband liked it a lot,especially the crispy sound of it. With every bite of the lechon, I could really taste all the spices that they put in the pig. The chicharon bulaklak was good, crunchy,and good with vinegar.

title: Craft Cafebar
reviewr_text:
Great selection of beer and alcohol. Beer is ice cold which is a must for me. Danny one of the owners was very nice and accommodating and next time I'm in cebu I will definitely go
Here again. 
Heard they are packed on the weekend with beer pong and dancing as well. 
Definitely go check it out.

title: Yamichan
reviewr_text:
All you can eat kbbq for 399 pesos! (About $8USD). You really can't beat it! Very friendly staff who help you with the menu.

Our favorite was the beef. The meats include- beef belly, beef brisket, beef tongue, and pork belly.

Lots of sides offered. They do have rice paper. Soup is yummy. Definitely a hot spot that lots of people go to! Highly recommend!

title: Laguna Garden Cafe
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Kimberly T."},{"reviewer_name":"PatrickJ T."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Ken S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Sherwin T."},{"reviewer_name":"Andrew M."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text:
This is a family owned restaurant which at first started as a small cafeteria , but moved on to being a family friendly restaurant at Ayala Mall. As Ayala Mall transformed itself to what it is now, this restaurant was there from the beginning.

The menu is primarily Filipino cuisine. If you like pork, I suggest the Crispy Pata, if you are into veggies, they have a dish which is composed of steam vegetables (can't remember name" but its on the menu, they also have seafood dishes, and a dessert menu based on traditional Filipino dessert. 

The dishes they offer are what you will see in most Filipino restaurants, but the the preparation, ambiance, and friendly service will make you a loyal customer if you appreciate such things. Take note, there are two locations in Ayala Mall one is part of the Mall, the other the one I'm writing about is part of the "Terraces" which is composed mainly of eating places. 

So if you are looking for a place to try Filipino dishes in a calm and family setting, then be sure to give this place a try.

title: Iamik's Chicken & Beer
reviewr_text: Highly recommended. Great chicken served about 30 ways. This combined with a friendly staff and a laid-back vibe makes iamiks a winner in my book!

main: Ipar’s Restaurante Y Bar De Tapas
title: Ipar's Restaurante Y Bar De Tapas
Sunburst
reviewr_text: Ah the place that started it all. This specific branch is the first branch that they opened and probably the only branch left that is owned by the original owner(s) (the other branches are owned by random franchisees). Up until now, many would flock towards this place(mostly locals) especially after going to church on a Sunday. They haven't changed much since I've been here ever since I can remember. The memories I've had since childhood will always be remembered. The feel/ambiance of it is just that of a classic diner especially with the checkered tablecloths. I usually order the classic (3pcs assorted chicken (you can choose your preferred cut) with potato wedges, coleslaw, and rice) or the prime cuts thigh (3pcs thigh with potato wedges, coleslaw, and rice). The chicken itself is good and flavorful enough without the need for gravy or any sauces but many usually dip it in ketchup or a mix of ketchup, worcestershire sauce, and hot sauce since it can enhance the flavor. Other than their chicken, they have choices of appetizers and others. Their liver and gizzard, chicken skin, and calamares(fried squid rings) are one of the popular ones. The sotanghon guisado in this specific branch is, in my opinion, better than the ones in other branches. Chop suey is always a crowd favorite if your looking for some veggies to add to your meal. I don't usually order dessert but my aunt usually orders their halo-halo(she likes it). Prices are reasonable but for those with a tight budget, they also offer combo/value meals(comprise of a mix of assorted dishes like chicken, noodles, and vegetables). If given a choice, as much as possible, I probably would prefer eating in this branch rather than the other branches located throughout Cebu but all of the branches are equally as good(it's just a personal preference).

title: Blue Elephant

title: Zubuchon
reviewr_text:
"The best pig, EVER!" -Anthony Bourdain, as proclaimed to Joel Binamira, the founder of Zubuchon, in a backyard, years before the restaurant was founded. With that same recipe, Zubuchon was born... and it's greatness, as declared by Bourdain, is one that I experienced... and have confirmed! 

You can order the classic pig, or boneless, by the "platter". A small platter stated to serve 2 and was P340. The *Fast Meal* sounded grander though as it did come with lechon, plus monggo soup, plain rice, and a side of acharra (fermented veggies). The serving of lechon came with two EXTRA crispy skins and a grand helping of luscious, melt-in-your-mouth and tasty pork. The monggo soup was quite savory and delicious, the chicharron on top giving it a bit of a crunchy texture. The added funk on the side with the acharra added another depth of flavoring. Multiple thumbs up with this meal... the lechon definitely shining! To keep the lechon as fresh as possible, lechon deliveries are made 2-3 times throughout the day. The dinner time lechon does deliver at 5pm, so if you come just before there is a chance it might not be ready yet, so do plan wisely!

With our appetites sated, we had to round off the meal with dessert. The *Zubuchon Dessert Platter* for P250 had all of the works -- leche flan, biko, budbud kabug, and two mango. Their biko was especially delectable and they made sure to drown it in brown sugar, haha. Everything was warm and yummy. We did indulge quite grandly here! There are several locations of Zubuchon. This one in the One Mango plaza is near some bars and karaoke bars, so I don't see why you couldn't hop over to them afterward.

title: Blue Elephant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"PatrickJ T."},{"reviewer_name":"Clydelle M."},{"reviewer_name":"Arnel E."},{"reviewer_name":"Dexter V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sandrine G."},{"reviewer_name":"Steve F."},{"reviewer_name":"PGreg H."},{"reviewer_name":"Dee S."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text:
How do you party it up in Cebu? Well you gather the whole family for a huge party at one of Cebu's rooftop spot.  It's no secret that rooftops get a bad rap here in the States because of idiots that think it's okay to act like a bunch of high schoolers at an elegant location with a view, but in Cebu I finally know what it means to party with people who actually have manners.  No overly rambunctious, rude hooligans just my huge family mingling it up with some foreigners and locals enjoying the scene.  Whatever others may rate it, in my book Blue Elephant at the Apple One Sky Lounge simply deserves nothing but a perfect five.  For giving my family a party to remember, Blue Elephant will be a prime spot for me every time I make my way to Cebu.

Blue Elephant is located on the 19th floor of a very prominent building near Ayala Mall in Cebu.  One thing to know beforehand is the importance to have a Visa card when you visit.  The reason is if you use Visa to pay for your visit then they wave the cover charge...so you better use your Visa. (Btw I am in no way working as a promoter for Visa; it's just my tip to help fellow travelers out.)  The décor of the building is very chic and modern.  I don't know how else to describe it but it's a typical rooftop.  What I mean is it has every element of a rooftop location: unparalleled view of the city below, neon and strobe lights throughout, tropical trees that add some greenery, and a DJ that's mixing Top 40s as well as other throwbacks.  Add to this some great servers and food coming out from the kitchen and you got a recipe for an awesome time.  I can only describe the scene so much but I feel that a picture can truly show the awesomeness better.

Now to the food.  Typical Asian flare with a bit of modern fusion touch.  I don't know what the dishes were to be exact because it was basically set for the party and on account that I had to be the obligatory hype man for the whole place which means I was too distracted to see what their menu entailed and see if I could match the dishes on the table.  But one thing that did stand out was their pad thai.  It was perfectly cooked and flavorful.  I literally had a whole plate...and then had another...and then one more for good measure.  Thankfully I was burning it off with some good ol' Dexter dancing.  Ya'll know what that looks like.  Another one was their seafood curry.  The dish had a delicate balance of curry flavor without overpowering the natural saltiness of the seafood.  Most importantly unlike other seafood curry that I've tried in the past, Blue Elephant's was not mushy.  There's nothing more unappetizing than mushy seafood curry.  Finally the third dish that I distinctly remembered was the Korean barbecue ribs.  My brother raved about how good it was and good thing I was able to grab my hands on a couple of pieces because the fam bam always beat me to.  As usual my bro knows his barbecue ribs.

I couldn't ask for a more amazing family.  I had not been back to the Philippines for almost two decades.  That is a long time not to see family back home.  So many things had changed but one thing has always remained the same.  No matter how long I had been gone, I never felt that I was a stranger.  It felt like we simply pushed life on pause and then hit play again.  And boy did we hit play.  I guess the reason why I party hardy is because of my family.  We press play and we press it hard.  And at Blue Elephant we did just that!

reviewr_text: Decent filipino food and prices are okay.  They do have a wide range of dishes to choose from and they do have some eclectic dishes like the noodles with squid ink.  They need more veggie choices by glad they made the Pinakbet vegetarian for me.

title: Tao Yuan
reviewr_text: Place is  excellent, food is great, traditional Chinese lauriat, Sharksfin soup, Lechon Macau , cold cuts, lapulapu beef broccoli . Place is clean and service is fast.

title: Red House Shabu Shabu
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Colby W."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Thomas K."},{"reviewer_name":"Angela L."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text:
One thing to remember.  Large portions are served.  We ordered the smaller dinner portion for 680P (I posted a photo of the dinner portion)and it was huge!  It was more than enough for 4 adults and one child.   They also have a area to create your own sauce,  which is fun.  If you don't want to make your sauce you can always ask the server make one.
I wish the broth had a bit more flavor but it was a bit mild for my taste.  It was a bit better once I added some sauce to it.

title: New Orleans
reviewr_text:
Want a taste of New Orleans in Cebu, Philippines?  You can get your wish at New Orleans restaurant at Ayala Center Mall at the Terraces.

When I think of New Orleans cuisine, I think of Jambalaya.  For some reason, though, none of us ordered their Jambalaya.  We started out with the Oysters which were yummy!!  My mother n'law liked her Fish N' Chips. The Salmon was enjoyed by my wife and also my brother n'law.  The Tuna Melt that I had was ok.  Was more like a Tuna burger though.  Fries were delicious.  The Mango Shake was large and really good!!  Speaking of large, all the portions were huge!!  We all had leftovers to enjoy the next day.

New Orleans restaurant is a fine choice at Ayala.  Worth finding out if you like them too.

title: Zark's Burgers
reviewr_text: Solid burger place considering the prices. Only $3, 150 php for most burgers and a good selection of fries, with the burger or separately. Word of advice, ask for medium well, otherwise you will get medium rare. Normally I would be OK with that, but not while traveling, don't want to take chances. Great service, good food.

title: Cebu's Original Lechon Belly
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jefferson S."},{"reviewer_name":"Abbys A."},{"reviewer_name":"Gio G."},{"reviewer_name":"Gil M."},{"reviewer_name":"Anneke D."},{"reviewer_name":"Barry T."},{"reviewer_name":"Maputing E."},{"reviewer_name":"Mike M."},{"reviewer_name":"Swan L."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."}]
reviewr_text:
Cebu City is known for their tasty lechon and if you want to sample one of the best (atleast in my opinion), then this is where you should go!

Cebu's Original Lechon Belly offers both original and spicy versions of the fabled roasted pig. There are other things in the menu like the corned beef stew that's just as delicious as the lechon. Don't worry about the price too much as it's definitely worth it. 

Expect to pay around php500.00 for 1/2 kilo lechon, 1.5L aoda and then some puso (steamed rice in a ball of coconut leaves). The meal should be enough for 3 person so still pretty affordable!

reviewr_text: Service and Wi-Fi excellent superfast and the cheesesteak sandwiches to die for if you're in Cebu you better come here you will not regret it

title: Cafe Bai
reviewr_text:
Breakfast buffet for two people was included in our 1 night stay at Bai Hotel in Mandaue, Cebu.  The buffet was at the hotel's Cafe Bai on the 2nd floor.  The venue was very large.  The restaurant was so clean, really spacious, and the staff was top notch.  

The buffet choices were more than I am used to.  We don't have as many entree choices as Cafe Bai had in my hometown in California.  They cater to an international clientele.  They had food stations for a multitude of cuisines such as Japanese, Korean, Chinese, Indian, Western, and Filipino.  Literally something for everyone.  My favorite choices were the Filipino dishes.

I would love to dine at their Breakfast Buffet during future visits to Cebu.  So worth the value!

title: Cafe Sarree
reviewr_text:
We woke up a little later than usual and we were ready to get some breakfast. We stayed at Escario Central Hotel so this place was very convenient to get to. Just across the way. 

I originally wanted to order a white cafe mocha but the waitress stated its not available. uhmm ok, aren't you a cafe? Anyway we end up getting the caramel latte and it was on the small side. I guess I'm used to having a huge cup of java so when I see a cute little cup, it tends to be on the tiny side to me. Anyway the latte came in a clear glass cup and you can see the layers of ingredients. It was nice. The flavor didn't have a wow factor to it. Back home I brew my own and have a whole fridge full of torani syrups and ID creamers stocked up, so when i order or make a certain flavor I expect that flavor to be very apparent. This was like coffee made from a regular coffee maker and they quickly threw some flavorings in it. But hey atleast there was a little bit of coffee art. Anyway a caffeine addict is a caffeine addict I quickly consumed my cup despite the lack of flavor.

We ordered the "fancy loaded french toast" and "Sausage" meals, and what they lack in taste in their coffe made up for in their food. The french toast was huge and the condiments were separatly organized on the plate. I took a bite and the crunch was heaven, french toast was not soggy. yay! Inside filling was ham and cheese. So it was like a french toast sandwhich. Ham was a little greasy and dry and didn't seem fresh, but the french toast exterior was very good. I tried my wife's hungarian sausage plate and it was reminescent of the State Fair of Texas. Sausage on a stick. Packed of flavor! She was also pleased with her selection.

Service was a little slow despite that there weren't any other customers. Waitresses were friendly. I did notice that when we arrived one customer was leaving and the a/c blew cold, however when he left they turned down the a/c. Like uhmm ok are we to have less a/c? *shrugs* They gave us a clicker thing to ring them when I needed something, it made me feel awkward because it was like the remote control to their doorbell. The bell sound echoed throughout their cafe.  Overall I'd come back again and try their other menu items, but they need to improve in their coffee offerings both in taste and availability. 

Tip: They accept credit cards.

reviewr_text:
Get yo glove on and order up a kilo of that killa belly!

On my first visit, didn't know what to expect. 

Then they handed me a plate of boneless lechon and a plastic glove and I immediately understood.

By the third visit in three days I was pretty hooked.

It's not the best lechon you've ever had, but it's pretty darn good.

I'll be back.

reviewr_text:
Been a regular since my CHILDHOOD. 
Now I am an adult, and Kanyoen has never failed my expectations. Even after visiting Japan, nothing has topped this yakiniku restaurant for its high quality meat and it's unbeatable sauce. I hope the restaurant remains open for even my grandchildren to experience.

title: Veranda Restobar
reviewr_text: The best kept secret in cebu serving the best cebuano fare.  The maskara (fried pig's head), the inun-unan tasik, and the halang-halang are a must try.

title: Sunburst
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Britt H."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Nina M."},{"reviewer_name":"Stewart O."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."}]
reviewr_text:
Sunburst has undoubtedly one if not Cebu's best tasting chicken! There is something about their chicken's crispy coating and juicy meat that makes it one of the best fried chicken you probably will taste in your lifetime. 

Though I've given them a perfect score, one of their service crew was actually quite rude. I came in and was given a look that seem to gauge if I could afford to eat there.. The nerve! 

Anyway, it's a good thing I loved their chicken or else I could have given them one star!

title: rai rai ken
reviewr_text:
Great affordable place to get ramen soup or filipino fusion ramen soup, like batchoy.  Broth was good and not oily. Tasty and salty. Toppings were the right portion based on the amount of noodles in the bowl.  You can get it in plain, miso, spicy.  Check out the menu pics I uploaded for more choices!

Great ambiance, the place is nicely decorated Asian ramen style theme. They have private rooms as well.

They do not serve alcohol.

title: 10 Doves Street
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Kristen T."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Hazel L."},{"reviewer_name":"ravi b."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Myles C."}]
reviewr_text: Awesome gelato and cakes in a really IG pic worthy place. Clean eating area with friendly and attentive staff. The carrot cake was a hit (not too sweet) that my mom ordered 2 more cakes to go. I enjoyed the chocolate decadence gelato while my sister and bro in law enjoyed the smores cake.

title: Alberto’s Pizza Mabolo Branch
reviewr_text:
Alberto's Pizza... what an experience. I cannot compare it to American-style pizza and be fair so I will just say that if you are on a budget, it's late night, or you are drunk, Alberto's may be a good enough choice.

We were hungry after midnight tonight and I am happy that I had the experience of going there and having pizza with a ton of locals. That said, I definitely won't go back. I'd also like to add however that a lot of our Filipino officemates actually really like it so... There's that.

3-stars to be fair and for the experience with a note that most westerners probably won't be into Alberto's.

Won't see ya there.

title: Spice Fusion
reviewr_text: This place has two locations, the other one is in crossroads mall. Singaporean themed but as the name says its a fusion. i'm good with their white chicken dish, though the crab cakes kinda mora like a pancake, not enough crab, if you are used to the typical crabcake. Other than that thier dishes usually tasty.

title: Dimsum Break
reviewr_text: One of the better Dimsum Break locations in the area. Food usually tastes good and its appearance usually ok. Staff is attentive and diligent. I recommend the pork steam rice, siomai, bucci, and bola bola siopao.

reviewr_text: Food is terrible - bland. Chicken tastes like it's made from powder.  Small selection of drinks (canned). Do not eat here.

title: Joed's Lutong Hapon
reviewr_text:
Imagine tasty and juicy bacon with thicker and bigger slices because that's how this place's chashu pork dish was for me. It was good AF and definitely a diet killer haha.

Although I had my doubts at first upon seeing all those "fats" on the meat, it actually tasted so freaking good but be prepared for the guilt trip right after for consuming all those calories. 

To be honest, there are prolly a lot more healthier options on the menu but for a once-in-a-blue-moon treat or a cheat day run, I don't think anyone could go wrong with this.

Oh yeah, pair it with miso soup because you know, you prolly need some soup to down all those deliciousness.

reviewr_text: This place considered higher end chinese restaurant. Food and service pretty good.  We went with some dim sum dishes, siomai, spicy tofu, minces meat with eggplant, and a squid dish. The tofu dish had a great smooth texture and i was told that they make their own.

title: Phat Pho
reviewr_text:
Visiting Cebu for the holidays and walking around IT park, my sister, niece and I decided to have Vietnamese for dinner. The place is clean and atmosphere is cozy. Our servers, Robie and Evangeline were very attentive and polite. While waiting for our food, we heard a woman's voice who sounded like she was throwing a fit in the kitchen. I asked Robie, the head waiter what was going on because I sensed that the other customers were quite tense and uncertain as to what was going on in the kitchen. It was truly a very unprofessional demeanor from LESLIE, the head chef. She was practically yelling at the top of her lungs to the kitchen staff and it made the other servers feel very awkward.
Other than this very unpleasant experience, the food was very good.  I would highly recommend this place.

title: Cafe Racer
reviewr_text:
The ambiance to this place is awesome, especially if you are a motor head. Oil drums have been converted into chairs, vw mini into cash register and beverage bar, a vw beetle with the front half turned into a outside barbecue and the other half a seating booth. The food is a mix of american and asian from grilled cheese to squid balls. 
imho, a place worth checking out especially in the evenings.

main: Murray’s New Orleans Bourbon Street Steak and Oysters
title: Murray's New Orleans Bourbon Street Steak and Oysters
reviewr_text: We had a late lunch for two here today. First time to stop in. We had such a hard time deciding on our selection due to all sounding so good. We had two styles of oyster appetizers and both were awesom....especially the carnival oysters. I had the full rack ribs....delicious and tender and she had the pasta dish, also delicious. Service was right on....fast, courteous and offered recommendations....very friendly. Also worthy of mention is the fresh squeezed lemonade and fantastic basic margarita. We really enjoyed this restaurant, the food and the service.

title: Hukad sa Golden Cowrie
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jonny M."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert N."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael H."},{"reviewer_name":"Totong B."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jenny C."},{"reviewer_name":"Swan L."},{"reviewer_name":"Emma D."},{"reviewer_name":"Keisha R."},{"reviewer_name":"Liza M."},{"reviewer_name":"Thomas L."},{"reviewer_name":"Nataraki T."}]
reviewr_text: A busy, bustling restaurant in the Ayala shopping mall with tasty traditional Filipino dishes. In the Philippines, vegetables are hard to come by, so we jumped at the eggplant dish. It was far from providing the fresh, clean salad feel that we were craving, but was an excellent dish nonetheless. The eggplant was cooked until it was tender and the sauce gave us that savory comfort feel. Their star dish has to be the fried pork leg. The crunch on the skin in contrast to the juicy tender meat was to die for. Unfortunately the pork sisig was a bit of a let down, we asked for extra crispy sisig, but even after letting it cook for a while on the sizzling platter, it was still mushy in texture (though not lacking in flavor). The servers walk around with white rice to help wash down all the richness.

title: Pakû
reviewr_text: It's unlimited chicken wings and unlimited rice! The food is great. I recommend the cream cheese, barbecue and mango wasabi. They also have unlimited iced tea drinks. You can also ask for all the favors and they'll give you two plates of assorted flavors!

title: Vikings

reviewr_text: One of the top dining experiences I usually get from hotels. Now affordable at Vikings. A selection of Japanese, Chinese, Italian, Filipino, American and Spanish cuisine prepared by chefs for the enjoyment of many. Vikings is the top notch buffet place in Cebu

title: Tao Yuan
reviewr_text: My family frequents here everytime there's an occasion. Their food is as authentic as it gets and they are very consistent on their food as well. The service, what can I say, superb. They also accept reservations, so you can call them ahead of time to reserve a table especially on a busy day. You can bring your own bottle of liquor here but you need to pay the corkage fee. What I like here is their seafood, it's fresh and cooked to your liking. I would definitely recommend this place.

title: Tymad Bistro
reviewr_text:
SO GOOD.

I love the photos on the wall and the books along the booth tables. There is a bright indoor area and a very spacious patio. 

Try the french kouign-Amann. It's like a croissant but 10x better. 

Chef Philippe is so warm and welcoming including his smiling staff! I witnessed a lot of local French friends coming in and out of the store to eat and relax as well. I felt very at home and like family! 

If you want traditional French breakfast of all sorts, crepes, eggs Benedict, pastries, illy coffee,   Etc, this place is not to be missed.

reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"David P."},{"reviewer_name":"Gregory C."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Danie S."},{"reviewer_name":"Erica V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Jennelle L."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Jo Anne G."},{"reviewer_name":"Laura A."},{"reviewer_name":"Rocky Betty Jo P."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco F."}]
reviewr_text:
Came here for dinner and always wanted to see what the commotion is about. 

I really like their garlic butter flavor for their shrimp and crab. It's addictive.

Not all the seafood is under the all you can eat price. Some are a premium.

Also there are no leftovers.   They will charge you double.

title: Vue Dine & Drink
reviewr_text: Great place open until midnight every day of the week. Get the Cajun Pork Chop (which is actually a hefty cut of meat--pork chop, country rib, and even a little pork belly all in one). And don't needless to keep the drinks coming until close!

title: Harbour City Dimsum House
reviewr_text:
One of my favorites places to visit when I was still living in Cebu so I was really excited to go back and drag my siblings to try it again.

Got disappointed. 
Food quality was not back 20 years ago, or maybe it was just wishful thinking that it will be the same after all these years.

title: Puso Bistro and Bar

main: Ipar’s Restaurante Y Bar De Tapas
title: Ipar's Restaurante Y Bar De Tapas
reviewr_text:
Authentic and delicious Basque Spanish cuisine! My brother and I were in town from the US for a week in the city, and saw this place well reviewed on other sites. Went and didn't regret it. Noted it hadn't been put on Yelp yet, but it deserves it so here it is! 
We got single portion Paella which takes a while to make, but is worth the wait! Enjoyed local craft beers and the house sangria which were top notch, and got to appreciate appetizers (garlic soup and chicken croquettes) and dessert (caramel flan) on either side of the main meal--all delish.
The design and execution of this place is also among the best we've seen in our restaurant thing adventures here in Cebu, we highly recommend this place!

title: Kimstaurant
reviewr_text: This is one of the best food places I've been to.  Prices are reasonable and the food is tasty plus good portions.  The tofu stew has a real kick but still enjoyed it.  Plus the food is prepared pretty fast which is another plus. They also give out free ice cream.

title: Hukad sa Golden Cowrie
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jonny M."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert N."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael H."},{"reviewer_name":"Totong B."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jenny C."},{"reviewer_name":"Swan L."},{"reviewer_name":"Emma D."},{"reviewer_name":"Keisha R."},{"reviewer_name":"Liza M."},{"reviewer_name":"Thomas L."},{"reviewer_name":"Nataraki T."}]
reviewr_text: I so wanted to give a good review but my experience cannot justify more than 2 stars. The welcoming person outside is good. She has mastered customer service but once we are in, it went downhill. First, I got the the chipped/broken sauce square implement, looks sharp and unsafe but I can live with that.  Living on the edge baby! There were 8 of us, and all drinks were provided except the easiest 1, the 3 glasses of calamansi juice. When it came, I did not get one, all the rest got theirs, why? It's a matter of simple math or just being aware that all have drinks except 1 and we have 3 attempts to get the waiters attention, 3 attempts until we got one's attention. It's early Friday night, we arrive around 5 pm but didn't really start eating until past 6 pm. We got our food in installments, even the Supposedly unlimited rice. He gave some of us but not all but saw the guy give in other table also. Why? Some of our food got cold while we wait for more dishes to come. I remember I ordered calamari that never came. The crispy para came last just when I got full. Most of the food tastes good but I was so hungry then that I question my judgment on food taste. Price and food are average so nothing really stands out that makes it worth the wait and irritation I felt. Maybe others have a different experience but I'm not going back. Location is nice in Ayala mall.

title: House of Lechon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Winlee W."},{"reviewer_name":"Carissa C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Evee N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joan N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gloria C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christy S."},{"reviewer_name":"Lina C."},{"reviewer_name":"Mark H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jonnah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Derek W."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Benedict A."},{"reviewer_name":"Lynne C."}]
reviewr_text:
I dined here, with a group of friends, on our first day in Cebu. I had high expectations for this place, especially since the restaurant itself is called House of Lechon, but I have to say that the lechon did not meet my expectations. Don't get me wrong, the lechon had the crispy skin (which is nothing but deliciousness), and the meat itself was juicy, but I was hoping that it would have some more flavor on it's own. The dipping sauces are what really gives it its flavor. Put that over rice and you're good to go. 

The other dishes we ordered were average. I can't remember everything that we ordered, but it wasn't too impressive. Since my mom is originally from Bichol, and since I'm kinda biased on how it [the dish] should taste, I made sure that I didn't order the Bichol express here. I had Bicol express at another restaurant elsewhere in Visayas and was highly underwhelmed by it. To avoid a repeat of that, I made sure I didn't order it. Looking back at it now, I wouldn't mind trying it if I do dine here again. The halo halo shake, on the other hand, was a nice treat to enjoy with my meal. I still prefer the actual halo halo dessert though.

As with most places in the Philippines, the staff we interacted with were very friendly, polite, and helpful.

Overall, I had a good dining experience here, however I wasn't too impressed with the food. I wouldn't mind giving this restaurant another try though.

title: The Pig & Palm
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Tricie C."},{"reviewer_name":"Jacob C."},{"reviewer_name":"Kevin G."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Daniel S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kristine S."},{"reviewer_name":"Carl I."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Dan P."},{"reviewer_name":"Cynthia Q."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text: I have absolutely NO idea why this place is ranked poorly. Yes it's a pricey penny but when the chef is a Michelin rated for good reason and the food and drinks are incredible, it's absolutely worth the price. I've come here plenty of times and have been impressed by the food. Things definitely that you can't miss are the croquettes, Korean fried chicken, and the toffee cake. Also huge kudos to the fantastic bartender because their drinks are some of the most well made in the entire city. I've finally tried all their specialty cocktails and love Dill or No Dill and Coff' Medicine the most. McBanDaq and Milk & Honey also have fantastic presentation so definitely give it a shot.

title: Abaca Baking Company
reviewr_text:
Going to Abaca Baking Company at Ayala Center Mall in Cebu City was like going to a restaurant in the United States.  Luncheonette Burger was exceptional!  Bakery Benedict was very very good too!!!

Abaca Baking Company is a taste of the U.S.A in the Philippines with the prices to match.  Great place to try if you can afford to splurge.

title: Gerry's Grill
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Val Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Erika R."},{"reviewer_name":"Paula C."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."},{"reviewer_name":"Dfrancisco G."},{"reviewer_name":"Phil O."}]
reviewr_text:
If I could fine every restaurant in this company in Yelp I will review all of them no star! Poor management, worker are sooooooo slow! They let us set the table for 30 minutes without menu, most of the wait staff was just chatting. 

Any way this is my second time I visited the restaurant but the 2nd I think I will never give them my business. I won't recommend this place, food sucks, waiter/ waitress have no manners, no manager  in a restaurant?! Never coming to any of this restaurant !

title: Jollibee
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Naomi O."},{"reviewer_name":"Shaima C."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Yochanan H."},{"reviewer_name":"Paulamertha A."},{"reviewer_name":"Travis M."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."}]
reviewr_text:
So, the oddest thing I had in Cebu was Jollibee's Amazing Aloha burger. A massive Pineapple slice overwhelmed the entire thing. 

I lived in Hawaii for four years, & never witnessed anything close to this; yes, we have pineapple & pork, pineapple on pizza, but hamburger and not cooked? NO!!! On a side note, the fries were good. 

Next, this location only took cash, no credit cards. So, it was like the 1980s in America. 

Finally, the service was blah, since they don't really make any suggestions. They just look at you rather puzzled, since everyone in the Philippines is familiar with this restaurant chain. However, it had been over 25 years since I have been in the Philippines. 

If you want to play it safe, stick with their version of fried chicken. It is called Chicken Joy Joy. Unlike American chains like KFC, Lee's, Church's and so forth that batter the chicken twice, Jollibee only has a thin coat. Perhaps, it is healthier, but still it's deep fried.

Finally, I would not recommend the spaghetti, since the sauce is like ketchup. In addition, the sauce has a hotdog cut up in it. Another oddity but a low budget addition; remember, you're in the Philippines at their version of a fast food restaurant chain. A lot of people go without in this country. When you're hungry you'll eat just about anything including an Amazing Aloha Burger.

title: Abuhan
reviewr_text: If you enjoy waiting 30 minutes for your order and the food arrives cold, at above average prices for this area, then Abuhan is the place for you. Requested ketchup for the stale, cold, soggy french fries, and after 5 minutes I went over to ask in person. Also requested Mang Tomas Sauce, was told they don't have it..in a filipino restaurant? Really? Beverages were too sweet, no table attention, loudmouth patrons seated at next table...need I say more? Huge restaurant, few patrons...I could see why.

title: Ulli's
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Jini O."},{"reviewer_name":"Jo Anne G."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Lisa K."}]
reviewr_text:
If you want something light, quick and cheap then this is the place to go.

It's outside on the top floor of ayala and they have soup, appetizers, meat and stone bowl. 

It's all asian food but different kinds which is also good when you want more choices.

The stone bowl is pretty good. I'd come back for sure.

title: Harbour City Dim Sum
reviewr_text:
Even lowering my standards already, it was terrible. We were craving some Chinese food, particularly chicken feet ao we decided to give this place a try. 

Everything was overly salty, and service was soooo slow. Beer was warm, fried rice was dry, veggies were greasy. 

Honestly couldn't wait to pay the bill and leave.

title: Tokyo Table
reviewr_text:
This buffet is located at City Time Square in Mandaue across from Park Mall. Once you enter City Times Square head towards the end and you'll find Tokyo Table.

Upon reading some reviews, I called to confirm their promotion where a birthday celebrant is complimentary. I called and advised that the birthday celebrant's birthday will be the following day but intend to celebrate it the day before. The man stated that as long as there were atleast 2 paying adults per 1 birthday celebrant, then indeed, they were complimentary. I asked to reconfirm and he stated, "yes, birthday month is ok". So off we went. I also notice that there was a 10% discount for checking in using yelp.

We arrived at about 6:30 pm. I advised I called earlier on the day regarding the birthday promo and said the birthday girl was with us in tow. 5 adults in total. She then said oh there needs to be 6 of you for the birthday celebrant to be free. I said thats not what I was told earlier. So she went to ask some other male receptionist as I stated I spoke with a man earlier. Long story short, There was only 5 of us so depsite the wrong info, everyone was charged including the birthday girl. I then showed them the yelp check in promo then they stated it was expired. By then I was like what in the %$*!! Anyway at 740 per person weekday dinner, paying for one other person was not gonna break the bank. It was just disappointing that one has to mislead the public in order for people to eat here. They asked for the birthday girl's i.d., which we gave, and she still had to pay. *womp womp* What was the point of asking for her identification if you still weren't going to honor your promo. Now on to the food.

Variety was way better than most other buffets in Cebu that I've tried. They had a mix of Filipino, Korean, Chinese, but mostly Japanese offerings. Everything I tasted was hot and flavorful. We opted to do hot pot but realized there was what they call a "mookata" (a heating utensil to cook both hotpot and yakiniku at the same time). Sadly, we only found out about the mookata at the end of the meal while sitting around trying to decide if we were gonna have another go at it. They also had a good selection of desserts that included my favorite, bread pudding. Their bread pudding was moist but lacked the custom bourbon or whisky sauce. It did have sauce though, just not sure what kind. The sushi had a different taste than what I've grown accustomed to. They added some kind of mushroom or something in one of their maki rolls. Haven't had that before (tasted strange). Their hot pot broth (we chose chicken) was seasoned a little salty but didn't mind it since we had veggies in there. Charge included drinks (even unlimited refills of San Miguel Beer, on tap) We asked for hot green tea, but stated it will be an additional 60 pesos added to the buffet price, but that you may have unlimited refills. I noticed at about 8:30ish the staff started putting up dinnerware. I thought they closed at 10 pm. *shrugs* I find it rude to be doing this while many patrons are still dining. Strange etiquette indeed.

Despite the annoyance in the beginning, food quality was pretty good and even rivaled with hotel buffets. Should you need to call them, I advise to ask for the person's name of whom you spoke with before hanging up to avoid a similar situation I endured. However, Jennabeth (receptionist lady) was very professional and warm. She was apologetic at the end. (Thank you for that, Jennabeth!) 

Restroom stalls are super tiny in the lady's room. So just an fyi if your used to Texas standard size restroom stalls. They also had only one sink. Are we to wait in line whilst someone is doing there makeup in front of said sink?!? *rolls eyes*

Free wifi, ask a waiter or waitress for the password. 20 pesos was charged for parking as you leave City Time Square.

reviewr_text: Great place for bbq especially if your on a budget or bringing the whole gang with you. This place is clean and bbq is great a lot of selection of meat. And friendly service. Highly recommended to anyone who wants to stop by here.

title: La Maison Rose
reviewr_text:
"oooh la la" One of he made up french expressions I know. French food is a new arena for me..It started trying macarons and now its moved on to French food. La maison is located in Lahug and has a pleasant, cozy, experience..its like your visiting someone's house. The decor which has hints of chinese makes me think of the phrase "French Shanghai." They do offer set menus at a reasonable price  if your not sure what to get. A notable feature is there use of ipads as menus and the staff are friendly enough to assist you in making choices. Fortunately the menu does have pictures and descriptions to decide.

On this first visit, I decided to order the pink peppered duck and a chocolate dessert. Again, I'm not an expert but it did taste delicious. I was told that the duck itself came from France so upon hearing that, I decided to order it. The duck was cooked well and to my satisfaction. The chocolate dessert was reminiscent of a warm brownie but it also was good.

They serve lunch and dinner at certain time frames but offer drinks and dessert throughout the whole day. A pleasant and tasty place to unwind and enjoy a good meal. Take note they advise making reservations if you decide to attend for dinner. The seating capacity is not that big which makes for a cozy experience.

title: Chow King
reviewr_text: This place just opened today. Its fast food chinese. This used ro be a favorite for me until most locations have seen to lowered their quality control. Hoping for a decent meal today. I usually go with the bolax2 siopao.

title: Cooee
reviewr_text:
This delicious healthy spot saved the day when I needed a vegan meal after a day's worth of heavy meaty dishes. It seems like there is a small trend of those who are subconscious of taking healthier options here in Cebu.

Cooee is serves fruit and veggie meals and drinks with that millennial trend of fruit bowls and salads. The portions are huge and worth the price. I could barely finish my fruit bowl with pureed kale. All in all, it was a delicious vegan meal that stood out in the general area. They have some meat dishes as well like silogs but the focus is fruits and vegetables.

Lots of seating.
Picture worthy.
Lots of options for those in search of clean eating.

Mangaon ta!

title: Zubuchon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Jacques I."},{"reviewer_name":"Tellie N."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Ron Z."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Lillian C."},{"reviewer_name":"Linda P."},{"reviewer_name":"Benjamin C."},{"reviewer_name":"Cris T."},{"reviewer_name":"David L."},{"reviewer_name":"Kathrine P."},{"reviewer_name":"John A."},{"reviewer_name":"Barry T."},{"reviewer_name":"Aileen B."},{"reviewer_name":"Angeli Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Ian Maren C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Geoffrey U."}]
reviewr_text:
Cebu is known for their lechon and cebuchon. So, first stop since we landed to Cebu decided to go here, they are famous for cebuchon. 
Came in around 3-4pm and sever informed us that they are out of cebuchon the deliver will come in at at 5-530pm. Since we're so hungry we just got other item on the menu. 
Ordered: Zebuchon sisig- very spicy and serving is small, good for one person only. 
Lechon sinigang -  is my favorite, taste very authentic. 
Monggo with Zebuchon  - it comes with cebuchon, good for cold weather. 
Adobong kangkong at chicharon - another favorite dish, very tasty and good combination with chicharon.
Fresh buko juice - its not cold, so disappointing
Mango shake and buko shake - very refreshing  
As we finish our order our server informed us they just got their delivery of cebuchon so, we got some for to go. Ate it the next day and just heat it up on microwave, oh my goodness is  very delicious and juicy.
Costumer service is good, friendly, and approachable.

title: Gibbs Hot Wings
reviewr_text: A popular hangout place, great for hanging out with the boyz. Wings are pretty good, i went with level 2 wings. Staff was very accomodating.

title: The Ching Palace
reviewr_text: I am a fan of this place.  It is not the fanciest and some dishes are better than others but I like that this place has been around for a while and the Chinese community endorses it.  To me that counts. The food is the typical chinese  fare.  I particularly like their seafood taro.  They have live seafood.  Service is good and also they have separate rooms for parties.  I have seen people celebrating weddings, birthdays and baptisms.  Everytime I'm in Cebu I pay a visit at least once.

title: Grand Majestic
reviewr_text:
So my brother and his family decided that we should further stuff our faces at Ayala Mall before heading out for the day.  I had said that I wanted some delicious halo-halo and well this place delivered on that promise.  What made this experience unique was the way their halo-halo is made.  I've never had this type of halo-halo and after the experience I don't think I can go back to a normal one.  Let me elaborate further.  This place may not serve the most stuffed halo-halo nor the largest I've ever eaten but it certainly has something going for it.  If you take a look at the pictures you can clearly see that the shaved ice that the halo-halo is famous for is completely made up of the flavor you order.  That's right all of the shaved ice is flavored ube or mango.  You just don't get a dalop of ice cream at the top--you get the whole halo-halo as the ice cream.  Incredible is an understatement.  Once everything gets mixed it is simply unbelievable the flavor this dessert packs. Like I said going back to a "normal" halo-halo will be really hard. 

Oh FYI for those that have been reading and wondering what halo-halo is don't fret I shall tell you.  This amazing concoction is a Filipino dessert consisting of shaved ice, palm fruit, jackfruit, coconut gel, other mixed fruits, sweet beans, flan, and topped off with ice cream that's either ube (sweet purple yam) or mango.  You then have the task of mixing it all together and trust me it's worth it at the end.

Anyways, I can only comment on the halo-halo at this restaurant because that's all I had.  We had eaten at a nearby restaurant already before coming here.  But based on my experience and the happy faces all around its a great place to grab a bite if even for just some dessert!

title: Luy's Classic Tea House
reviewr_text:
One of the most authentic chinese restaurants ive tried thanks to my cousin who brought us here 2 years ago. Until today, taste of their food is still very good.

We always get the shrimp dumplings and the soup dumplings. Dip them in chili sauce and wow! Delicious! The seafood is always fresh. They have live fish, lobster, and even eel that you can pick from outside. May not be a good idea for animal
lovers though or for anyone not into that sort of thing, i mean seeing that their meal was alive just a few minutes ago.

But anyway, their food is really flavorful. And from what i hear, chefs are really from places such as hongkong etc and so the taste they put into their food is really authentic chinese. I got to try the spinach soup today too and it was surprisingly really good! They added egg, tofu and shrimp so it tasted more like a healthy egg drop! I loved it!  Gotta check this place out if you havent yet.

title: Birdseed
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"John L."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Maya S."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Alan S."},{"reviewer_name":"Carl V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Rustum N."},{"reviewer_name":"Cha S."},{"reviewer_name":"ravi b."},{"reviewer_name":"Paula T."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris M."},{"reviewer_name":"Pablo G."}]
reviewr_text:
The restaurant was located back behind BK in Vibo Place on Escario, and it was nice and quiet there despite the busy traffic out front. 

Service was quick and we were seated promptly. Waitress was courteous and eager to please.

Food: We both ordered the eggs benedict, and although the food was only warm, it was well seasoned. The poached eggs were perfectly cooked and the hollandaise sauce was good. I also ordered peach tea, which was reminiscent of P.F. Chang's dragon oolong tea back home in the States. My wife ordered a cappuccino which had a cute shaped heart in the center. 

2nd visit: We ordered the breakfast skillet and the beef brisket with kimichi. We're from Texas so we have a certain expectation when it comes to brisket. Yup, nope it's no Texas brisket but hey it still packed its own special flavor. Brisket was tender and moist. The breakfast skillet came with potatoes, tomatoes, spinach, bacon and some wonderfully flavored sausage. At first glance I thought to myself, " whattt Texas toast!!" but nope it was french toast. French toast was on the soggy side though. For beverages we ordered a mango caramel shake, which was soo good and the peach tea again.

The only complaint we had was that the food came out warm and not piping hot. ( 2nd visit was better, food arrived hot). Otherwise, We'll be back again to try their other offerings.

Tip: They have wifi and they accept credit cards.

title: Ramen Yushoken
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Angela L."},{"reviewer_name":"Gio G."},{"reviewer_name":"Dani S."},{"reviewer_name":"Zerra Mae Lyka L."},{"reviewer_name":"Judy J."}]
reviewr_text:
I came here twice and ordered hiyashi chuka (cold noodle) and the first time I ate it, the taste is really good and the ingredients are abundant but in the middle of my meal, I found a strand of black hair inside my noodle. I got grossed out and didn't finish it.

Since I love the cold noodle, I came back second time to give them another chance and this time, the noodles were way too hard and undercooked but they claim that's how they make it. I refused to eat because I'm afraid I might get stomach ache. Barely took 2 bites but it took them so long to finally decide to recook that dish for me. 

Love this place but just not that confident in the consistency in their preparation of food.

title: Manila Foodshoppe
reviewr_text:
This place is only one word: Lumi. Yup, they have one of the best lumi. This business used to be called Manila Restaurant located at Manalili st. Even though it's good, it's not like what it use to be. The flavor is almost as good as before but the meat content has significantly decreased. They've dumbed down their best menu. I remember when the soup was so thick and flavorful, now it's somewhat saturated. Their grilled pork belly was surprisingly good, and so is the siopao, which was soft and was adequately stuffed with meat.

Don't expect quality service though. Also better get your own tissue or napkin as theirs is so minute and thin, you have to use three pieces to wipe smudges or else it'll just shred.

I tried editing the business info as this is located at Mandaue City, Cebu, not Manila. It is in Parkmall of Mandaue. The yelp moderator hasn't paid attention to this yet.

reviewr_text:
Fell in love most specially to their Japanese ambience. I recommend you try their outdoor venue.

When we found the place a guy immediately assisted us to the place where we will park. Thereafter, he instantly told us that we were in table 6. The staff here are polite and very attentive even when the place is full packed.

We got Noukou Korretti ramen which was already good for two! They allow sharing so it's a real bonus for me and my boyfriend because I usually can't eat a whole Ramen. The broth was really good! The takoyaki was also good, and exceptional. We also tried their yakisoba, and gyoza which were also good. 

You'll experience a glimpse of Japan, once you'll come here for a good price!

title: Zubuchon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Jacques I."},{"reviewer_name":"Tellie N."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Ron Z."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Lillian C."},{"reviewer_name":"Linda P."},{"reviewer_name":"Benjamin C."},{"reviewer_name":"Cris T."},{"reviewer_name":"David L."},{"reviewer_name":"Kathrine P."},{"reviewer_name":"John A."},{"reviewer_name":"Barry T."},{"reviewer_name":"Aileen B."},{"reviewer_name":"Angeli Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Ian Maren C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Geoffrey U."}]
reviewr_text:
Zubuchon was the best part about visiting Cebu.  Seriously.  We came here because how could we not?  Anthony Bourdain recommended it and when Anthony Bourdain recommends something then it's an instant must!  Plus, this was super close to our hotel. 

Since we spent most of the day traveling, we didn't eat lunch,;so came here for a late meal around 4pm.  Because of so, we were the only ones dining in and as we were deliberating about what size of lechon to order, our server overheard us and told us that lechon is only available at dinner, an hour and a half away.  NOOO!  We clearly started to panic, which is when another employee got scared and said to our server that they had it so could serve it.  Thank the lawwwd.

Although the menu recommends a small lechon for two people, we ordered the medium size because we are fat Americans.  We also ordered a side of Pancit with Lechon and Eggplant Salad.  Nothing took long to make. 

Pancit with Lechon is Pancit Canton with pieces of lechon tossed throughout, and it was sooo good!  Obviously, I loved the bites of lechon the most, but the the egg noodles and veggies were scrumptious.  And it wasn't too salty or heavily sauced, which I appreciated.  Eggplant Salad was also very good, with a nice citrus flavor that complemented the smokiness of all the roasted pig we ate.  And speaking of, the lechon was uh-may-zzziiiing!  I knew it was gonna be good, but I didn't know it was gonna be THAT good!  The lechon was perfectly roasted, creating a tender, juicy meat with every morsel of a bite, and I loved that it was not overly salted, letting the pig do its thang.  And do not even think about skipping out on the crispy skin.  The crackle with the meat makes it all the more heavenly.  Like I said before, we ordered the medium size for two of us.  But pretttttty sure we coulda slaughtered a large size.  Do yourself a favor and just get the large size lechon.  Don't live in regret like me. 

Zubuchon was one of the best meals I had in the Philippines!  The lechon is what to order.  A large size at that.  Actually, scratch that.  Order a whole roasted pig, which you can actually do here!  Pork it up and get some of the wonderful sides to go with.  And lightly add some vinegar and calamansi to top it off.  Peace.  *Mic drop*

title: Top of Cebu
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco R."},{"reviewer_name":"Caitlin M."},{"reviewer_name":"Sivilay T."},{"reviewer_name":"Tawny T."},{"reviewer_name":"Kartik K."}]
reviewr_text:
Review #043 - 2019

This was also another spot that I requested our tour guide to bring us to and I was not disappointed at all.

We showed up around 12:30 PM for lunch.

The five of us were seated immediately as the place wasn't too busy.

I ordered the aligue rice and the grilled pork belly as my main entree to share with daughter while the three guests ordered their own items to share.

I really enjoyed both of the items I ordered.  I also got to try the sizzling sinigang from their order, which I thought was ok.  The pork belly in this dish was actually what I was expecting my dish to taste like, but mine was still good.  I didn't really like the sizzling sinigang gravy poured over it too much though.

The food was actually good & the view was awesome, but service was hit & miss.  Some of the servers were friendly, while some kind of ignored us.  The worse one was the supervisor/manager, Ruth.  She was super rude and had her nose in the air the whole time we were there & asked for her assistance.

title: The Pyramid
reviewr_text: I ordered spaghetti carbonara. Just don't. Service was so bad it was funny. The waitress came to my table, eventually, with a flyswatter in her hand positioned to swing. Seriously. Half a dozen waiters were standing around while I was desperately looking to order something. Obviously they knew something I didn't. Don't eat here, they were hinting. Just leave.

title: Blu Bar & Grill
reviewr_text:
This restaurant is a roof top of Marco Polo Cebu. Has plenty of seafood options, Fried calamari and fish and chips are good. They also have lobster bisk, clam
Chowder. Folks with me ordered stake as well and was good. Sandwiches are served with thin cut fries or chips. Their cream
Brûlée and chocolate cake are good too. You won't be disappointed with the quality and service. For weekend nights reservation is highly recommended.

title: Nonki Japanese Restaurant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Felix A."},{"reviewer_name":"Christine C."},{"reviewer_name":"Rocky Betty Jo P."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris M."}]
reviewr_text: I've ate a-lot of japanese food across US and Asia now here in cebu for business, hungry for Japanese food eh.... Went to Ayala mall and tried the japanese there for lunch and man it was a disappointment. I cant give up went to get a SIM card and internet BAMMMMM, let do our research find me a japanese sushi bar..  found Nonki with 5 star with Yelp and 4.5 star with google... now its time to eat fresh japanese food...... verdict....  one of the BEST Chirachi bowl i ever have, fresh fresh fresh...... Service was amazing and quick. Thank you for being the fix of my japanese food hunger.

title: Birdseed
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"John L."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Maya S."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Alan S."},{"reviewer_name":"Carl V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Rustum N."},{"reviewer_name":"Cha S."},{"reviewer_name":"ravi b."},{"reviewer_name":"Paula T."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris M."},{"reviewer_name":"Pablo G."}]
reviewr_text:
Really enjoyed some different dishes, everything cooked perfectly, no burnt eggs!!   Meat really tender. I had the pesto pork chop and my friend had the beef over rice. The server was prompt and right there. 
  Great experience nice setting. A little difficult to find. It is in mall right behind The Burger King you can see from the street. 

I will return here.

title: Nonki Japanese Restaurant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Felix A."},{"reviewer_name":"Christine C."},{"reviewer_name":"Rocky Betty Jo P."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris M."}]
reviewr_text:
Love the atmosphere, food, and Japanese toilet seats in the bathroom.

The menu is large, so non-sushi eaters can definitely find other things to eat, like teriyaki or ramen.

Selections of cold bottled Japanese tea and hot tea. Tempura is awesome, and the restaurant is lovely inside.

title: Puso Bistro and Bar
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jessica S."},{"reviewer_name":"Sivilay T."},{"reviewer_name":"Cha S."},{"reviewer_name":"Ian Jude F."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."}]

title: Kusina ni Nasing
reviewr_text: I like to call this place a "neighborhood" favorite. i only heard about this place via word of mouth. They are known for their "liempo" I consider it pretty good, but other people swear by it and order a chicken and a sausage on a stick.

title: Da Won
reviewr_text: Came to this place a few months ago. The restaurant is nice, clean and decent compared to the last Korean bbq place I've been to. They have legitimate gas/charcoal grills on the tables not the portable propane gas stoves at some other places in town. We didn't do the bbq. They have a good variety of banchans (side dishes) which was a plus. We ordered deep fried chicken (it was kinda dry and tough), bibimbap and the pork dontaksu plate. Overall the food was good and prices were average.

title: Feria
reviewr_text: This is the review for weekday breakfast buffet at Radisson Blu. Breakfast buffet was not included in our hotel package so discounted price for hotel guest is P650 ($12)/person. I was surprised and impressed at the wide variety of food options including Chinese and Indian cuisine. They not only have an omelette station but a noodle bar station. My favorite was the sikwate, Puto Maya, and Fresh Mango Fruit. Servers were so nice, friendly, and helpful. I absolutely loved their funny and witty food signs: "Congee-nially yours" & "If you were a fruit, you would be a fine-apple".

title: Buffet 101

reviewr_text: i've been told this is a Manila based restaurant so expectations and anticipation has been high among the lovals. First impressions, they have a great variety of good selection, including stations that will cook pasta anf grill seafood. The ambiance is great, dare insay it konfa like that og a nice hotel. The staff ver attentive and friendly. The Japanese section was excellent in my opinion though i found their roasr beef on the dry side, other than that thus a place i will visit every so often if i want a variery.

title: Shawarma Gourmet
reviewr_text: This is the best shawarma I've had ever. I went with beef and it was great. The wrap had a slight crisp to it and the ingredients tasted great. The beef filling was moist. they also have hukas which ive been wanting to try.
