title: Big Tom's Charbroiled Burgers
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Dexter S."},{"reviewer_name":"William E."},{"reviewer_name":"Dean S."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert C."},{"reviewer_name":"Craig F."},{"reviewer_name":"Danny G."},{"reviewer_name":"Leah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Mike M."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheika G."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris M."}]
reviewr_text: Very good burgers for the Philippines.  Only a few places are a little better (Allstars is one of them).

title: La Fortuna Bakery
reviewr_text: Was here 2 years ago and I was appalled at their conditions on the buffet. I even saw little cockroaches near the dining section. I just ate there yesterday and to my surprise they moved the buffet to the second floor and was astounded on the major improvement. Food and desert was b+ on my book (really good) area was clean ( very clean) Although buffet was good the store pricing on their products where on the high side. I purchased a bunch of Argao tableya ( chocolate tablets). Pricing was 280 pesos compared to 251 in SM city. She even claimed that you can't get any lower pricing from Argao. I don't mind the cost just didn't like the dishonesty of the owner ( old lady). So again if you come to this place the buffet is around 225 pesos per person which is reasonable just beware of the prices in the store especially the tableya or products that they don't produce it will be slightly higher better to purchase from SM which has really good pricing. For dried foods Carbon would be the cheapest if you don't mind the smell

title: Neo Neo Grill House
reviewr_text:
Came here for a whole day get-together event. My sister-in-law had been in contact with Gina and Chris way before we arrived. 
The night before the event we went to check on the place. It was clean and bright. There was the small function room that we reserved and if ever there was an overflow we could extend to outside. 
I was going to get charged just to keep the reservations which I was agreeable anyhow. 
That morning I got there 15 min. before 11 am and met up with Chris. I told him what I expect of the event-- just a few drink choices, my set menu that should be served sporadically and have my chicken pieces cut into 3. I wanted food served at 12 noon in a boodle style. He told me that Juvy was the my guy for the day. 
Guests started coming in and the next thing I know  they were serving the entire order already. They were taking drink orders left and right --who are we kidding? We know that drinks cost much more than food hence the reason why I wanted only couple drink choices. They were raking drink orders like there is no tomorrow. The grilled chicken were not cut into pieces. Hubby had to send back the same chicken piece 3 times as it still looked bloody!
So when I went up to Juvy and asked if Chris (the owner) had even relayed my message he said no. 
Unbelievable!!!
I even had Juvy call Chris and told him that they did not do what I asked them to do. 
Just after lunch we already raked in P13,000! That already pretty much set the entire day's arrangement. 
Dinnertime came and I had other set of guests came I sent my food orders. I reminded the staff to please just give couple drink options--never fails! The waiters started to take orders--until I found out and took matters into my own hands. 
We had to wait for our food for another 30 min!! Yes they had few Grab orders but 30 min!!! C'mon! The drinks we had to wait longer. The Iced tea was not ready!! Food came in after 30 min( we had to stand there and made sure we got our orders) and no iced tea in sight. Guests had nothing to drink. We cancelled the iced tea because they did not want them anymore. Just asked for water instead. The other food I ordered they were just going to cook and I don't know how long more it would take. This time everyone had stopped eating since the food took so long to come in. 
The staff were doing their best but looked overwhelmed. They were not understaffed but certainly were inefficient. They could use some more training. We had to literally "help out" since I could not stand watching and waiting for our water, clear out the plates 
At the end of the day I paid close to 20K! Asked for discount and they took off the corkage charge. 
Inspite of the experience my hubby still gave them a big 1k tip because he knew they worked hard. 
The 2 star was for the convenience and the space. 
Food could have been better and service NEEDS a lot of IMPROVEMENT

title: Tim Ho Wan
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Phil S."},{"reviewer_name":"Marissa S."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Cynthia Q."},{"reviewer_name":"Tracy N."},{"reviewer_name":"Ray J."}]
reviewr_text: This place specializes in their dim sum however curiously their food tastes different than some of the classic dim sum I grew up with in China (guess it's because it's from Hong Kong). Regardless, the food is high quality and technically perfect so I can't complain. Definitely give the pork buns a go since that's what they're known for. The cookie crust outside and gooey inside make it an absolute joy to eat. Other than that, you won't go wrong ordering egg white egg rolls and pork and shrimp beancurd wraps.

title: Isla Sugbo Seafood City
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"David P."},{"reviewer_name":"Gregory C."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Danie S."},{"reviewer_name":"Erica V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Jennelle L."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Jo Anne G."},{"reviewer_name":"Laura A."},{"reviewer_name":"Rocky Betty Jo P."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco F."}]
reviewr_text: Fresh seafood but it was mostly bland. We had steamed shrimp, very fresh but not even a dash of salt so ended up no flavor. The guso as salad was ok. The tanguige as tinola( like sinigang) was good but when it was sizzling it looks so appetizing yet so bland. Disappointed. The BBQ and the grilled liempo did taste good. The calamari at first had so much breading u can't realize it was squid. 2nd order came and barely had any coating. Not consistent - again bland without the included dipping sauce. There where 6 of us and we paid Php 5,500!!! Not too impressed but place is very classy, ample parking and very attentive wait staff.

title: Cafe Laguna
reviewr_text: Good location and decent price for Filipino food. However I am giving them only 3 stars because of the slow responding servers. We had to ask for our dessert several times. There were only five tables and still took them 5 minutes to give us our check. I have been here two times and each experience has been the same.

title: Cafe Laguna
reviewr_text: Wandered around Ayala as our condo was nearby, instead of hoping into Cebu traffic, we followed our noses to this place and we weren't disappointed in the least. Group of seven seated after a thirty minute wait, it was a very busy evening for them and now we know why. We ordered beef nilaga, lechon kawale, adobong pusit, crispy crab  legs, lumpia, crispy pata, pork ribs, and eggplant salad. I honestly couldn't find fault in any of the dishes served, the nilaga soup was perfect, lechon was crispy, juicy, and absolutely delicious. The pork ribs were on the sweeter side but truly excellent. I really enjoyed the lumpia, it was well made and just perfectly cooked, an absolute delight with the sensation of crispy wholesome goodness. Overall this place blew past all my expectations for what good quality Filipino food should be and the staff handled everything well despite the really busy evening. I'd recommend this place to anyone in the area and hope to see you there! Thanks for your time.

title: The Thray
reviewr_text: The steak had the chewiness of a rubber tire. It could not be chewed enough to swallow. The Chicken was burned.  Ugh.  Waste of money.

title: Yakski Barbecue
reviewr_text:
Better than Larcian in so many ways! The food is cooked properly (not burnt), the place is cleaner and best of all you won't smell like you've been to the kitchen yourself. 

Try their chicken inasal, longganisa, and pork barbeque (large is php18.00 and small is php10.00).

They also serve local beers so it's best for those who would like to drink during or after dinner.

title: Sans Rival
reviewr_text:
This place is a welcome addition to Cebu. This place is based in dumaguete
and their signature item are "sylvanas" light brown colored coin shaped sweetness. The offer western based meals and a great dessert selection.

title: Planet Vegis
reviewr_text: This place is PERFECT!! Best adobo I've ever had in my life. Couldn't believe it isn't real meat. It tasted so homemade. Also had the tofu Sisig which again was so delicious & zesty. The service was great. The atmosphere is awesome, but most of all THE FOOD!!!

title: Zubuchon

reviewr_text: I ate three lechon while I was in Cebu and Zubuchon was a wonderful example of this roasted pig! Great seaweed salad, excellent service. Will be a definite stop the next time I'm in Cebu. Recommended!

title: Cafe Laguna
reviewr_text: This is still the gold standard when it comes to Filipino food, above average when it comes to pricing but worth it imho. The ayala location will still be #1 but its nice to know they have a restaurant in this mall and this part of town.

title: Zubuchon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Jacques I."},{"reviewer_name":"Tellie N."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Ron Z."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Lillian C."},{"reviewer_name":"Linda P."},{"reviewer_name":"Benjamin C."},{"reviewer_name":"Cris T."},{"reviewer_name":"David L."},{"reviewer_name":"Kathrine P."},{"reviewer_name":"John A."},{"reviewer_name":"Barry T."},{"reviewer_name":"Aileen B."},{"reviewer_name":"Angeli Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Ian Maren C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Geoffrey U."}]
reviewr_text:
Arrived in Cebu City, the Visaya's in search for the best Lechón.  I love my swine with that crispy cracklin' skin.  Among the locals they recommend Zubuchon and Rico's.  Since we stayed over in one of the Mactan resorts the Marina Mall had both Zubuchon and a Rico's. The lady and I ordered drinks, a cold mango smoothie and a pineapple mint smoothie.  The pineapple mint was simply divine, so freshly especially with that mint!  As for our entrees went with the Lechón pansit, sizzilin' Lechón sisig, half order of Zubuchon Lechón, and garlic rice.

Lechón Pancit: Pretty much your typical Chinese stir-fried noodles with bits of shrimp and cuts of Lechón.  It was waaaaay to salt for us! We had to down half our smoothies due to the saltiness.

Lechón Sisig: Came sizzlin' on a cast iron pan.  Very aromatic with tons of flavor. Only downside is that it was way to salty! You can't eat this without rice.

Zubuchon Lechón: Half order. Was surprised that it was just lukewarm and not all the skin was crispy! Some of it was chewy.  The flavor was alright so I had to dip it in my vinegar, soy sauce, lime, pepper mix.

Overall, the food was decent.  I was expecting to blown outta my mind.  Price was about 1200 Pesos so it wasn't bad.  Service was attentive. I like being called "Sir" everywhere I go, so empowering....haha. 

Went to Rico's next...

title: Ulli's
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Jini O."},{"reviewer_name":"Jo Anne G."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Lisa K."}]
reviewr_text: On top of Ayala Mall in the new outdoor area L4.  Modern style atmosphere.  The style is street food of Asia.  The skewers had a good flavor but the soup (causeway beef soup) we orders was a bit bland. The squid on the skewers were very tender.  The price was not bad for the size of the servings.

title: Dimsum Break
reviewr_text:
My buddy and I had a long day starting @ 5am (this coupled with me going to bed @ 2am) & catching the ferry from Dumaguete & taking the bus back from the southern tip of the island.  My buddy and I went to Dim sum Break.  This is a restaurant that serves fast food dim sum near the bus terminal in Cebu Philippines.  

It's kind of ironic because it's like a fast food dim sum that's already prepared and set out for display.  The dim sum was actually pretty good (maybe we were just hungry) & very reasonably priced.

title: Bicester Cafe
reviewr_text: Cute cafe with Filipino breakfast as one of their food options. Initially, I didn't expect a lot of the food since it's a coffee shop, but the taste exceeded my expectation. We ordered tapsilog and chorizo - the chorizo was not too sweat, which I enjoyed. Location is in a plaza so there's plenty of parking. They also take credit card!

title: Red Lizard
reviewr_text: Great customer service and decent Mercian food and that's coming from a California Native. Today I tried the shredded pork taquitos and they are amazing!

title: The Buzz Cafe
reviewr_text: Enjoyed their ice cream on a cassava cone and cool flavours to choose from.  Too bad there's no matcha flavour.  Had the avocado And salted honey before. I have yet to try their food.

title: Domings Ngohiong
reviewr_text:
This is a hometown/ word of mouth place. It is street food, but this particular place holds a lot of sentiment to the locals and they say its all about the sauce.

Ngohiong is kind of like a fried egg roll but the filling is simpler usually from part of coconut plant i believe. They also offer fried chicken which has a simple coating, you can choose from what they call "bisaya" native chicken which is smaller in size and like a free range versus the "bantris" which is bigger size and the grocery kind.

The place is only open from 730am to 130pm. So if you want to try a local favorite, come and try. Take note, the place is located in Fairlane Village., part pf a housing development.

title: Big Tom's Charbroiled Burgers
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Diego R."},{"reviewer_name":"Dexter S."},{"reviewer_name":"William E."},{"reviewer_name":"Dean S."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert C."},{"reviewer_name":"Craig F."},{"reviewer_name":"Danny G."},{"reviewer_name":"Leah M."},{"reviewer_name":"Mike M."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheika G."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris M."}]
reviewr_text: Outstanding 100% ground sirloin burgers, cooked to perfection (medium) and served with a delicious bun.  5 stars if they gave you more and better fries, but I don't think you'll find a better burger anywhere in Cebu.

title: Bucket Shrimps
reviewr_text:
Located street side with an open air concept, this is the first ever Bucket Shrimps location.  This original location is located in what used to be the owner's grandma's parking lot.  

Bucket Shrimps offers a cajun flavour which has been fine tuned to Filipino taste buds.  It is a bit sweeter and absolutely bowl licking tasty.  It can be spicy or non-spicy.  There is also garlic butter flavour. 

As the name suggests, they offer buckets of shrimps.  But it does not end there, you can get crab, mussels, bbq pork, liempo as well.  So you can get both seafood and grilled pork items.  Eat this with rice.  There may be more on the menu, but we stuck to the above.

The concept is similar to restaurants offering cajun seafood boiled in plastic bags, but instead of serving the food in boiled plastic bags (which I have to admit is rather unappetizing), this place serves them in appetizing looking buckets :).  There are no utensils provided, they give you gloves.  There are no plates provided, you just put the food straight on the plastic table cover.  You can order beer here as well.

Everything was scrumptious and the location is just so unique for North American Standards, like an old school carinderia street food, with no quality being compromised.  Kamayan style, street food style, this place is really a different and fun dining experience!!!

Note: there may be kids who may come in and ask you to buy their items. This might take away from the tranquility of eating your food in peace.

title: Butterbean Desserts and Cafe
reviewr_text:
We decided to try this place after a massage. I google mapped it and it was pretty close to where we stayed ( further down escario) so we decided to take a jeep there. The location for this place is a little bit after Golden Peak Hotel, so if your coming from there it'll be on your right. 

We order their roast beef bahn mi and master beef ribs. bahn mi meat was on the dry side and I believe there was only one flavor. They did not include cilantro but I belive they did include cucumbers. Presentation was cute. My wife ordered the beef ribs and she stated it was just ok. For dessert I ordered an ice cream sandwhich and she a piece of ube cake. Now that was good. Ice cream sandwhich seemed to be pre-made as it was kinda stiff and chewy, however the chocolate cookie was tasty. Ube cake was moist and fresh.

Service was good and the waitress was very attentive and friendly. Overall I might come back to taste their other desserts.

Tip: they accept credit cards, and if you want to jeepney back you hafta walk a little ways.

title: Everything Yummy
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Pier View P."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Jo Anne G."},{"reviewer_name":"Yna C."}]

title: Coffee Prince Cebu
reviewr_text:
Starbucks has found its match! Coffee Prince Cebu is LOVE! 

The place is just gorgeous, the service superb, and the interior is just breath-taking! 

Perfect for late night hangout when you just want to have coffee or simoly need a place to while away time!

Do drop by! You won't regret it!

title: Joed's Lutong Japon
reviewr_text: A Filipino take on japanese food. Ambiance is really quaint, staff is friendly and the food ok, a nice place to have a fun meal and enjoy the cozy ambiance. Dont order the gyoza but other stuff is pasable.

title: Kanyoen Yakiniku Restaurant
reviewr_text: My family loves it here. Some of the most authentic Japanese yakiniku you can get in Cebu. The servers are always attentive, they have great items on the menu, including imported drinks like sake and rice wine from Japan. Even with the way the tables are set up, you have the option to dine on a regular chair/table or like true Japanese restaurants where you're seated on the floor. It's easy to see why Japanese tourists love coming to dine here - it's an authentic yakiniku experience. That means they do serve Kobe beef on the menu! Unfortunately that also means, to those sensitive of the issue, smoking is allowed while dining. Other than that, the meat quality is top notch. You get what you pay for. That said, this is a little more on the pricey side. On average, according to my dad, it comes out to about P2k to P2.5k a person each time we come here. Well worth it, in my opinion.

title: Harbour City Dim Sum
reviewr_text: Ehhh? my expectation was already lower but oh my gosh! Service is just terrible, everything takes a while, it supposed to be dim sum. I guess the rice with the chicken was good (2 stars) they even serve soda warm because they don't have ice. I liked some but mostly are just ok.

title: Pueblo Mexicano
reviewr_text:
Came here for dinner last night and love their margaritas. Their salt has a spiciness to it that gives it a kick. 

The food is delish too. Had fish tacos, corn soup, and their nachos.

Love the Mexican vibe to it as well. I'll have to go back to try their dessert.

title: Red House Taiwan Shabu Shabu
reviewr_text:
If you want a place that's a little healthier then this is the place to go.

Hot pot here is great. Portions are huge and they have hello kitty fish cake which was so cute and yummy.

It's not buffet but it's filling.  I'd come back for more.

title: Banri Noodle House
reviewr_text: Been here many times already. I have to say, they are consistent in their cooking. The sushi/sashimi here is good as well as it is fresh. My favorite here is their Maguro Uni-Don (be sure to ask them if it's available though) since it sells fast. Also, their grilled hamachi kama (hamachi head) is exceptional as well, but it is also subject to availability. One good thing about this place is that they always have lunch specials everyday that you can choose from. A good sign that the restaurant is managed properly because the owners are usually present everyday. I would definitely recommend this place.

reviewr_text: Love that place. Come here with my family every so often. Pho Bo soup is very good and the cucumber drink is delicious! There is not many Vietnamese places in Cebu, but they serve decent food.

title: Iamik's Chicken & Beer
reviewr_text:
What a crazy shame... I can't believe I've let this review go so long without finishing and posting it.  

There's so much to be said but I think I can sum up my opinion about Iamik's by simply saying, this place is amazing and reasonably priced.  When I'm working in Cebu, I go two or three times a week, it seems.  Everything I've ordered is delicious, especially the nut chicken, cordon blue, and nuggets.  

My only minor complaint is that they have almost no veggies on the menu but, this is kinda common for The Philippines, from what I've seen (and I've been three times in the last year, equalling about two months). Iamik offers a cucumber salad which, we always order.  I like the vinegar that comes with it. I wish he'd throw some carrots and ranch dressing, corn on the cob, or even just sliced tomatoes in the mix.  THAT would be amazing. haha 

The music is always great, and if you go around 5 or 6 when they open, it's usually really chill.  The later it gets, though, the more it fills up with folks who are definitely there for the fun and beer.  

I'll definitely see ya there!

title: Bake & More
reviewr_text:
This place used to be called mehl and zucker but the staff said they changed the name so they could be identified as a bakery.
They are a german. bakery and I'm a fan of the apple strudel. The staff is attentive and the ambiance is first rate.

title: Lemon Grass

reviewr_text:
Probably the worst places to eat. I would only go here if I had no other choices.  

Food isn't the greatest and service is okay.  Not authentic Vietnamese or Thai. 

Had the Thai beef salad and it was pretty salty.  Also their chicken was salty too.

title: Zubuchon
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Jacques I."},{"reviewer_name":"Tellie N."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Ron Z."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert N."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Lillian C."},{"reviewer_name":"Linda P."},{"reviewer_name":"Benjamin C."},{"reviewer_name":"Cris T."},{"reviewer_name":"David L."},{"reviewer_name":"Kathrine P."},{"reviewer_name":"John A."},{"reviewer_name":"Barry T."},{"reviewer_name":"Aileen B."},{"reviewer_name":"Angeli Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Ian Maren C."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Geoffrey U."}]

title: Larsian BBQ
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Julia C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christopher C."},{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Matthew S."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"JessicaAllyn C."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Carlo L."},{"reviewer_name":"Fedd F."},{"reviewer_name":"Jeelyn D."},{"reviewer_name":"Janine D."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."},{"reviewer_name":"Emma D."}]
reviewr_text:
Amazing. 
If you like barbecue. Then come here please. You pick the meat or fish you want them to bbq for you. And then they bring it to you and eat. You can also have the fish either grilled or turned into soup. It is an experience i haven't had before and i am glad that my friend brought us here. At first the place looked skeptical because it definitely looked like a wet market. But from my experience, skeptical usually means great food. 
Place can be crowded and loud because of people barking at passerby's in an attempt to get them to eat at their stalls. There are also alot of flies because it is outdoors and the place is a bit dirty lookin. 
The great side about this place is that the food is cooked deliciously!!! It was amazing.. i kept eating and eating. I was definitely surprised on how good the food came out. 
If you are a picky eater or someone that may want to make sure what you are eating is 100% taken care of an sanitary. You might lose your mind in this place cuz i personally doubt that this place is clean, but it is probably safe to eat to some extent. Place gets crowded late at night. 
I'd come back here. A must go place for when you are in the city.

reviewr_text: If I was reviewing this just on the ambiance I would give it a 5. The staff is so friendly and if it's your birthday they will sing and dance and put a happy birthday message on the large TVs. The food was good not great. The price is great 699 php for seafood upgrade with all the basics. My sister ordered beef sukiyaki but it was plain although tasted good when dipped in one of the dipping sauces. The garlic shrimp was the best IMO.

reviewr_text:
I ordered the 1/8 kg of lechon and it was the best I've ever tasted! Hands down, without a doubt!  The meat was so delicious, juicy and tender. The skin was crunchy too! I'll definitely be returning! 

Also, don't pay with "OLD" bills. Because they won't accept it! I guess one of them I gave her was  wrinkled...odd but okay.

title: Isla Sugbo Seafood City
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"David P."},{"reviewer_name":"Gregory C."},{"reviewer_name":"Jerry H."},{"reviewer_name":"Danie S."},{"reviewer_name":"Erica V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Jennelle L."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Jo Anne G."},{"reviewer_name":"Laura A."},{"reviewer_name":"Rocky Betty Jo P."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco F."}]
reviewr_text: Recently tried this Buffet/Resto. Really cool concept of having a all you eat theme where you ask them to cool your food how you like it. The price point was well worth every penny. 4 stars due to the fact, ordered a few grams of shrimp and it was not included or was forgotten to be served.

title: The Pig & Palm
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Tricie C."},{"reviewer_name":"Jacob C."},{"reviewer_name":"Kevin G."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Daniel S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kristine S."},{"reviewer_name":"Carl I."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Dan P."},{"reviewer_name":"Cynthia Q."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text:
So I've traveled all over  lookIng for my favorites restaurants. I've accumulated about 35 that I consider the best. However this spot is #2 on my list, #1 being a steak dinner I had in Argentina.

I went with the right foodie person who appreciates this place as much as I did. I'm from California and this place has convinced me to come back to Cebu three times in 2019 along with its beautiful waters and landscape. Cebu is truly a food capital in this world.

Try a little of everything. Share each big plate with 2 people! You will be happy when you leave in a food coma.

title: Top of Cebu
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Keith A."},{"reviewer_name":"Marco R."},{"reviewer_name":"Caitlin M."},{"reviewer_name":"Sivilay T."},{"reviewer_name":"Tawny T."},{"reviewer_name":"Kartik K."}]
reviewr_text: Must-see stop, not only for the views but also for the food.  We ditched the tours and hired our own Grab driver and specifically requested him to take us here. He's a natural born Cebuano and has never eaten here. He was so impressed with their Batchoy, which is the iconic Soup for Cebu and IloIlo.  The Grilled Pork Belly was out of this world delicious!  My Tuna Belly was so-so though the locally-sourced mango salsa was delish.  Aligue Rice with crablets  (baby crabs) was different.  The price was reasonable compared to other high-end touristy places.  Highly recommend !!!!

title: Mr. Griddle
reviewr_text: I really had high hopes for this place but was disappointed.  Prices are reasonable but the food is way too oily.  My friend ordered their burger and you can see a pool of oil swimming in her plate after she picked it up.  I ordered the veggie burger and after a while didn't feel to great cus you can feel the oil kick back after eating it.  Wouldn't come back here again. Plus the griddle fries did not look appetizing and the sauce was a little too much that you forget there's fries in the plate.

title: CnT Lechon
reviewr_text: They sell lechon by the kilos...and at a fair price. We paid 500 pesos for 1 kilo of regular lechon. They can even provide you with an option to go spicy! The lechon was tasty, but the pinakbet was too salty although it was cooked with chicharon which was nicely crispy.

reviewr_text: This is the most beautiful place to go specially if you want nice beverages or foods to be served. I think this place is also a pretty thing to tell about anyone...because this is what you want...ok

reviewr_text: This place is conveniently located on whats known as "mango ave" now calles gen. maxilom. It can get pretty busy since its close to colleges and the "mango nightlife."  Its standard fast food fare and gets the job done.

title: Gibbs Hot Wings
reviewr_text: The experience could have been a 5 if not because of their waitress who seems not to be interested in getting our orders. She doesn't smile at all. Anyway, we went there for their Level 1 Chicken Wings. I was not able to resist the smell of their Carbonara which I definitely loved! We also took a liter of their Summer drink. It just took a little while for us to get our bill since we sat outside their restaurant. :)

title: Laguna Garden Cafe

title: 10 Doves Street
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Kristen T."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Hazel L."},{"reviewer_name":"ravi b."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Myles C."}]
reviewr_text:
The cakes were a burst of flavor, and the texture is to be praised.
The presentation, also great. If you want cake that truly feels unique, dove street is the place to go.

title: Tao Yuan
reviewr_text: This is our go to chinese restaurant in Cebu! Place is huge and have some private rooms too. They serve authentic chinese food! I love this place! I love the assorted seafood like  steamed live fish, crabs and shrimps. I highly recommend their noodles too!

title: Cafe Laguna
reviewr_text: Love this place. Lechon kawali was HELLA good. We also tried their adobong kangkung which was delicious. Fish wasn't salty. Food proportion was large for 2-3 people. I ordered their green and ripe mango shake and all were fresh. Can't go wrong with this place. Dessert menu had diff variations so I ordered the bibingka with cheese to go! And I'm sure I'll be able to enjoy that with my coffee in our hotel

title: Cebu Sumibi Yakiniku Tajimaya
reviewr_text: yummmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmm yummmmmmmmmmmmmm yummmmmmm so yummmy yum yum yum in my tum tum

title: Cafe Laguna
reviewr_text: Cafe Laguna at the Ayala Center in Cebu is an excellent restaurant to dine at.  They make some yummy Filipino food.  Nice ambiance and good customer service are also pluses.  Definitely, a restaurant worth trying if you want tasty Filipino cuisine.

title: Dolce
reviewr_text: Came here for coffee and dessert and it was ok.  I had the matcha cake which was still too sweet for me and that was considered the diet cake.  The coffee is pretty huge for a small size.  It's also a nice place for some IG photos.

title: Casa Verde
reviewr_text: The food was ok, the drinks were ok, staff were fine. The bathroom?? Was uber disgusting! The toilet  was gross!! There was the wet floor, cockroaches crawling all over the wall. No toilet paper. ( luckily I always bring my own TP) And after I did my business ,I was washing my hands but there was no paper towel and the hand dryer was not working. I would not go back because of that restroom situation .

title: Cebu's Original Lechon Belly
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jefferson S."},{"reviewer_name":"Abbys A."},{"reviewer_name":"Gio G."},{"reviewer_name":"Gil M."},{"reviewer_name":"Anneke D."},{"reviewer_name":"Barry T."},{"reviewer_name":"Maputing E."},{"reviewer_name":"Mike M."},{"reviewer_name":"Swan L."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."}]
reviewr_text: Definitely top 3 of Cebu's lechon places. Flavor in the spicy lechon is a must see for first timers exploring the lechon style of Cebu. Cebu's Original Lechon Belly does a kamayan style (eating with your hands) dinning. I found it to be fun being from the states, giving an alternative authentic Filipino feel, with banana leaves and all. Don't worry neat freaks, the kamayan dinning comes with gloves! Pretty cool experience for me and my traveling buddies.

title: Chikaan sa Cebu
reviewr_text: Place is decent. Food not so good kalderetang Kambing was off - it had banana. Service sucks - inattentive.

title: Larsian BBQ
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Julia C."},{"reviewer_name":"Christopher C."},{"reviewer_name":"M A G."},{"reviewer_name":"Edwin R."},{"reviewer_name":"Matthew S."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"JessicaAllyn C."},{"reviewer_name":"Kent H."},{"reviewer_name":"Joey R."},{"reviewer_name":"Carlo L."},{"reviewer_name":"Fedd F."},{"reviewer_name":"Jeelyn D."},{"reviewer_name":"Janine D."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael C."},{"reviewer_name":"Emma D."}]
reviewr_text:
Great for first time visitors but  once you've eaten here, you wouldn't want to go back!

Larsian serves grilled food and barbeque - chicken, fish, pork, longganisa, hotdog, and anything that can be grilled. The price is perfect for those looking for budget-friendly eats but the place is definitely not the cleanest. We went there and saw a cockroach flying from one stall to the other and then crawling all over the food on display! It was a good thing we already finished eating or else We would have hurled all the food we've eaten.

It's definitely something every newbie in Cebu should experience but then after there are are better and cleaner alternatives!

title: Dolce
reviewr_text:
Dolce has a good spot past Marco Polo hotel, away from busy streets. Its white interior and glass walls gives it a chic feel.

They have a good selection of cakes, cookies and other pastries which are all pretty good. I like that cakes are mostly moist. They also have bubbles teas and so far the Taro i have had before tasted quite good. I tried the green tea latte but it tasted really sweet i had to add water twice to lessen the sweetness. And thats saying something to me coz i have a sweet tooth..or teeth more like.

But despite that, since i do like the kind of place that it is and what they offer i'll still give them a decent 4 star.

title: Cafe Noriter
reviewr_text:
Before you enter Café Noriter, you are greeted with this: "We serve HAPPINESS!" A group of 4 Korean friends own Café Noriter. They came to the Philippines for a vacation, fell in love with the country and decided to stay. :) 

The number one reason why I loved this place is because of the cute interiors and homey feel. "Noriter" means "playground" in Korean and that is definitely the vibe of the place! Inside, the space is maximized by having a second floor which is divided into little hangout spots. Seriously, it's like a playhouse! There are stuffed toys everywhere, you can write on the walls, and many small rooms for you to hang with your friends! Such a happy place :3 

The café offers a simple menu of coffee and simple dessert. The best-seller is their Java Chip and Caramel Macchiato. I somehow almost always order the Mango Smoothie. BUT, the one thing you MUST EAT here is the Honey Bread. I have tried other honey bread in other Korean cafés in Manila. They do not compare to the honey bread here. It's crispy on the outside but pillowy soft on the inside with the right amount of sweetness. Yummy-ness :D Also, they offer FREE WiFi. So, the last time I was here, I stayed from 3-730PM. It was just such a chill place to be. :)

Café Noriter offers what people look for and need in a coffee shop, a cozy ambiance. It just feels great to have a place to share good laughs with friends over coffee and stuffed toys. For those who are young at heart and love coffee, this café is a good place to bring out the kid in you! :D I hope you will love it as much as I do!

title: La Buona Italian Restaurant
reviewr_text: The trick to a successful trip is in finding a delightful Italian restaurant. The owner does a nice job of working with what is locally available to create Southern and Northern dishes. The spaghetti puttanesca was nice, but I asked for extra anchovies to bring it home. The veal mushroom was a miss. Overall, a welcome retreat.

title: Larsian BBQ

reviewr_text: When you visit Cebu.. Don't forget to visit Larsian Cebu.. The best BBQ station in Cebu City..

title: 10 Doves Street
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Kristen T."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Hazel L."},{"reviewer_name":"ravi b."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Myles C."}]

title: Sachi
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Ed T."},{"reviewer_name":"Keisha R."},{"reviewer_name":"Myles C."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris S."}]
reviewr_text:
This particular location is more of a kiosk and specializes  more on the authentic takoyaki and okonomiyaki. There
seems to be a lot of buzz about tourism im Japan, but since I am unable to visit at this time I decided to visit Japanese places in Cebu. The two dishes I orderes the takoyaki and okonomiyaki i have seen on various videos of Japan and their street food so I decided to give it a try. The takoyaki was better than expected and as I watches them make it I could tell they were on the right track. I could taste the independent ingredients in harmony. The okonomiyaki also tasted good. The flavors were not overpowering but at the same time you can discover the nature of its intent.
Its a great place to stop by for a snack and imagine you are in Japan since they do claim to be authentic. I plan to try the other location for their ramen dishes. Note at current time they have 2 other actual restauranr locations one at ayala and one in mandaue.

title: Blue Elephant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"PatrickJ T."},{"reviewer_name":"Clydelle M."},{"reviewer_name":"Arnel E."},{"reviewer_name":"Dexter V."},{"reviewer_name":"Sandrine G."},{"reviewer_name":"Steve F."},{"reviewer_name":"PGreg H."},{"reviewer_name":"Dee S."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text: This place has a great view of the city. Food is not impressive. It's supposed to be a Thai restaurant but having tried better Thai food somewhere else, I think they're better off sticking to Filipino food ( most of the food is filipino anyway on the menu). Tom Yum soup was Abby salty and the Pad Thai was just okay. But if want to come and hang out then this is the place because of the location.

title: Puso Bistro and Bar
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jessica S."},{"reviewer_name":"Sivilay T."},{"reviewer_name":"Cha S."},{"reviewer_name":"Ian Jude F."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."}]

title: Laguna Garden Cafe
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Kimberly T."},{"reviewer_name":"PatrickJ T."},{"reviewer_name":"Toyo M."},{"reviewer_name":"Ken S."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Sherwin T."},{"reviewer_name":"Andrew M."},{"reviewer_name":"Monz S."}]
reviewr_text:
Laguna Garden Cafe has been here for years and quality of food has never declined.

They serve authentic filipino dishes and desserts. We always get the crispy kangkong which is deep fried water spinach for our appetizer. Yes it is definitely greasy but it is sooo good especially when paired with the dip it comes with. The entrees are well-known filipino ones such as lechon kawali, "bistek", pancit, squid (cooked according to your liking) and the like.

We also thoroughly enjoy they merienda ("snack") menu and go for their pancit palabok which is very good. One of our favorites is also the puto bumbong which is sticky rice and purple yam topped with butter, coconut shreds and if you like, sugar. They make this sooo well one piece is not enough. And lastly, we love their puto and sikwate. Mango added and its bomb!

Cafe laguna definitely knows that the way to a Pinoy's heart is to make his stomach happy!

title: Seafood Island
reviewr_text: Me & 2 other ppl decided to eat here while shopping at the mall. Sadly to say it was a horrible experience. We waited very long for our food and place was not even crowed it was empty. When our food arrived the shrimp was over cooked it taste like rubber and couldn't even pill the shell off! The whole 2 crabs that we ordered did not have any meat in the body part. They actually gave us the top part of the crab all shell no meat with the legs and they kept the the bottom part of crab witch had all the meat. I would never go back to this place again at any of it's locations!

title: Ulli's
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Brian J."},{"reviewer_name":"Jini O."},{"reviewer_name":"Jo Anne G."},{"reviewer_name":"Katrina E."},{"reviewer_name":"Lisa K."}]

title: AA BBq
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Anneke D."},{"reviewer_name":"Thu N."},{"reviewer_name":"Gee F."},{"reviewer_name":"Trina T."},{"reviewer_name":"Mike M."},{"reviewer_name":"Stephen B."}]
reviewr_text:
AA BBQ grill is always my first stop in Cebu. 

It doesn't look like much: a sort of covered outdoor canteen with plastic chairs and a view of the parking lot. At the counter, you see fish, squid and prawns wrapped in cling wrap, and you're supposed to take a tray, open the transparent plastic partition that separates you from the seafood, and tong your fish directly onto it. There are colorful menus that allow you to choose typical Filipino dishes via their photos, and the first time I saw them I assumed that they had pulled the images off the internet.

Once you order, and surrender your tray of raw seafood to the staff behind the counter, you pick your table and wait for only 5-10 minutes until the food starts streaming out of the kitchen (and no, those photos were not pulled off the internet). Squid grilled to perfection, kinilaw (seafood ceviche in vinegar), grilled vegetables mixed with glass noodles, fried fish and steamed fish and grilled prawns and more fresh vegetables! I am always amazed to see what emerges from that kitchen.

To be enjoyed with a pitcher of the day's fresh juice (for example, watermelon-guava-apple), and raw baby chili in soy sauce (or not!).

title: Hukad sa Golden Cowrie
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Jonny M."},{"reviewer_name":"Sheena Y."},{"reviewer_name":"Robert N."},{"reviewer_name":"Michael H."},{"reviewer_name":"Totong B."},{"reviewer_name":"Kelsie H."},{"reviewer_name":"Jenny C."},{"reviewer_name":"Swan L."},{"reviewer_name":"Emma D."},{"reviewer_name":"Keisha R."},{"reviewer_name":"Liza M."},{"reviewer_name":"Thomas L."},{"reviewer_name":"Nataraki T."}]
reviewr_text:
When I touched down in Cebu, all I wanted was Filipino food- it never disappoints with such a wide variety. I always leave feeling full and satisfied. Hukad is a nicer Filipino joint along the likes of Lantaw, Chikaan, or Tsiboom. They do traditional Filipino dishes at a decent price- and it's great to find this at a place like Ayala Mall, which has mostly international influences. 

If you're at Ayala, you really should check out the Filipino restaurant options such as Laguna Cafe or Chikaan in addition to Hukad.

title: Nonki Japanese Restaurant
reviewer_name: [{"reviewer_name":"Felix A."},{"reviewer_name":"Christine C."},{"reviewer_name":"Rocky Betty Jo P."},{"reviewer_name":"Chris M."}]
reviewr_text: I have eaten at their original location on A.S. Fortuna, but visit their restaurant in SM Cebu City more often. This is the best sushi in Cebu. I am always completely satisfied and always rave how their sushi is always consistently fresh, delicious, and well prepared. My favorite is the chopped tuna sashimi. It's mixed with a creamy spicy sauce, small crispy bits of fried panko and green onions.  I've always loved the U.S. style Philadelphia Roll, a combination of Philadelphia cream cheese and salmon sashimi. Well, Nonki does is well with pieces of fresh mango.  I love it! I appreciate their prices, consistency, and fast service.

title: Osaka Takoyaki
reviewr_text:
The place was cozy similar to many places in Japan, food was ok. Restaurant is located inside SM Seaside in the Mountain Wing.

The soup takoyaki tasted like hush puppies and was equally crunchy. The soup to dip them in was on the salty side, not sure if thats how its suppose to be. My brother ordered some type of Osaka Burger, the poached egg was cooked well and tasted delightful. The curry was good, flavorful, but not spicy. If you are expecting green tea, they do not serve green tea. I found that kind of odd as normally Japanese themed restaurants normally have this as a staple and is regularly available. *shrugs* I did sample their takoyaki once before and they were delicious.

Staff: When we first entered it seemed as if all staff were in a meeting or training of some sort, this continued on during our meal but they vacated the remaining tables of the restaurant and continued behind us. You can hear the trainor say, "the customer.. and when the customer.. You.." We didn't linger after the meal but had we did this can easily turn annoying. Waitress who waited on us was polite. Food was of good temperature.

We paid about 600 pesos, I wanna say, for the 3 items.  Good place to snack, but needs more variety in their menu.

title: Cafe Dessart
reviewr_text: Great cozy place to go to. They have interesting dessert options where the barrista will add some final flair upon select items which creates a instgrammable delight. They also have a machine that can create a picture that you send thru facebook messenger to on top of you cappuciono or as some same selficcino. Staff is very accommodating and attentive.

title: Kuya J's Restaurant
reviewr_text: Went to the kuya J's in the Ayala terraces on Cebu ....ordered 4 items...10 mins later waiter comes to table and says 2 items were "out of stock"...so we ordered different items....5 mins later a waitress comes to tell us that another of the items was "out of stock"....complete mismanagement or incompetence ...will never go to Kuya J's again...

reviewr_text: Had breakfast here with my husband while visiting Cebu! Very pleasant experience. Had the cappuccino, mango juice for my drinks. Clean and very trendy atmosphere. It's a bit pricey in my opinion for the locals. It's kind of hidden so you have to keep your eyes open finding this place if you're not familiar with the area. Great experience though for sure.

title: Grand Majestic
reviewr_text:
Came here on a friday at lunch time and price per head starts at 550 pesos.

(FYI) Dont confuse this place as the one in Ayala Mall as this is their Buffet restaurant located at the Old Grand Convention Center.

They have a big parking lot which they share with 2 other restaurants within the building and a hall. I havent been here in years so when i came and saw they renovated the whole place, i really came to like it. Place is clean, fresh looking and modern.

I was surprised that they were really packed for lunch I even had to wait for them to refill some of the food because it was gone in minutes. They have a decent number of food available and taste was pretty good. Some of the ones that I liked included the Squid ala pobre, Scallops, fried fish, the bread( i forgot the name) and the ube cake for dessert. 

They also have a craving station, sushi area and noodle area. I tried the udon but i tasted too much garlic on my broth I didnt like it very much. Overall it was a good experience but does have some room for improvement.
